EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed along a cold front as it moved through South Central Texas. Some of these storms produced large hail, damaging wind gusts, and heavy rain that led to flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms produced heavy rain that led to flash flooding. Multiple low water crossings were closed in northwestern Bexar County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Minor flooding slowly dwindled during early August 2019 with dry weather to start the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from July, the Big Sioux River near Bruce (gage site BRCS2) started the month at 0.53 feet above flood stage with flooding of agricultural land.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed over the central deserts during the afternoon and early evening hours on September 25th; most of them produced the standard monsoon type weather hazards including heavy rain and gusty outflow winds. However, due to a favorable combination of elevated instability and enhanced wind shear with height, one of the stronger and more organized thunderstorms managed to produce a weak tornado to the south of Phoenix during the early evening. At 1825MST a trained weather spotter located 7 miles to the west of Casa Grande reported a weak landspout tornado over an open field. The tornado quickly dissipated near State Route 84 and Midway Road, and it produced no damage. Of course, there were no injuries. Due to the very weak nature of the tornado, a tornado warning was not issued. Despite the lack of damage, the tornado was still significant and created media awareness due to its rarity.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed across the central deserts during the afternoon hours on September 25th, and although most of the storms produced heavy rain, one of the stronger and more organized thunderstorms was able to produce a weak tornado to the south of Phoenix. The tornado was based on favorable atmospheric conditions including elevated instability and enhanced wind shear with height. According to a trained weather spotter located about 7 miles west of Casa Grande, at 1825MST a weak landspout tornado developed over an open field and then rapidly dissipated near State Route 84 and Midway Road. The tornado did not produce any damage or injuries and due to the weak and short lived nature of the tornado, a tornado warning was not issued.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain was heavy at times on the 19th, and there were hit and miss thunderstorms as well. There was no severe weather, but there was plenty of lightning. During the evening, an employee at Little Rock National Airport (Pulaski County) was struck by lightning while loading a plane. He was knocked unconscious for several minutes before being treated at a local hospital.||At 600 pm CST on the 19th, it was 31 degrees at Harrison (Boone County) and 32 degrees at Mountain Home (Baxter County). Pockets of freezing rain were reported. Ice coated exposed objects, with quarter to half inch accruals from Harrison (Boone County) to Western Grove (Newton County). This led to power outages in places.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One-quarter inch of freezing rain was measured around Harrison.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A dryline moved through parts of the eastern Panhandles the afternoon of the 17th. Moisture (dewpoint temperatures) where much greater ahead of the boundary and instability was high enough for a few storms to form. There was sufficient wind shear (good clockwise turning of wind with height in this case) to allow a supercell thunderstorm to rapidly developed as it moved from southern to northern Beaver County, Oklahoma. A few miles south of the Oklahoma / Kansas, a tornado was reported with this supercell as the storm then quickly exited the Oklahoma Panhandle into southern Kansas as the tornado remained over rural, open country.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Based on radar, pictures, reports, and videos, the best estimate was a touchdown around 733 PM CDT and crossed over the OK/KS state line around 735 pm. It then continued for at least another 5 minutes into rural southern KS. No damage was reported as the tornado remained in rough, open country.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Desert Southwest remained under the influence of high pressure at the end of August, leading to excessive heat warning conditions across the region. Three fatalities (2 direct and 1 indirect) were reported by the Maricopa County Department of Public Health.

Outflow boundaries from previous days storms provided focus for thunderstorm development with a variety of severe weather on the 1st.
Outflow boundaries from previous days storms provided focus for thunderstorm development with a variety of severe weather on the 1st.

A vigorous upper level storm system followed a favorable track for Panhandles severe thunderstorms as it crossed southern Nevada and moved east into the Desert Southwest.  A frontal boundary in the area and the storm system led to significant wind shear and instability across the area.  This led to two rounds of severe weather occurred across the Texas Panhandle on the 20th.  A combination of supercell storms and small thunderstorm line segments developed and moved across the northern Texas Panhandles.  These storms produced wind damage, hail up to tennis ball size and flooding through the morning hours.  The storms helped enhanced a cold front positioned across the area causing it to shift south focusing the strongest storms across the southeastern portions of the area for the afternoon.||After a brief lull in activity, an upper level disturbance back to the west of the Panhandles coupled with daytime heating south of a cold front, moderate and an abundant moisture provided a favorable environment for additional supercell thunderstorm development across areas that previously did not see storms earlier in the morning (the southeast TX Panhandle).  With high amounts of instability during the afternoon, very large hail up to 5.5 in diameter was reported along with a tornado southwest of Wellington, TX.  Supercells eventually moved east of the Panhandles  during the evening of the 20th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Late report via social media of golf ball hail size.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong surface cold front crossed the region from west to east on January 29th. As it did so, a wave of low pressure developed along the frontal boundary over southwestern Virginia and moved northeastward to a position near Philadelphia by the evening of the 29th. This led to a rain and snow mix developing ahead of the cold front, but changing over to all snow following the frontal passage. In general, 1 to 2 inches of snow were observed across the far eastern West Virginia panhandle, with very little to no snow reported across the remainder of eastern West Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 1 to 2 inches were observed across Berkeley County, with 1.6 inches reported near Martinsburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system brought severe weather to the region on the 9th. Severe thunderstorms produced wind damage and a few tornadoes. In additional to thunderstorms producing damage, non-thunderstorm winds were very strong as the system departed, which also caused damage well behind the thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tractor shed was destroyed in Caddo Gap.

In additional to thunderstorms producing damage, non-thunderstorm winds were very strong as the system departed, which also caused damage well behind the thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tree limbs were broken and shingles were blown off roofs in Subiaco.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Warmer, more humid and unstable air began to return north across East Texas during the evening hours on April 3rd, and continued through much of the day on the 4th, well east of an area of surface low development over the Oklahoma Panhandle. This was in response to an upper level trough that began to pivot east from the Rockies and across the Plains during the early morning hours of the 4th. Upper level disturbances ejecting northeast ahead of the trough tapped into some elevated instability aloft which resulted in isolated elevated severe thunderstorms developing over portions of extreme Eastern Texas, which quickly shifted northeast into portions of Northwest Louisiana. One isolated severe thunderstorm produced large hail just northeast of Carthage, which eventually moved into the Bethany community along the TX/LA line. Additional scattered strong to severe thunderstorms developed by mid to late afternoon on the 4th, as daytime heating yielded additional instability as a warm front mixed north into East Texas and North Louisiana as the aforementioned upper level trough moved into the region. Nickel size hail was reported near the Huntington community in Eastern Angelina County before the storms weakened later that evening with the loss of instability.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A picture of hen egg size hail was posted to social media via a broadcast meteorologist.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Minor flooding slowly dwindled during early August 2019 with dry weather to start the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from July, the Big Sioux River at Sioux Falls I-90 (gage site SFLS2) crested at 0.28 feet above flood stage on August 3. Significant amounts of agricultural land were flooded north of Sioux Falls.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed along a weak cold front which pushed across southeast South Dakota during the evening of August 15.  With moderate instability of 1000-2000 J/kg and deep layer shear from 45 to 55 knots, a few stronger storms produced hail of nickel to walnut size.

A weak disturbance moving through during the overnight hours produced isolated elevated thunderstorms near the Missouri River.  With limited instability and effective shear, the storms were fairly brief and updrafts limited to marginally severe hail production.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail was from nickel to quarter size.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Minor flooding slowly dwindled during early August 2019 with dry weather to start the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from July, the Big Sioux River near Brookings (gage site BRKS2) began the month at 1.49 feet above flood stage. Significant amounts of agricultural land remained flooded. A few rural roads near the gage site were also flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Tincup fire began July 30th due to a lightning strike and burned the entire month of August.  It was located approximately 30 miles northeast of Soda Springs.  It was allowed to burn naturally and grew to 264 acres by the end of August.  It reduced heavy dead and down fuel loading that was above historic range to to past fire suppression.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Tincup fire began July 30th due to a lightning strike and burned the entire month of August.  It was located approximately 30 miles northeast of Soda Springs.  It was allowed to burn naturally and grew to 264 acres by the end of August.  It reduced heavy dead and down fuel loading that was above historic range to to past fire suppression.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A lightning strike caused the 4,889 acre Spud Fire approximately 12 miles southwest of Carey.  It burned grass and brush and threatened no structures.  It began around 5:30 PM MDT on August 1st and was controlled on August 5th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A lightning strike caused the 4,889 acre Spud Fire approximately 12 miles southwest of Carey.  It burned grass and brush and threatened no structures.  It began around 5:30 PM MDT on August 1st and was controlled on August 5th.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A National Weather Service photographed a tornado southwest of Lake Wolcott at 1:55 PM MDT on August 2nd.  It occurred over open land and no damage occurred.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Some tree damage occurred 4 miles north of Lago.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three branches were downed from a cottonwood tree 4 miles north of Lago.  The largest was 4 inches in diameter.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On August 9th a mud slide occurred one mile past the east fort of Baker Creek.   Warm Springs Road was impassable from the west of the Hot Springs in Ketchum.  3 to 5 inches of mud covered the road.

It grew to 363 acres in rugged terrain covered by grass, brush and juniper.  No structures were threatened and it was contained on August 16th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a weak disturbance acted to focus persistent lower to mid-level warm advection, persistent showers with only a rogue flash of lightning or two blossomed in the high moisture content air mass. Rainfall from 3 to 6 inches was common across a small area of southern Charles Mix and southwest Bon Homme counties, especially between 0500-0900CST.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy early morning rainfall resulted in ponding of 1 to 2 feet of water over parking lots in many areas on the west side of Wagner, including across the road from the fire station.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough was over Arizona and New Mexico with a dryline across parts of southeast New Mexico and West Texas. Very good moisture and instability were present to the east of the dryline. Good wind shear (changing wind direction and speed with height) was present as well as an area of increase in upper level winds (upper jet) which resulted in an increase in upper lift. The combination of good lift, moisture, instability, and wind shear contributed to thunderstorms with large hail, strong winds, and a tornado across parts of West Texas.

Highway 26 closed for a period of time due to the fire near mile marker 300. although strong winds drove the fire and threatened structures it was able to be contained with no damages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong storms produced heavy rainfall and flooding as a slow-moving cold front moved across southeastern Kansas and into Missouri from overnight April 30th and continued into May 1st. Rainfall accumulations of three to six inches on already very saturated soils led to widespread flooding of low water crossings and larger river systems. In one case, two kayakers perished on Bull Creek when they attempted to float the river after it had risen nearly 14 feet from the heavy rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A co-op observer reported a 24-hr rainfall accumulation of 4.77 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Multiple rounds of storms producing heavy rainfall, severe winds, hail and tornadoes moved across Southeastern Kansas and into the Missouri Ozarks from May 20th through May 22th as upper level disturbances interacted with a slow moving but powerful storm system over the Central Plains. Tornadoes occurred with each round, with the strongest and most numerous tornadoes occurring during the late afternoon and evening of the 22nd. The cumulative rainfall caused areas of flash flooding with some flooding lingering across the region. Some locations in southeastern Kansas and southwestern Missouri reported in excess of 8 inches of rainfall over the 72 hour period.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree was uprooted. Report received via social media.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous upper level low pressure system developed across southern Nevada.  Significant wind shear and instability developed as moisture was drawn north into the Panhandles setting the stage for a very long duration and higher end severe episode.  Initially, elevated supercell storms developed in the NW Texas Panhandles on the cold side of a nearly stationary frontal boundary and moved northeast into the central Oklahoma Panhandle as the first of multiple disturbances moved across the area.  Hail up to golf ball size and wind damage was reported with these storms. ||During the afternoon hours, upper level disturbances, daytime heating and the very pronounced frontal boundary stretching from near Amarillo northeast into Beaver County, Oklahoma became the main catalyst for surface based supercells, which produced very large hail up to baseball size and several tornadoes.  Two very large and long tracked tornadoes produced damage across the northeast Panhandles.  Both were rated EF-2s based on the damage, but they remained in very rural areas throughout their life-cycle.  A total of eight tornadoes occurred during this event, however three of these were landspouts that developed along an outflow produced by storms early in the event.  With the loss of daytime heating, supercells congealed into a line which produced gusty winds and hail across the eastern Texas Panhandle before finally moving east and exiting the region in the early morning hours on May 24th.
An isolated pulse thunderstorm produced damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm produced wind gusts estimated at 60 mph that knocked down tree branches in Boerne.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mesoscale convective system moved down from North Texas and produced heavy rain which led to flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms produced heavy rain with as much as 3.19 inches in just over an hour reported at a site in Helotes. This rain caused flash flooding closing 28 low water crossings in Bexar County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Convection developed over the mountains in northern Mexico and moved across the plains into Texas. This airmass was very hot and dry and one of these storms produced damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm produced wind gusts estimated at 60 mph that caused major tree damage in Del Rio.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms produced heavy rain that led to flash flooding. The right lane of I-10 near W. Woodlawn Ave. was flooded in San Antonio.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface low pressure system that moved across South Dakota and Minnesota, dragging behind it a cold front that moved into portions of northwest and central Iowa on the 30th of September. As the surface front moved through Iowa, it stalled out and effectively divided the state in half as it oriented it self from southwest to northeast across the state. While the itself stalled, it separated two distinctly different air masses with temperatures in the 50s to low 70s prevailing on the north side and 80s to around 90 prevailing to the south. Surface moisture was also divided with dew points in the 50s on the cool side and low to mid 70s on the warm side. ||Showers and storms persisted north of the front overnight of the 30th into the 1st and during much of the day of the 1st. That activity yielded little more than periods of moderate to heavy rain and sub-severe thunderstorms. Along and south of the front, thermodynamic and kinematics yielded much more vigorous storms and ultimately heavy rainfall and severe weather. SBCAPE profiles yielded 2000 to 3000+ J/kg by early to mid afternoon along with effective bulk shear around 50 to 60 kts, and persistent strong moisture flow yielding precipitable water values around 1.75 to 2.0 inches. Additionally, in the lowest 1 to 3 km, CAPE values exceed 100 J/kg and was accompanied by enhanced low level helicity due to frontal proximity. As a result, virtually all modes of severe weather were possible. In the end, the majority of reports revolved around severe hail, nearing 3 inches in diameter, and heavy rainfall in excess of 3 to 4 inches. A handful of funnel cloud and damaging wind reports were also received.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: CoCoRaHS observer recorded heavy rainfall of 3.49 inches over the past 24 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous upper level low pressure system developed across southern Nevada.  Significant wind shear and instability developed as moisture was drawn north into the Panhandles setting the stage for a very long duration and higher end severe episode.  Initially, elevated supercell storms developed in the NW Texas Panhandles on the cold side of a nearly stationary frontal boundary and moved northeast into the central Oklahoma Panhandle as the first of multiple disturbances moved across the area.  Hail up to golf ball size and wind damage was reported with these storms. ||During the afternoon hours, upper level disturbances, daytime heating and the very pronounced frontal boundary stretching from near Amarillo northeast into Beaver County, Oklahoma became the main catalyst for surface based supercells which produced very large hail up to baseball size and several tornadoes.  Most of the tornadoes remained in Texas, however one very large and long tracked tornado  crossed the Texas state line into Beaver county and eventually into Ellis County, Oklahoma. This tornado was rated an EF-2 in Beaver County based on the damage, but it remained in very rural areas throughout its life-cycle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Multiple rounds of storms producing heavy rainfall, severe winds, hail and tornadoes moved across Southeastern Kansas and into the Missouri Ozarks from May 20th through May 22th as upper level disturbances interacted with a slow moving but powerful storm system over the Central Plains. Tornadoes occurred with each round, with the strongest and most numerous tornadoes occurring during the late afternoon and evening of the 22nd. The cumulative rainfall caused areas of flash flooding with some flooding lingering across the region. Some locations in southeastern Kansas and southwestern Missouri reported in excess of 8 inches of rainfall over the 72 hour period.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The COOP observer measured a 24 hour rainfall of 4.18 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An unusually strong and cold area of high pressure surged into the northern Plains in early March.  Winds were mainly a gusty 20 to 35 mph, and when coupled with temperatures from 10 below to 20 below zero, produced a long duration of wind chills colder than 20 below zero.  Coldest wind chills were recorded between 0400-0900 on March 3, reaching -51 near Oak Lake, -48 at Volga, -47 at Flandreau and White Lake, -46 at Colton and 5 miles south of Hendricks, -45 at Windom, Worthington and near Sioux Falls, and -44 at Huron, Brookings and Madison.  March 3 was one of the coldest March days on record for the area, with the coldest or second coldest March high temperatures on record at Huron, Sioux Falls, Mitchell and Sioux City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Warmer, more humid and unstable air began to return north across East Texas and North Louisiana during the evening hours on April 3rd, and continued through much of the day on the 4th, well east of an area of surface low development over the Oklahoma Panhandle. This was in response to an upper level trough that began to pivot east from the Rockies and across the Plains during the early morning hours of the 4th. Upper level disturbances ejecting northeast ahead of the trough tapped into some elevated instability aloft which resulted in isolated elevated severe thunderstorms developing over portions of extreme Eastern Texas, which quickly shifted northeast into portions of Northwest Louisiana. Additional scattered strong to severe thunderstorms containing large hail developed farther east across portions of North Louisiana, which resulted in several instances of hail over this area before weakening late in the morning and early afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Half dollar size hail fell in the Bethany community along the Louisiana/Texas border.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A negatively tilted upper level trough moved through the Southern Plains and across the Ark-La-Tex during the morning and afternoon hours on April 6th, with deep southerly winds returning warm and moist air north into East Texas and North Louisiana near of a warm front. Very steep mid level lapse rates and strong shear were present ahead of this trough, which resulted in severe thunderstorms producing large hail and occasional damaging winds across portions of East Texas during the afternoon hours before weakening during the evening with the loss of instability and the departure of the upper trough.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ping pong ball size hail fell 5 miles north of Maydelle. Report via picture submitted through social media.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front mixed north across portions of Deep East Texas to near the Louisiana/Arkansas border during the early morning hours of April 7th, but steep lapse rates aloft and a shortwave trough which ejected northeast over Northeast Texas, North Louisiana, and Southern Arkansas enhanced the development of scattered elevated strong to severe thunderstorms across portions of North Louisiana near and north of the front. Several reports of large hail were received from these storms during the early morning hours prior to daybreak, with additional strong to severe thunderstorms developing later in the afternoon ahead of the primary upper level trough that lifted east out of Southwest New Mexico and across much of Central Texas and Louisiana. These storms eventually diminished during the late afternoon hours once the upper trough shifted east of the region into the Lower Mississippi Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail fell just outside of Sibley off of Highway 164.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong surface cold front crossed the region from west to east on January 29th. As it did so, a wave of low pressure developed along the frontal boundary over southwestern Virginia and moved northeastward to a position near Philadelphia by the evening of the 29th. This led to a rain and snow mix developing ahead of the cold front, but changing over to all snow following the frontal passage. In general, 1 to 3 inches of snow were observed across northern Virginia, with less amounts south and west.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 2 to 3 inches were observed across Fairfax County, with 3.0 inches reported near Vienna.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Potent winter storm impacted the area bringing periods of heavy snow and strong winds in the 30 to even 50 mph. Whiteout conditions along area roads and highways hindered traffic with closures on the interstates to alleviate any potential for accidents while providing crews safe access to clear drifts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sensor at Sage Creek Basin with elevation of 7850 feet measured snow water equivalent of 1.4 inches. Snow to liquid ratio used to calculate snowfall was 15 to 1 for a total of 21.5 inches of snowfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy mountain snow fell late on the evening of the 5th through the afternoon on the 7th. Snowfall amounts of mainly over a foot reported with largest of close to 3 feet in the Sierra Madre Range.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front mixed north across portions of Deep East Texas to near the Louisiana/Arkansas border during the early morning hours of April 7th, but steep lapse rates aloft and a shortwave trough which ejected northeast over Northeast Texas, North Louisiana, and Southern Arkansas enhanced the development of scattered elevated strong to severe thunderstorms across portions of North Louisiana near and north of the front. Several reports of large hail were received from these storms during the early morning hours prior to daybreak, with additional strong to severe thunderstorms developing later in the afternoon ahead of the primary upper level trough that lifted east out of Southwest New Mexico and across much of Central Texas and Louisiana. These storms eventually diminished during the late afternoon hours once the upper trough shifted east of the region into the Lower Mississippi Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dime to penny size hail fell in Bernice.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The upper trough that brought strong to severe thunderstorms across portions of East Texas, North Louisiana, and Southwest Arkansas during the early morning through the afternoon hours on April 7th exited the region east of the Mississippi Valley by the early morning hours of April 8th, allowing for cooler and drier air to begin spilling southeast into the area behind an associated cold front in wake of this trough. However, cold temperatures aloft contributed to steep lapse rates as strong forcing continued on the west side of the departing trough, which resulted in isolated to scattered showers and a few thunderstorms over portions of Southwest Arkansas and Northcentral Louisiana. One isolated severe thunderstorm developed over Eastern Miller County Arkansas, which resulted in quarter size hail falling in the Genoa community before diminishing by late afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel to quarter size hail fell at the Genoa Grocery Store in the Genoa community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level trough shifted east into Western Texas and Oklahoma during the early morning hours of April 17th, entering Central Oklahoma and Texas during the afternoon. This trough allowed the dry line to mix east across Central Texas during the afternoon ahead of an associated cold front, while southerly winds increased across the Ark-La-Tex, returning warm, moist, and unstable air back north across much of the region. Large scale forcing increased across East Texas, Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas, and North Louisiana during the evening through the early morning hours on the 17th-18th, resulting in showers and thunderstorms becoming more numerous while spreading north northeast across the area. Steep mid level lapse rates and strong wind shear had spread east across the region ahead of the trough and associated cold front, such that scattered strong to severe thunderstorms developed, resulting in damaging winds which downed trees across portions of East Texas along and south of Interstate 20. These storms weakened by daybreak and diminished from west to east on April 18th, as the cold front had pushed through the area returning cooler and drier air into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were downed near the intersection of Highway 175 and 855 in the Cuney community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong closed upper level low pressure system advanced east across Central Texas during the evening hours of April 24th, which helped to mix a warm front north into portions of Deep East Texas and Northcentral Louisiana. As a result, warm, moist, and unstable air began to build north along and south of the front, as steepening lapse rates aloft spread east along the axis of increasing large scale forcing ahead of the low. This resulted in an increase in scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms near and south of the warm front from the late evening hours of the 24th through the early morning hours of the 25th across East Texas and North Louisiana. Coupled with the strong wind shear present across the expanding warm sector, several supercell thunderstorms developed, with one supercell spawning six separate tornadoes from San Augustine Texas northeast to Eastern Union Parish Louisiana, directly impacting the cities of San Augustine Texas and Ruston Louisiana along its 150+ mile track across the NWS Shreveport County Warning Area. In fact, this supercell spawned another tornado across Northwest Morehouse and Southern Ashley County Arkansas, to complete its nearly 180 mile track before dissipating. Other isolated supercells developed near and south of the warm front which spawned tornadoes across Northern Caddo Parish and Central La Salle Parish in Northern Louisiana, with other severe thunderstorms producing damaging winds across portions of Northcentral Louisiana as well, before the storms exited the region around daybreak on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This is a continuation of the Northwest Sabine Parish tornado. This EF-1 tornado began to weaken as it entered Southeast Desoto Parish, with maximum estimated winds around 95 mph. It snapped and uprooted several trees near the Pelican community, where a tree fell on a vehicle on Highway 175 just south of the Highway 483 intersection, resulting in an injury to the female driver in the vehicle. The tornado continued its northeast movement to Highway 177 north of Parish Road 507 snapping and uprooting several more trees before finally lifting. In all, this long track tornado from Eastern Shelby County Texas through Northwest Sabine and Southeast Desoto Parishes in Northwest Louisiana remained on the ground for 32.1 miles before finally lifting.

These storms weakened by daybreak and diminished from west to east on April 18th, as the cold front had pushed through the area returning cooler and drier air into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were downed at various locations throughout Tyler and Smith County, including the intersection of West Grande Avenue and Old Noonday Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level trough shifted east into Western Texas and Oklahoma during the early morning hours of April 17th, entering Central Oklahoma and Texas during the afternoon. This trough allowed the dry line to mix east across Central Texas during the afternoon ahead of an associated cold front, while southerly winds increased across the Ark-La-Tex, returning warm, moist, and unstable air back north across much of the region. Large scale forcing increased across East Texas, Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas, and North Louisiana during the evening through the early morning hours on the 17th-18th, resulting in showers and thunderstorms becoming more numerous while spreading north northeast across the area. Steep mid level lapse rates and strong wind shear had spread east across the region ahead of the trough and associated cold front, such that scattered strong to severe thunderstorms developed, resulting in damaging winds which downed trees across portions of Shreveport, as well as in the Cloutierville community in Southern Natchitoches Parish. These storms weakened by mid-morning and diminished from west to east during the daytime hours on April 18th, as the cold front had pushed through the area returning cooler and drier air into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were blown down on East Ratcliff Street, some of which had fallen on at least a dozen homes and some vehicles near Querbes Park Golf Course. Other trees were downed on East Elmwood, and across a 4-5 block area near and west of Youree Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front mixed north across portions of Deep East Texas to near the Louisiana/Arkansas border during the early morning hours of April 7th, but steep lapse rates aloft and a shortwave trough which ejected northeast over Northeast Texas, North Louisiana, and Southern Arkansas enhanced the development of scattered elevated strong to severe thunderstorms across portions of North Louisiana near and north of the front. Several reports of large hail were received from these storms during the early morning hours prior to daybreak, with additional strong to severe thunderstorms developing later in the afternoon ahead of the primary upper level trough that lifted east out of Southwest New Mexico and across much of Central Texas and Louisiana. These storms eventually diminished during the late afternoon hours once the upper trough shifted east of the region into the Lower Mississippi Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ping pong ball size hail fell on Penal Farm Road just south of Minden.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fairly buoyant and moist air mass resided over our area. The main upper level jet was over western Lake Erie, with a trailing upper level shortwave over southern Michigan during the mid afternoon. Both of these neared western New York by late afternoon into early evening. As these upper level features interacted with subtle lake breeze boundaries, there was a rapid increase in thunderstorm coverage across the Niagara Frontier. Storms blossomed across Niagara, Orleans, and Genesee counties. These storms rapidly became severe, producing some damaging winds and large hail. These storms all appeared to be rotating, helping them to maintain their severity for an extended amount of time.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A barn was reported to have collapsed on Knowlesville Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong closed upper level low pressure system advanced east across Central Texas during the evening hours of April 24th, which helped to mix a warm front north into portions of Deep East Texas and Northcentral Louisiana. As a result, warm, moist, and unstable air began to build north along and south of the front, as steepening lapse rates aloft spread east along the axis of increasing large scale forcing ahead of the low. This resulted in an increase in scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms near and south of the warm front from the late evening hours of the 24th through the early morning hours of the 25th across East Texas and North Louisiana. Coupled with the strong wind shear present across the expanding warm sector, several supercell thunderstorms developed, with one supercell spawning six separate tornadoes from San Augustine Texas northeast to Eastern Union Parish Louisiana, directly impacting the cities of San Augustine Texas and Ruston Louisiana along its 150+ mile track across the NWS Shreveport County Warning Area. In fact, this supercell spawned another tornado across Northwest Morehouse and Southern Ashley County Arkansas, to complete its nearly 180 mile track before dissipating. Other isolated supercells developed near and south of the warm front which spawned tornadoes across Northern Caddo Parish and Central La Salle Parish in Northern Louisiana, with other severe thunderstorms producing damaging winds across portions of Northcentral Louisiana as well, before the storms exited the region around daybreak on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF-1 tornado with maximum estimated winds around 105 mph briefly touched down as it crossed Highway 508 and Raspberry Road near the Walsh community. The most significant damage was where it snapped multiple power poles and snapped/uprooted 20-30 trees on Highway 508.

CZ_NAME: CHEQUAMEGON BAY BAYFIELD TO OAK PT WI
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of storms developed the night of the 4th across the Dakotas and pushed across northern Minnesota during the morning hours of the 5th. These storms were exhibiting a downward trend as they moved along the South Shore of Lake Superior, but a few gusts to around 45 mph were observed in the Ashland area ahead of the complex and as the leading edge moved through.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The gust was measured at the Ashland Breakwater Lighthouse.

CZ_NAME: HAMLIN BEACH TO SODUS BAY NY
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The region was in a weak cyclonic mid-level flow with subtle boundaries embedded in this flow. Limited shear was available while diurnal instability increased and supported thunderstorm development by midday. Storms developed along a mid-level boundary across western Lake Ontario and moved across the lake early in the afternoon. Outflow from these storms pushed across the lake and into western New York, weakening near Olcott. This outflow proceeded farther inland, continuing to weaken, with the exception of one location in Rochester where it intersected a developing thunderstorm and produced localized but significant damage. Storms also tracked up Lake Erie, producing gusts up to near 50 mph at Dunkirk and Fredonia. These weakened by the time they reached Buffalo.

Strong low pressure brought heavy snow and near blizzard conditions to portions of southern WI. Lake enhanced snow did contribute to the overall snow totals for the counties adjacent to Lake MI. Many vehicle slide-offs and accidents occurred. Many schools and other events were cancelled.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to five inches of snow followed by freezing drizzle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Ahead of a strong cold front, storms along a prefrontal trough became severe. These storms grew quickly, with a line of convection over Canada reaching our western zones by late morning. Morning sunshine increased instability, especially along the warmer lakes. Broken lines of thunderstorms produced mainly wind damage across the area with two primary lines occurring. One of the lines was across the North Country, and the second was across the Genesee Valley. These two caused most of the damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down onto power lines near Jefferson and Eastview Terrance.

These storms grew quickly, with a line of convection over Canada reaching our western zones by late morning. Morning sunshine increased instability, especially along the warmer lakes. Broken lines of thunderstorms produced mainly wind damage across the area with two primary lines occurring. One of the lines was across the North Country, and the second was across the Genesee Valley. These two caused most of the damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down onto County Road 36.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fairly buoyant and moist air mass resided over our area. The main upper level jet was over western Lake Erie, with a trailing upper level shortwave over southern Michigan during the mid afternoon. Both of these neared western New York by late afternoon into early evening. As these upper level features interacted with subtle lake breeze boundaries, there was a rapid increase in thunderstorm coverage across the Niagara Frontier. Storms blossomed across Niagara, Orleans, and Genesee counties. These storms rapidly became severe, producing some damaging winds and large hail. These storms all appeared to be rotating, helping them to maintain their severity for an extended amount of time.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down in Bakerside State Park.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Historical flooding occurred in north central Nebraska as rivers, creeks and other streams rose due to the combination of snow, rain, and rapid snow melt on top of frozen ground. The greatest flooding occurred along the Niobrara, Keya Paha, Elkhorn and Loup Rivers; Ponca, Long Pine, Victoria and Cedar creeks; and one fatality occurred from the failure of Spencer Dam that is located on the Niobrara River. In addition to the Spencer Dam failure, several privately owned dams failed. The failure of these private dams contributed to additional overland flooding and most likely exacerbated the flooding in localized areas that led to community evacuations. The combination of weather elements on ice in the rivers led to increased runoff and rapid breakup of ice. Large ice chucks on several rivers destroyed or damaged river bridges, to include state, county and private owned bridges in several counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooding reported along the Niobrara River south of Norden.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved across central Florida producing several reports of damaging winds. A powerful storm system was moving across much of the Southeastern U.S. as high amounts of instability and moisture aided in the development of numerous thunderstorms along a cold front. Winds just off the ground were strong - in excess of 60-70 mph and the thunderstorms that developed tapped into these strong winds and brought them down to the surface. Numerous thunderstorms developed across the area, in addition to the storms associated with the cold front. These storms affected a large part of the east central Florida coast, producing strong winds along the Volusia, Brevard, St. Lucie and Martin County coasts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Weatherflow site at Melbourne Beach measured a peak wind gust of 35 knots from the southwest.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong closed upper level low pressure system advanced east across Central Texas during the evening hours of April 24th, which helped to mix a warm front north into portions of Deep East Texas and Northcentral Louisiana. As a result, warm, moist, and unstable air began to build north along and south of the front, as steepening lapse rates aloft spread east along the axis of increasing large scale forcing ahead of the low. This resulted in an increase in scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms near and south of the warm front from the late evening hours of the 24th through the early morning hours of the 25th across East Texas and North Louisiana. Coupled with the strong wind shear present across the expanding warm sector, several supercell thunderstorms developed, with one supercell spawning six separate tornadoes from San Augustine Texas northeast to Eastern Union Parish Louisiana, directly impacting the cities of San Augustine Texas and Ruston Louisiana along its 150+ mile track across the NWS Shreveport County Warning Area. In fact, this supercell spawned another tornado across Northwest Morehouse and Southern Ashley County Arkansas, to complete its nearly 180 mile track before dissipating. Other isolated supercells developed near and south of the warm front which spawned tornadoes across Northern Caddo Parish and Central La Salle Parish in Northern Louisiana, with other severe thunderstorms producing damaging winds across portions of Northcentral Louisiana as well, before the storms exited the region around daybreak on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF-1 tornado with maximum estimated winds near 110 mph touched down on Brooks Loop in the Lucky community where it snapped large branches before crossing Highway 4. The tornado continued northeast across Highway 9 where it broke power poles and snapped/uprooted approximately 20 trees before lifting.

Ahead of a strong cold front, storms along a prefrontal trough became severe. These storms grew quickly, with a line of convection over Canada reaching our western zones by late morning. Morning sunshine increased instability, especially along the warmer lakes. Broken lines of thunderstorms produced mainly wind damage across the area with two primary lines occurring. One of the lines was across the North Country, and the second was across the Genesee Valley. These two caused most of the damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was down on the 1300 block of Macedon Center Road.

CZ_NAME: SODUS BAY TO MEXICO BAY NY
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cell popped up along the lake shore in the evening. This cell was very isolated, but due to cold air aloft coming over the lake and warm late summer water temperatures, a water spout was reported from SUNY-Oswego.

A fairly buoyant and moist air mass resided over our area. The main upper level jet was over western Lake Erie, with a trailing upper level shortwave over southern Michigan during the mid afternoon. Both of these neared western New York by late afternoon into early evening. As these upper level features interacted with subtle lake breeze boundaries, there was a rapid increase in thunderstorm coverage across the Niagara Frontier. Storms blossomed across Niagara, Orleans, and Genesee counties. These storms rapidly became severe, producing some damaging winds and large hail. These storms all appeared to be rotating, helping them to maintain their severity for an extended amount of time.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter to ping pong ball sized hail was reported.

CZ_NAME: VOLUSIA-BREVARD COUNTY LINE TO SEBASTIAN INLET 0-20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved across central Florida producing several reports of damaging winds. A powerful storm system was moving across much of the Southeastern U.S. as high amounts of instability and moisture aided in the development of numerous thunderstorms along a cold front. Winds just off the ground were strong - in excess of 60-70 mph and the thunderstorms that developed tapped into these strong winds and brought them down to the surface. Numerous thunderstorms developed across the area, in addition to the storms associated with the cold front. These storms affected a large part of the east central Florida coast, producing strong winds along the Volusia, Brevard, St. Lucie and Martin County coasts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: US Air Force wind tower 1007 measured a peak wind gust of 34 knots from the south.

Winds just off the ground were strong - in excess of 60-70 mph and the thunderstorms that developed tapped into these strong winds and brought them down to the surface. Numerous thunderstorms developed across the area, in addition to the storms associated with the cold front. These storms affected a large part of the east central Florida coast, producing strong winds along the Volusia, Brevard, St. Lucie and Martin County coasts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: US Air Force wind tower 0019 measured a peak wind gust of 41 knots from the southwest.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong jet stream combined with a tight surface pressure gradient resulted in strong wind gusts across portions of the Billings forecast area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust of 70 mph was recorded in the Big Timber area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong subsidence and packed height gradients allowed for high winds to be felt across the North Snowy Range Foothills.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wyoming Department of Highway sensor at Dana Ridge or eleven miles south-southwest of Hanna measured the reported wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A 44 year old man died the afternoon of the 21st when his hang glider landed in the ocean near Devil's Slide along the San Mateo coastline. The pilot landed in the ocean and unhooked himself from the glider but could not make it to shore due to heavy surf and cliffs. He was found unconscious and not breathing and was pulled from the water. CPR was performed but the victim was not responsive and pronounced dead.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 44 year old man died the afternoon of the 21st when his hang glider landed in the ocean near Devil's Slide along the San Mateo coastline. The pilot landed in the ocean and unhooked himself from the glider but could not make it to shore due to heavy surf and cliffs. He was found unconscious and not breathing and was pulled from the water. CPR was performed but the victim was not responsive and pronounced dead https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/04/21/body-recovered-from-water-off-devils-slide/.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure aloft allowed several shortwaves to pass over northern and central California the 25th through the 28th. High winds ahead of the main upper level wave developed the 25th before a series of shortwaves brought heavy snow and rain to the Sierra Nevada and portions of Eastern California.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet MTH03 atop Mammoth Mountain measured a wind gust of 108 mph (elevation 11053 feet MSL).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure aloft allowed several shortwaves to pass over northern and central California the 25th through the 28th. High winds ahead of the main upper level wave developed the 25th before a series of shortwaves brought strong downslope winds, snow, and spillover rainfall to western Nevada.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snowfall between 6 and 14 inches was reported in the higher elevations (generally above about 7000 feet MSL) of the Carson Range. This includes ski areas such as Diamond Peak and Mount Rose. 1 mile northeast of Incline Village 7 inches of snowfall was reported at 6697 feet MSL.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong closed upper level low pressure system advanced east across Central Texas during the evening hours of April 24th, which helped to mix a warm front north into portions of Deep East Texas and Northcentral Louisiana. As a result, warm, moist, and unstable air began to build north along and south of the front, as steepening lapse rates aloft spread east along the axis of increasing large scale forcing ahead of the low. This resulted in an increase in scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms near and south of the warm front from the late evening hours of the 24th through the early morning hours of the 25th across East Texas and North Louisiana. Coupled with the strong wind shear present across the expanding warm sector, several supercell thunderstorms developed, with one supercell spawning six separate tornadoes from San Augustine Texas northeast to Eastern Union Parish Louisiana, directly impacting the cities of San Augustine Texas and Ruston Louisiana along its 150+ mile track across the NWS Shreveport County Warning Area. In fact, this supercell spawned another tornado across Northwest Morehouse and Southern Ashley County Arkansas, to complete its nearly 180 mile track before dissipating. Other isolated supercells developed near and south of the warm front which spawned tornadoes across Northern Caddo Parish and Central La Salle Parish in Northern Louisiana, with other severe thunderstorms producing damaging winds across portions of Northcentral Louisiana as well, before the storms exited the region around daybreak on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were downed along the 4300 block of Highway 485 north of Robeline.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fairly buoyant and moist air mass resided over our area. The main upper level jet was over western Lake Erie, with a trailing upper level shortwave over southern Michigan during the mid afternoon. Both of these neared western New York by late afternoon into early evening. As these upper level features interacted with subtle lake breeze boundaries, there was a rapid increase in thunderstorm coverage across the Niagara Frontier. Storms blossomed across Niagara, Orleans, and Genesee counties. These storms rapidly became severe, producing some damaging winds and large hail. These storms all appeared to be rotating, helping them to maintain their severity for an extended amount of time.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A power pole was snapped with wires down on Sunset Beach Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level shortwave moved east through the eastern Great Lakes, with a trailing weak surface trough and locally grown lake breeze and differential heating boundaries. An initial area of convection moved through the Niagara Frontier to western Lake Ontario in the morning, with additional development down the trough axis over Lake Erie and western New York. The somewhat early arrival of convection limited destabilization to some extent, but we still managed moderate instability by early to mid afternoon with a very moist environment. Low level winds were light, but somewhat better mid-level flow yielded moderate vertical wind shear.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A waterspout was reported off of Dunkirk.

As a result, warm, moist, and unstable air began to build north along and south of the front, as steepening lapse rates aloft spread east along the axis of increasing large scale forcing ahead of the low. This resulted in an increase in scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms near and south of the warm front from the late evening hours of the 24th through the early morning hours of the 25th across East Texas and North Louisiana. Coupled with the strong wind shear present across the expanding warm sector, several supercell thunderstorms developed, with one supercell spawning six separate tornadoes from San Augustine Texas northeast to Eastern Union Parish Louisiana, directly impacting the cities of San Augustine Texas and Ruston Louisiana along its 150+ mile track across the NWS Shreveport County Warning Area. In fact, this supercell spawned another tornado across Northwest Morehouse and Southern Ashley County Arkansas, to complete its nearly 180 mile track before dissipating. Other isolated supercells developed near and south of the warm front which spawned tornadoes across Northern Caddo Parish and Central La Salle Parish in Northern Louisiana, with other severe thunderstorms producing damaging winds across portions of Northcentral Louisiana as well, before the storms exited the region around daybreak on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF-2 tornado with maximum estimated winds near 125 mph touched down near the intersection of June Lane and Searcy Eden Road, where it uprooted and snapped some trees and then proceeded northeast. The tornado paralleled Searcy Eden Road to LA Highway 500, where it uprooted and snapped several trees along its path. Just before reaching LA Highway 500, the tornado strengthened to its strongest where it tore off the right half of the roof of a well-constructed home and completely destroyed its carport. The tornado weakened slightly as it crossed LA Highway 500 where it uprooted and snapped numerous trees, some of which fell on a number of mobile homes. The tornado continued northeast where it crossed Highway 84 uprooting several more trees. It then weakened further while it paralleled Zimmer Creek Road and Parish Road 285. Additional tree damage was noted across these areas, but was more widely scattered in nature. The tornado crossed LA Highway 127 just south of the community of Summerville where it uprooted a few more trees, including one that fell onto the Summerville Baptist Church before it lifted just south of LA Highway 503 east of Summerville. The church steeple was also blown off. ||One home was destroyed by the tornado and seven homes suffered minor damage. In addition, four mobile homes were destroyed and three mobile homes suffered minor damage.

An atmospheric river associated with a midlatitude cyclone brought greater than 2 inches of rainfall to the Sierra Nevada and 1 to 2 feet of snowfall above 7000 feet in the Lake Tahoe Basin and in Mono County. Rainfall totals in northeast California and the lower valleys of northern Mono County ranged from around 0.50 inches up to nearly 1.50 inches. Freezing levels derived from WFO Reno soundings rose slowly throughout the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: SNOTEL near Independence Lake reported 4.50 inches of rainfall in a 48-hour period from 1 December 0000PST to 2 December 2359PST. Station elevation of 8337 ft MSL.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An atmospheric river associated with a midlatitude cyclone brought greater than 2 inches of rainfall to the Sierra Nevada and 1 to 2 feet of snowfall above 7000 feet in the Lake Tahoe Basin and in Mono County. Rainfall totals in northeast California and the lower valleys of northern Mono County ranged from around 0.50 inches up to nearly 1.50 inches. Freezing levels derived from WFO Reno soundings rose slowly throughout the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Denten Creek RAWS MWKC1 near Blairsden reported 2.84 inches of rainfall in a 48-hour period from 1 December 0000PST to 2 December 2359PST. Station elevation of 5149 ft MSL.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The region was in a weak cyclonic mid-level flow with subtle boundaries embedded in this flow. Limited shear was available while diurnal instability increased and supported thunderstorm development by midday. Storms developed along a mid-level boundary across western Lake Ontario and moved across the lake early in the afternoon. Outflow from these storms pushed across the lake and into western New York, weakening near Olcott. This outflow proceeded farther inland, continuing to weaken, with the exception of one location in Rochester where it intersected a developing thunderstorm and produced localized but significant damage. Storms also tracked up Lake Erie, producing gusts up to near 50 mph at Dunkirk and Fredonia. These weakened by the time they reached Buffalo.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down onto Latta Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Ahead of a strong cold front, storms along a prefrontal trough became severe. These storms grew quickly, with a line of convection over Canada reaching our western zones and Lake Erie by late morning. Morning sunshine increased instability, especially along the warmer lakes. Storms moved inland as the day went on.

Many vehicle slide-off and accidents occurred. Some schools and other events were cancelled on January 23rd. A man collapsed and died while shoveling in Milwaukee.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to eight inches of snow accumulation and areas of freezing drizzle.

Two people were killed in a car accident in Sheboygan County. A few schools closed early on January 18th over far southern and southwest WI. There were 2 indirect deaths after shoveling.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to seven inches of snow accumulation with the highest amounts near Lake MI. Numerous vehicle slide-offs and accidents occurred. Two men died in their homes shortly after shoveling on January 20th.

Some schools and other events were cancelled on January 23rd. A man collapsed and died while shoveling in Milwaukee.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five to seven inches of snow accumulation and areas of freezing drizzle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fairly buoyant and moist air mass resided over our area. The main upper level jet was over western Lake Erie, with a trailing upper level shortwave over southern Michigan during the mid afternoon. Both of these neared western New York by late afternoon into early evening. As these upper level features interacted with subtle lake breeze boundaries, there was a rapid increase in thunderstorm coverage across the Niagara Frontier. Storms blossomed across Niagara, Orleans, and Genesee counties. These storms rapidly became severe, producing some damaging winds and large hail. These storms all appeared to be rotating, helping them to maintain their severity for an extended amount of time.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down and on fire from the electrical wires it took down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Historical flooding occurred in north central Nebraska as rivers, creeks and other streams rose due to the combination of snow, rain, and rapid snow melt on top of frozen ground. The greatest flooding occurred along the Niobrara, Keya Paha, Elkhorn and Loup Rivers; Ponca, Long Pine, Victoria and Cedar creeks; and one fatality occurred from the failure of Spencer Dam that is located on the Niobrara River. In addition to the Spencer Dam failure, several privately owned dams failed. The failure of these private dams contributed to additional overland flooding and most likely exacerbated the flooding in localized areas that led to community evacuations. The combination of weather elements on ice in the rivers led to increased runoff and rapid breakup of ice. Large ice chucks on several rivers destroyed or damaged river bridges, to include state, county and private owned bridges in several counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooding reported at the Hidden Paradise Resort along the Long Pine Creek.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Winter storm conditions occurred across Keith, Arthur, McPherson, Logan, Hooker and Thomas counties during the evening and overnight hours March 13th into the daytime hours on March 14th. Snowfall amounts of 1 to 3 inches combined with northwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts around 60 mph to produce blowing and drifting snow with visibilities as low as a quarter mile at times. The blizzard conditions led to numerous road and business closures to include Interstate 80 from the Wyoming stateline to east of Lincoln county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: General public located 8 miles east of Tryon reported 3 inches of snowfall. Snowfall amounts of 2 to 3 inches occurred across McPherson County during the overnight hours on March 13th into the daytime hours March 14th.  Northwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to around 60 mph produced blowing and drifting snow with visibility a quarter mile or less at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful storm system tracked across western and north central Nebraska on March 13th and 14th. High winds occurred across southwest, central and north central Nebraska. Northwest winds of 35 to 45 mph with gusts to 77 mph were observed. The highest winds began during the evening hours on March 13th and continued through the morning hours on March 14th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Thedford AWOS recorded a peak wind gust of 63 mph at 335 am CST. Wind of this magnitude occurred during the early morning hours on March 14th across Thomas County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong closed upper level low pressure system advanced east across Central Texas during the evening hours of April 24th, which helped to mix a warm front north into portions of Deep East Texas and Northcentral Louisiana. As a result, warm, moist, and unstable air began to build north along and south of the front, as steepening lapse rates aloft spread east along the axis of increasing large scale forcing ahead of the low. This resulted in an increase in scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms near and south of the warm front from the late evening hours of the 24th through the early morning hours of the 25th across East Texas and North Louisiana. Coupled with the strong wind shear present across the expanding warm sector, several supercell thunderstorms developed, with one supercell spawning six separate tornadoes from San Augustine Texas northeast to Eastern Union Parish Louisiana, directly impacting the cities of San Augustine Texas and Ruston Louisiana along its 150+ mile track across the NWS Shreveport County Warning Area. In fact, this supercell spawned another tornado across Northwest Morehouse and Southern Ashley County Arkansas, to complete its nearly 180 mile track before dissipating. Other isolated supercells developed near and south of the warm front which spawned tornadoes across Northern Caddo Parish and Central La Salle Parish in Northern Louisiana, with other severe thunderstorms producing damaging winds across portions of Northcentral Louisiana as well, before the storms exited the region around daybreak on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were blown down in the White Sulphur Springs community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The region was in a weak cyclonic mid-level flow with subtle boundaries embedded in this flow. Limited shear was available while diurnal instability increased and supported thunderstorm development by midday. Storms developed along a mid-level boundary across western Lake Ontario and moved across the lake early in the afternoon. Outflow from these storms pushed across the lake and into western New York, weakening near Olcott. This outflow proceeded farther inland, continuing to weaken, with the exception of one location in Rochester where it intersected a developing thunderstorm and produced localized but significant damage. Storms also tracked up Lake Erie, producing gusts up to near 50 mph at Dunkirk and Fredonia. These weakened by the time they reached Buffalo.

CZ_NAME: HAMLIN BEACH TO SODUS BAY NY
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Ahead of a strong cold front, storms along a prefrontal trough became severe. These storms grew quickly, with a line of convection over Canada reaching our western zones by late morning. Morning sunshine increased instability, especially along the warmer lakes. Broken lines of thunderstorms produced mainly wind damage across the area with two primary lines occurring. One of the lines was across the North Country, and the second was across the Genesee Valley. Both affected adjoining marine areas.

These storms grew quickly, with a line of convection over Canada reaching our western zones by late morning. Morning sunshine increased instability, especially along the warmer lakes. Broken lines of thunderstorms produced mainly wind damage across the area with two primary lines occurring. One of the lines was across the North Country, and the second was across the Genesee Valley. These two caused most of the damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fairly buoyant and moist air mass resided over our area. The main upper level jet was over western Lake Erie, with a trailing upper level shortwave over southern Michigan during the mid afternoon. Both of these neared western New York by late afternoon into early evening. As these upper level features interacted with subtle lake breeze boundaries, there was a rapid increase in thunderstorm coverage across the Niagara Frontier. Storms blossomed across Niagara, Orleans, and Genesee counties. These storms rapidly became severe, producing some damaging winds and large hail. These storms all appeared to be rotating, helping them to maintain their severity for an extended amount of time.
An extremely unstable environment led to widespread severe weather across Texas and Oklahoma on the 20th into the morning of the 21st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five to 7 inches of rainfall, especially eastern half of Grant county. Parts of SH-11, US-60, and SH-74 closed due to flooding.

CZ_NAME: VOLUSIA-BREVARD COUNTY LINE TO SEBASTIAN INLET 0-20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front was approaching the Florida peninsula causing winds to become south-southeast and increase throughout the day. This also led to an increase in moisture across east central Florida and showers developed over the peninsula - moving quickly to the north-northeast. As these showers moved over the Brevard County coast they produced strong wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: ASOS at the Melbourne International Airport (KMLB) measured a peak wind gust of 37 knots from the southwest.

CZ_NAME: VOLUSIA-BREVARD COUNTY LINE TO SEBASTIAN INLET 0-20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved across central Florida producing several reports of damaging winds. A powerful storm system was moving across much of the Southeastern U.S. as high amounts of instability and moisture aided in the development of numerous thunderstorms along a cold front. Winds just off the ground were strong - in excess of 60-70 mph and the thunderstorms that developed tapped into these strong winds and brought them down to the surface. Numerous thunderstorms developed across the area, in addition to the storms associated with the cold front. These storms affected a large part of the east central Florida coast, producing strong winds along the Volusia, Brevard, St. Lucie and Martin County coasts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: US Air Force wind tower 0714 measured a peak wind gust of 46 knots from the south.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong closed upper level low pressure system advanced east across Central Texas during the evening hours of April 24th, which helped to mix a warm front north into portions of Deep East Texas and Northcentral Louisiana. As a result, warm, moist, and unstable air began to build north along and south of the front, as steepening lapse rates aloft spread east along the axis of increasing large scale forcing ahead of the low. This resulted in an increase in scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms near and south of the warm front from the late evening hours of the 24th through the early morning hours of the 25th across East Texas and North Louisiana. Coupled with the strong wind shear present across the expanding warm sector, several supercell thunderstorms developed, with one supercell spawning six separate tornadoes from San Augustine Texas northeast to Eastern Union Parish Louisiana, directly impacting the cities of San Augustine Texas and Ruston Louisiana along its 150+ mile track across the NWS Shreveport County Warning Area. In fact, this supercell spawned another tornado across Northwest Morehouse and Southern Ashley County Arkansas, to complete its nearly 180 mile track before dissipating. Other isolated supercells developed near and south of the warm front which spawned tornadoes across Northern Caddo Parish and Central La Salle Parish in Northern Louisiana, with other severe thunderstorms producing damaging winds across portions of Northcentral Louisiana as well, before the storms exited the region around daybreak on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were downed at the Cypress Bend Park on Toledo Bend Reservoir. A tree had fallen on a fifth wheel trailer, with additional trees having fallen on several vehicles at the park. Fortunately, no injuries were reported. Report via pictures posted to the KALB Facebook page.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Historical flooding occurred in north central Nebraska as rivers, creeks and other streams rose due to the combination of snow, rain, and rapid snow melt on top of frozen ground. The greatest flooding occurred along the Niobrara, Keya Paha, Elkhorn and Loup Rivers; Ponca, Long Pine, Victoria and Cedar creeks; and one fatality occurred from the failure of Spencer Dam that is located on the Niobrara River. In addition to the Spencer Dam failure, several privately owned dams failed. The failure of these private dams contributed to additional overland flooding and most likely exacerbated the flooding in localized areas that led to community evacuations. The combination of weather elements on ice in the rivers led to increased runoff and rapid breakup of ice. Large ice chucks on several rivers destroyed or damaged river bridges, to include state, county and private owned bridges in several counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Water reported over several streets in O'Neill.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Winter storm conditions occurred across Keith, Arthur, McPherson, Logan, Hooker and Thomas counties during the evening and overnight hours March 13th into the daytime hours on March 14th. Snowfall amounts of 1 to 3 inches combined with northwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts around 60 mph to produce blowing and drifting snow with visibilities as low as a quarter mile at times. The blizzard conditions led to numerous road and business closures to include Interstate 80 from the Wyoming stateline to east of Lincoln county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The cooperative observer at Kingsley Dam reported 1 inch of snowfall. Snowfall amounts of 1 to 3 inches occurred across Keith County during the overnight hours on March 13th into the daytime hours March 14th.  Northwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to around 60 mph produced blowing and drifting snow with visibility a quarter mile or less at times.

CZ_NAME: NIAGARA RIVER TO HAMLIN BEACH NY
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level shortwave moved east through the eastern Great Lakes, with a trailing weak surface trough and locally grown lake breeze and differential heating boundaries. An initial area of convection moved through the Niagara Frontier to western Lake Ontario in the morning, with additional development down the trough axis over Lake Erie and western New York. The somewhat early arrival of convection limited destabilization to some extent, but we still managed moderate instability by early to mid afternoon with a very moist environment. Low level winds were light, but somewhat better mid-level flow yielded moderate vertical wind shear.

A powerful storm system produced blizzard conditions across Garden, Sheridan, Grant, and Cherry counties.  Snowfall amounts ranged from 4 to 10 inches, where northwest winds gusted to 60 mph at times leading to blizzard conditions. Snow drifts of 4 to 6 feet were common across Sheridan and western Cherry counties, with 2 to 4 feet drifts over the remainder of the area. The NDOT web page noted road closures for many area roadway during the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: General public located 4 miles north of Valentine reported 6 inches of snowfall with blizzard conditions.  Northwest winds gusting to 50 to 60 mph produced snow drifts of 2 to 4 feet across eastern Cherry County. Some area roads became closed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Southern New England was on the cool side of a frontal boundary. However, strong winds aloft and directional shear led to rotating thunderstorms in the mid-afternoon hours that moved from northern CT into central MA. Strong rotation prompted a few tornado warnings but with the circulation remained aloft presumably due to the cool surface temperatures. Large hail did fall, however.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported in Brimfield by the broadcast media.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Historical flooding occurred in north central Nebraska as rivers, creeks and other streams rose due to the combination of snow, rain, and rapid snow melt on top of frozen ground. The greatest flooding occurred along the Niobrara, Keya Paha, Elkhorn and Loup Rivers; Ponca, Long Pine, Victoria and Cedar creeks; and one fatality occurred from the failure of Spencer Dam that is located on the Niobrara River. In addition to the Spencer Dam failure, several privately owned dams failed. The failure of these private dams contributed to additional overland flooding and most likely exacerbated the flooding in localized areas that led to community evacuations. The combination of weather elements on ice in the rivers led to increased runoff and rapid breakup of ice. Large ice chucks on several rivers destroyed or damaged river bridges, to include state, county and private owned bridges in several counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Highway 11 bridge across the Niobrara River about 5 miles south of Butte is closed due to flooding. An ice jam produced large ice blocks that remained at the time of NWS storm survey.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A member of the public spotted a waterspout about 5 miles north of Ookala on the Big Island of Hawaii. The phenomenon apparently dissipated without incident; no serious injuries or property damage were reported.

An upper low approaching the Aloha State from the east brought heavy showers and isolated thunderstorms to northern and eastern sections of the Big Island of Hawaii. The downpours caused ponding on roadways, and small stream and drainage ditch flooding. No serious injuries or property damage were reported.

A mid-level shortwave moved east through the eastern Great Lakes, with a trailing weak surface trough and locally grown lake breeze and differential heating boundaries. An initial area of convection moved through the Niagara Frontier to western Lake Ontario in the morning, with additional development down the trough axis over Lake Erie and western New York. The somewhat early arrival of convection limited destabilization to some extent, but we still managed moderate instability by early to mid afternoon with a very moist environment. Low level winds were light, but somewhat better mid-level flow yielded moderate vertical wind shear.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful storm system produced blizzard conditions across Garden, Sheridan, Grant, and Cherry counties.  Snowfall amounts ranged from 4 to 10 inches, where northwest winds gusted to 60 mph at times leading to blizzard conditions. Snow drifts of 4 to 6 feet were common across Sheridan and western Cherry counties, with 2 to 4 feet drifts over the remainder of the area. The NDOT web page noted road closures for many area roadway during the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The cooperative observer located 6 miles north of Gordon reported blizzard conditions with 10 inches of snowfall. Northwest winds gusting to 50 to 60 mph produced 4 to 5 foot drifts across Sheridan County.

A very strong low pressure system moved from the lower Ohio River Valley to the Great Lakes on the 14th, pushing a cold front through late that evening. Ahead of the cold front, strong to severe thunderstorms developed, producing mainly scattered wind damage.

Continued melting of the remaining snowpack prolonged flooding concerns through the Milk River and Poplar River basins.

Coastal low pressure formed off the Carolina coast on April 2, then moved up the coast and passed offshore of Massachusetts on April 3. Strong west winds followed the passage of the low during the afternoon and night of April 3.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At 8:53 PM EST, the Automated Surface Observation System (ASOS) platform at Worcester Regional Airport reported a wind gust to 55 mph.  At 10:10 PM EST a tree fell on a house on Uxbridge Road in Mendon.

The blizzard conditions led to numerous road and business closures to include Interstate 80 from the Wyoming stateline to east of Lincoln county.

Snowfall amounts of 1 to 3 inches occurred across Thomas County during the overnight hours on March 13th into the daytime hours March 14th. Northwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to around 60 mph produced blowing and drifting snow with visibility a quarter mile or less at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough of low pressure in the Mississippi Valley tracked northeast through the Ohio Valley. A strong surface low developed in eastern Kentucky. Mixed freezing rain and sleet early on on the evening of the 19th quickly transitioned to a heavy snow overnight. This system was followed by bitter cold and sub-zero wind chills.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer southeast of Tollesboro measured an inch of snow.
