EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several areas of weakening convection moved through the area during the morning. Following this, debris clouds slowly eroded and allowed moderate instability to develop. Remnant outflow boundaries and differential heating boundaries from areas of lingering cloud cover acted as the focus for new convective development in the afternoon, mainly from the western Finger Lakes to points southeast and east of Lake Ontario. Moderate instability coupled with limited shear produced a pulse storm environment, with brief, marginal severe structures. Storms were stronger and longer lived farther east in central and eastern New York where stronger instability developed. The pulse storms produced several instances of spotty wind damage. Convection briefly trained over eastern Ontario County, with numerous reports of flooded and closed roads. A little later in the evening, a short line segment briefly developed in the western Finger Lakes, along an old remnant outflow boundary from earlier upstream convection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North Street was reported flooded and impassible between Oak and Maple Streets.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An outflow boundary from convection in North Texas moved into South Central Texas and initiated new convection. Some of these storms produced large hail and damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm produced wind gusts estimated at 75 mph. A CoCoRAHS observer reported three large Oak trees, estimated at one to two feet in diameter, snapped in half near FM 474 in Boerne.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Intensifying low pressure tracked across northwest Maine to the Gulf of Saint Lawrence during the 1st...drawing a cold front across the region producing damaging winds. The high winds across northern and eastern Maine occurred in several phases. In the first phase...onshore southerly winds with a very strong low level jet affected Downeast areas during the morning. The most significant impacts with this phase generally occurred along the Downeast coast. Wind gusts along the coast generally ranged from 55 to 65 mph...with isolated gusts up to around 70 mph. The second phase occurred with winds associated with a convective line of showers along the cold front which also crossed the region during the morning. Wind gusts with the line of showers generally ranged from 40 to 50 mph. These winds affected much of the region. The third phase of the event occurred with west-southwest gradient winds which developed during the afternoon in the wake of the cold front and persisted into the late afternoon and evening. Wind gusts with this phase of the event generally ranged from 50 to 60 mph...with the greater impacts across northern and central portions of the region.|Power outages rapidly increased during the 1st...peaking at around 62000 customers across northern and eastern Maine. Power was not completely restored in some areas until later on the 3rd. Numerous trees were snapped or toppled along with broken branches. Utility poles were also toppled or damaged in many areas. The fallen trees and utility poles blocked many roads...leading to road closures and slowing the recovery process. Heavy rains occurred with the system leading to wet soils. The wet soil and changing wind directions likely contributed to the large number of toppled trees. Damage to the roof and siding of an elementary school was reported in Surry...along the Hancock county coast. A stained glass window was blown out of a church in Caribou...in northeast Aroostook county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fairly buoyant and moist air mass resided over our area. The main upper level jet was over western Lake Erie, with a trailing upper level shortwave over southern Michigan during the mid afternoon. Both of these neared western New York by late afternoon into early evening. As these upper level features interacted with subtle lake breeze boundaries, there was a rapid increase in thunderstorm coverage across the Niagara Frontier. Storms blossomed across Niagara, Orleans, and Genesee counties. These storms rapidly became severe, producing some damaging winds and large hail. These storms all appeared to be rotating, helping them to maintain their severity for an extended amount of time.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported down at Lemon School Road and Emerson Road. The report was relayed by the NWS Binghamton office.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An atmospheric river associated with a midlatitude cyclone brought greater than 2 inches of rainfall to the Sierra Nevada and 1 to 2 feet of snowfall above 7000 feet in the Lake Tahoe Basin and in Mono County. Rainfall totals in northeast California and the lower valleys of northern Mono County ranged from around 0.50 inches up to nearly 1.50 inches. Freezing levels derived from WFO Reno soundings rose slowly throughout the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: June Mountain Ski Area reported 12 inches of snowfall in a 1-day period from the morning of the 1st through the 2nd at an elevation of 7545 feet MSL.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow-moving storm system brought a prolonged period of snow to central Illinois from the evening of January 11th through the morning of January 13th.  Snow began across the Illinois River Valley during the evening of January 11th as low pressure developed over the Texas panhandle.  As the low tracked slowly northeastward into Kentucky, light to moderate snow continued through January 12th before gradually tapering off and coming to an end by midday of the 13th.  Widespread snowfall in excess of 6 inches occurred along and north of the I-70 corridor...with as much as 12 to 16 inches falling along and southwest of a Macomb to Lincoln line.  The highest observed snowfall total was 16.0 inches just west of Jacksonville in Morgan County.  Numerous traffic accidents occurred due to snow-covered roads.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Weather observers measured 6 to 12 inches of snow across McLean County...including 11.8 inches in Chenoa, 10.6 inches 2 miles northwest of Normal, and 8.0 inches in Leroy.  Numerous traffic accidents occurred due to snow-covered roads.  The snow was heavy and wet, which made plowing of roads difficult.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Well ahead of an approaching cold front and more tied to convective enhanced shortwave, strong thunderstorms developed in clusters early morning. Warm rain processes dominated with precipitable water values closing in on 1.8 inches. Congealing storms dropped very heavy rain over north Buffalo to the Tonawandas. The rain occurred in span of 60-90 mins. As storms moved east, they progressed more quickly, so the main focus turned to strong winds once they moved into Ontario and Wayne counties and their adjoining waters.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Route 266 was closed from Sheridan Drive to Grand Island Boulevard due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hot temperatures were recorded across southeast Arizona on August 27th.  One heat-related fatality occurred in southeast Pima County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Above normal temperatures occurred in southeast Arizona on August 27th.  High temperatures included 105 degrees at the Tucson International Airport, 107 degrees at Sells and 104 degrees (record high) at Sasabe.  The Pima County Medical Examiner confirmed that heat was the primary cause of death for one adult male 11 miles south of Three Points.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several areas of weakening convection moved through the area during the morning. Following this, debris clouds slowly eroded and allowed moderate instability to develop. Remnant outflow boundaries and differential heating boundaries from areas of lingering cloud cover acted as the focus for new convective development in the afternoon, mainly from the western Finger Lakes to points southeast and east of Lake Ontario. Moderate instability coupled with limited shear produced a pulse storm environment, with brief, marginal severe structures. Storms were stronger and longer lived farther east in central and eastern New York where stronger instability developed. The pulse storms produced several instances of spotty wind damage. Convection briefly trained over eastern Ontario County, with numerous reports of flooded and closed roads. A little later in the evening, a short line segment briefly developed in the western Finger Lakes, along an old remnant outflow boundary from earlier upstream convection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple reports of trees and wires down were received.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong surface cold front crossed the region from west to east on January 29th. As it did so, a wave of low pressure developed along the frontal boundary over southwestern Virginia and moved northeastward to a position near Philadelphia by the evening of the 29th. This led to a rain and snow mix developing ahead of the cold front, but changing over to all snow following the frontal passage. In general, 1 to 3 inches of snow were observed across northern Virginia, with less amounts south and west.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 1 to 3 inches were observed across southern Fauquier County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Historical flooding occurred in north central Nebraska as rivers, creeks and other streams rose due to the combination of snow, rain, and rapid snow melt on top of frozen ground. The greatest flooding occurred along the Niobrara, Keya Paha, Elkhorn and Loup Rivers; Ponca, Long Pine, Victoria and Cedar creeks; and one fatality occurred from the failure of Spencer Dam that is located on the Niobrara River. In addition to the Spencer Dam failure, several privately owned dams failed. The failure of these private dams contributed to additional overland flooding and most likely exacerbated the flooding in localized areas that led to community evacuations. The combination of weather elements on ice in the rivers led to increased runoff and rapid breakup of ice. Large ice chucks on several rivers destroyed or damaged river bridges, to include state, county and private owned bridges in several counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Bridge approaches on highway 21C  crossing the Middle Loup River just west of Comstock have been compromised.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Historical flooding occurred in north central Nebraska as rivers, creeks and other streams rose due to the combination of snow, rain, and rapid snow melt on top of frozen ground. The greatest flooding occurred along the Niobrara, Keya Paha, Elkhorn and Loup Rivers; Ponca, Long Pine, Victoria and Cedar creeks; and one fatality occurred from the failure of Spencer Dam that is located on the Niobrara River. In addition to the Spencer Dam failure, several privately owned dams failed. The failure of these private dams contributed to additional overland flooding and most likely exacerbated the flooding in localized areas that led to community evacuations. The combination of weather elements on ice in the rivers led to increased runoff and rapid breakup of ice. Large ice chucks on several rivers destroyed or damaged river bridges, to include state, county and private owned bridges in several counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooding with water reported over the road on Highway 96 northwest of Burwell.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several areas of weakening convection moved through the area during the morning. Following this, debris clouds slowly eroded and allowed moderate instability to develop. Remnant outflow boundaries and differential heating boundaries from areas of lingering cloud cover acted as the focus for new convective development in the afternoon, mainly from the western Finger Lakes to points southeast and east of Lake Ontario. Moderate instability coupled with limited shear produced a pulse storm environment, with brief, marginal severe structures. Storms were stronger and longer lived farther east in central and eastern New York where stronger instability developed. The pulse storms produced several instances of spotty wind damage. Convection briefly trained over eastern Ontario County, with numerous reports of flooded and closed roads. A little later in the evening, a short line segment briefly developed in the western Finger Lakes, along an old remnant outflow boundary from earlier upstream convection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple reports of trees and wires down were received.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong surface cold front crossed the region from west to east on January 29th. As it did so, a wave of low pressure developed along the frontal boundary over southwestern Virginia and moved northeastward to a position near Philadelphia by the evening of the 29th. This led to a rain and snow mix developing ahead of the cold front, but changing over to all snow following the frontal passage. In general, 1 to 3 inches of snow were observed across northern Virginia, with less amounts south and west.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 1 to 3 inches were observed across Clarke County.

This was able to produce very low wind chills across eastern West Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The combination of cold temperatures and strong winds produced wind chills as low as -15 degrees.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Remnant outflow boundaries from earlier thunderstorms acted as the focus for new convective development. Moderate instability coupled with limited shear produced a pulse storm environment, with brief developed structures. Convection over the lake was short-lived in the early overnight hours of August 18th into the 19th.

Well ahead of an approaching cold front and more tied to convective enhanced shortwave, strong thunderstorms developed in clusters early morning. Warm rain processes dominated with precipitable water values closing in on 1.8 inches. Congealing storms dropped very heavy rain over north Buffalo to the Tonawandas. The rain occurred in span of 60-90 mins. As storms moved east, they progressed more quickly, so the main focus turned to strong winds once they moved into Ontario and Wayne counties and their adjoining waters.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The ramp from 190 north to 198 east was closed due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: With a surface low remaining north and northeast of the state, and a surface trough to the east; heavy downpours occurred in parts of Maui and the Big Island as deep tropical moisture made its way northward. The episode resulted in a flash flooding event in the Puna District on the Big Island. No significant injuries were reported. The cost of any damages was not available.

After a warm start to October, cooler air began to filter down into the Missouri Valley region. A day plus prior, late on the 10th and into the 11th, a cold front slid through the state, dropping temperatures a solid 10 to 15 degrees. While that itself only put the state into the 40s and upper 30s, it also allowed cooler and drier air to continue to filter in. By the evening of the 12th, the parent low pressure system to the aforementioned cold front remained rooted in northern Minnesota and deepened, yielding southwesterly winds across Iowa. Even with the southerly flow, dew points in the low to mid 20s and mostly clear skies allowed temperatures to drop below freezing statewide. The coldest temperatures, into the mid and uppe 20s, were seen in the valley areas such as the Nishnabotna. The remainder of the state did manage to drop to around 30.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain in the Puna District in windward Big Island led to the closure of Pohaku Drive at the 39th Avenue intersection. The normally dry Waipahoehoe Stream overflowed and forced the closing of the roadway in Orchidlands Estates.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper air trough developed north of the islands and brought heavy rain and flash flooding to parts of the island chain. Some properties on Oahu were damaged by the inundation, while residents on Maui saw road closures because of the precipitation. No serious injuries were reported. The cost of damages was not available.

A surface low pressure system that moved across South Dakota and Minnesota, dragging behind it a cold front that moved into portions of northwest and central Iowa on the 30th of September. As the surface front moved through Iowa, it stalled out and effectively divided the state in half as it oriented it self from southwest to northeast across the state. While the itself stalled, it separated two distinctly different air masses with temperatures in the 50s to low 70s prevailing on the north side and 80s to around 90 prevailing to the south. Surface moisture was also divided with dew points in the 50s on the cool side and low to mid 70s on the warm side. ||Showers and storms persisted north of the front overnight of the 30th into the 1st and during much of the day of the 1st. That activity yielded little more than periods of moderate to heavy rain and sub-severe thunderstorms. Along and south of the front, thermodynamic and kinematics yielded much more vigorous storms and ultimately heavy rainfall and severe weather. SBCAPE profiles yielded 2000 to 3000+ J/kg by early to mid afternoon along with effective bulk shear around 50 to 60 kts, and persistent strong moisture flow yielding precipitable water values around 1.75 to 2.0 inches. Additionally, in the lowest 1 to 3 km, CAPE values exceed 100 J/kg and was accompanied by enhanced low level helicity due to frontal proximity. As a result, virtually all modes of severe weather were possible. In the end, the majority of reports revolved around severe hail, nearing 3 inches in diameter, and heavy rainfall in excess of 3 to 4 inches. A handful of funnel cloud and damaging wind reports were also received.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: CoCoRaHS observer recorded heavy rainfall of 2.58 inches over the past 24 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep trough and associated surface low tracked into the Ohio Valley late on the 19th. A large shield of warm advection precipitation moved over the area late on the 19th into the early 20th. Most locations received between one and two inches of precipitation, leading to isolated instances of flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The river gage on the Opequon Creek at Martinsburg exceeded the 10 foot flood stage during the indicated period, leading to flooding along portions of Douglas Grove Road (County Road 9/16) and Bowers Road. Additionally, water covered the stream access point at the Van Metre Ford Pedestrian Bridge. The peak level of 10.88 feet occurred at 6:15 PM on the 20th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep trough and associated surface low tracked into the Ohio Valley late on the 19th. A large shield of warm advection precipitation moved over the area late on the 19th into the early 20th. Most locations received between one and two inches of precipitation, leading to isolated instances of flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The stream gage on the Bull Run at Manassas Park exceeded the 12 foot flood stage during the indicated period. Water covered backyards in the Yorkshire area and flooded portions of the Bull Run trail system. The peak level of 12.62 feet occurred at 10:38 AM.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strengthening low pressure system moved up the Appalachians from the afternoon hours of January 23rd through the night and into the early morning hours of January 24th. Strong winds associated with the system led to high wind gusts across the higher elevations of the Blue Ridge.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of between 58 mph and 72 mph were measured at Wintergreen Resort. There were several reports of trees down along the Blue Ridge.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A squall line developed along a pre-frontal trough over the Gulf of Mexico and moved southeast into west-central Florida during the overnight hours. A few of these storms produced marine wind gusts around the Tampa Bay.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The PORTS site at Old Port Tampa (OPTF1) measured a 35 knot thunderstorm wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Well ahead of an approaching cold front and more tied to convective enhanced shortwave, strong thunderstorms developed in clusters early morning. Warm rain processes dominated with precipitable water values closing in on 1.8 inches. Congealing storms dropped very heavy rain over north Buffalo to the Tonawandas. The rain occurred in span of 60-90 mins. As storms moved east, they progressed more quickly, so the main focus turned to strong winds once they moved into Ontario and Wayne counties and their adjoining waters.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain of 2.51 inches was reported in 60-90 minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: SE Alaska had been under a blocking ridge for three weeks. Finally, a weak front penetrated the ridge on 3/9, but no big deal weatherwise. Next, a slammer of a front moved across the Gulf and made landfall early on the morning of 3/10 and across the Panhandle during the day. First, there were strong winds everywhere. Next, it dumped snow on Hyder. There were thunderstorms on the west side of Baranof Island. No damage reported so far other than a few tree branches down, and big time snow removal at Hyder and Stewart, B.C.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: On 3/10 Salmon landing in downtown Ketchikan recorded 73 KT gusts at 1423. The tide gauge on the cruise ship docks recorded 67 KT at 1112. No damage has been reported so far.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level shortwave trough triggered thunderstorms rooted in a very moist boundary layer with precipitable water values near 2.0 inches. Some of these storms produced heavy rain that led to flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms produced heavy rain that led to flash flooding. The San Antonio Fire Department made a water rescue on the city's south side.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light rain changed over to light snow by the mid afternoon on Friday January 11. After several hours of not accumulating due to warm surface temperatures snow began to pile up shortly after sunset. While the atmosphere was certainly cold enough to produce plenty of snow it was warm enough to keep the snow to liquid ratio rather low. So, while more than 1 of liquid fell in many areas, this translated to roughly 5 to 8 inches of snow. Some of that liquid fell as rain, but the low snow to liquid ratio caused it to be a rather densely packed snow which clung to trees across the area, forming a picturesque winter wonderland. Snow continued to fall through the day on January 12, but most of the snowfall occurred through the night between January 11 and 12. Some totals in the region exceeded 12 inches, but most areas ended up with between 5 and 8 inches. At least 3 fatalities were blamed on snow covered roads and numerous other minor to moderate injuries occurred as a result of vehicle slide offs and impact.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 10 and 12 inches of snow fell across Pettis County, with most of it falling over the course of the first 12 hours. Light snow continued into the next day (January 12), but was fairly light, and only accounted for 1 to 2 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The progression, first of a strong cold front that pushed across northern Colorado and then the surge of moisture that accompanied a decaying midlevel disturbance, resulted in heavy snow across the mountains of western Colorado. Snow began over the northern and central mountains 12  to 24 hours earlier than the rest of the zones as a result of the showers associated with the cold front. Additionally, the Upper Gunnison River Valley received moderate snow during the latter half of the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell across the area which led the Colorado Department of Transportation to close Douglas Pass several times during the event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved northeastward through the Northeastern US during the early morning hours of January 9th. EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts were observed up to 8 inches across the western portions of Pendleton County, with the highest report near Cherry Grove.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved through the Great Lakes region on the morning of January 29 and departed into Canada. In the wake of this low, an arctic cold front moved through the lower Great Lakes region early on January 29, allowing for arctic high pressure to build over the midwest, setting up an extremely cold pattern for January 29 - 31. The blistering cold that entered the region resulted in temperatures on January 30 and 31 being some of the coldest recorded in five years. A strong pressure gradient set up over the region between the departing low pressure system and the incoming surface high resulting in winds to 30 - 35 mph across the region. These strong winds along with the extreme cold allowed for wind chills to drop below zero degrees by midday on January 29 and not return above zero until late on January 31. The coldest temperatures during this event were on the morning of January 30 with several locations approaching or exceeding record low temperatures in the -5F to -11F range. During these coldest temperatures, the wind chill reached -25F for several hours across the entire area with several locations reaching wind chill values of -35F to -40F for a time. Temperatures on January 30 stayed near or below zero for much of the day and dropped back below zero on the morning of January 31. Record low temperatures were set again on January 31, but the winds had subsided to 15 to 20 mph across the area, allowing for wind chills in the -15F to -20F range. Temperatures reached the upper single digits during the day on January 31 and winds subsided to light and variable, ending the extreme cold threat. Four deaths were reported in Ohio as a result of the extreme cold. All area schools closed on both January 30 and 31 due to the cold conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extremely cold weather settled over the area on January 30 and 31, bringing the coldest temperatures that the region had seen in four or five years. With winds gusting to 30 - 35 mph, wind chills across the county dropped below zero midday on January 29 and did not recover to above zero until late on January 31. Wind chills reached -25F for a period on January 30 with wind chills of -30F to -35F being noted during the late morning hours. All area schools were closed on January 30 and 31 due to the extreme cold.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Two systems moved across the Gulf bringing snow to the northern Panhandle. Cold air in place combined with 2 periods of strong lift in the low and mid levels resulted in a period of moderate to heavy snow early Mon 2/18 and again late Mon afternoon into early Tue morning, 2/19.  Storm totals were highly variable. Impact was slick roads and snow removal.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing drizzle was observed around midnight 2/18 with a thin glaze on vehicles in the valley. By morning, 2/18, 1-3 inches new snow had fallen out of the first frontal band. The second, stronger band moved into the area through the afternoon. Storm totals were highly variable ranging from near 8 inches at the Juneau Forecast Office, 7 inches West Juneau, but only 1.5 inches at the airport. Impact was slick roads with some cars in the ditch and snow removal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved through the Great Lakes region on the morning of January 29 and departed into Canada. In the wake of this low, an arctic cold front moved through the lower Great Lakes region early on January 29, allowing for arctic high pressure to build over the midwest, setting up an extremely cold pattern for January 29 - 31. The blistering cold that entered the region resulted in temperatures on January 30 and 31 being some of the coldest recorded in five years. A strong pressure gradient set up over the region between the departing low pressure system and the incoming surface high resulting in winds to 30 - 35 mph across the region. These strong winds along with the extreme cold allowed for wind chills to drop below zero degrees by midday on January 29 and not return above zero until late on January 31. The coldest temperatures during this event were on the morning of January 30 with several locations approaching or exceeding record low temperatures in the -5F to -11F range. During these coldest temperatures, the wind chill reached -25F for several hours across the entire area with several locations reaching wind chill values of -35F to -40F for a time. Temperatures on January 30 stayed near or below zero for much of the day and dropped back below zero on the morning of January 31. Record low temperatures were set again on January 31, but the winds had subsided to 15 to 20 mph across the area, allowing for wind chills in the -15F to -20F range. Temperatures reached the upper single digits during the day on January 31 and winds subsided to light and variable, ending the extreme cold threat. Four deaths were reported in Ohio as a result of the extreme cold. All area schools closed on both January 30 and 31 due to the cold conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extremely cold weather settled over the area on January 30 and 31, bringing the coldest temperatures that the region had seen in four or five years. With winds gusting to 30 - 35 mph, wind chills across the county dropped below zero midday on January 29 and did not recover to above zero until late on January 31. Wind chills reached -25F for a period on January 30 with wind chills of -30F to -35F being noted during the late morning hours. All area schools were closed on January 30 and 31 due to the extreme cold.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of storms moved through the Delta region during the evening of the 13th. These brought some damaging winds to the region. Another round of severe weather occurred during the afternoon and evening of the 14th across eastern Mississippi. These storms brought damaging winds and hail to the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down across Highway 50.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust of 63 mph was recorded at Oak Creek RAWS.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong pre frontal winds were locally enhanced by mountain waves, producing isolated high winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 58 mph were recorded at a home in Joshua Tree.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: SE Alaska had been under a blocking ridge for three weeks. Finally, a weak front penetrated the ridge on 3/9, but no big deal weatherwise. Next, a slammer of a front moved across the Gulf and made landfall early on the morning of 3/10 and across the Panhandle during the day. First, there were strong winds everywhere. Next, it dumped snow on Hyder. There were thunderstorms on the west side of Baranof Island. No damage reported so far other than a few tree branches down, and big time snow removal at Hyder and Stewart, B.C.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow measured on 3/11 at 0900 was 27.5 inches in 24 hours ending at midnight 3/11. Impact was intense snow removal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light rain changed over to light snow by the mid afternoon on Friday January 11. After several hours of not accumulating due to warm surface temperatures snow began to pile up shortly after sunset. While the atmosphere was certainly cold enough to produce plenty of snow it was warm enough to keep the snow to liquid ratio rather low. So, while more than 1 of liquid fell in many areas, this translated to roughly 5 to 8 inches of snow. Some of that liquid fell as rain, but the low snow to liquid ratio caused it to be a rather densely packed snow which clung to trees across the area, forming a picturesque winter wonderland. Snow continued to fall through the day on January 12, but most of the snowfall occurred through the night between January 11 and 12. Some totals in the region exceeded 12 inches, but most areas ended up with between 5 and 8 inches. At least 3 fatalities were blamed on snow covered roads and numerous other minor to moderate injuries occurred as a result of vehicle slide offs and impact.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 12 and 18 inches of snow fell across Cooper County, with most of it falling over the course of the first 12 hours. Light snow continued into the next day (January 12), but was fairly light, and only accounted for 1 to 2 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The progression, first of a strong cold front that pushed across northern Colorado and then the surge of moisture that accompanied a decaying midlevel disturbance, resulted in heavy snow across the mountains of western Colorado. Snow began over the northern and central mountains 12  to 24 hours earlier than the rest of the zones as a result of the showers associated with the cold front. Additionally, the Upper Gunnison River Valley received moderate snow during the latter half of the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 15 to 22 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts of 42 and 30 inches estimated at the Schofield Pass and Porphyry Creek SNOTEL sites, respectively.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: After additional heavy snow fell on an already unstable snowpack, a natural avalanche occurred southwest of Lake City and destroyed a home.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A natural avalanche released and hit a residence with 3 people inside along County Road 30, southwest of Lake City. The occupants were rescued and taken to a medical facility. The house was destroyed in the avalanche.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The phasing of two systems...a strong low pressure system that lifted across the Four Corners region and a shortwave trough that dove southward through the Great Basin...resulted in moderate to heavy snow over the mountains of eastern Utah.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 15 to 30 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts up to 37 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level system moved out the Rockies and provided the lift above a cold and moist airmass to produce widespread snow, some of it heavy.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6 inches was reported at Scott State Lake.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A long duration, elevation and upslope dependent snowfall occurred. Snowfall totals ranged from 4 to 18 inches, including 16 inches in Jericho and 4 inches in Plattsburgh.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong shear and deep layer moisture preceded a cold front across the local area, with strong wind gusts of 40-50  mph in just shower activity. Deep convection (thunderstorms) was very, very sparse due to limited surface based instability. Gusty winds from shower activity did produce some minor wind damage across parts of NE Florida, including some downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was uprooted as a line of shower moved through Hawthorne. The cost of damage was estimated for the inclusion of the event in Storm Data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system moved through the central Appalachians on the 19th and 20th. Ahead of this system, rain fell through the day on the 19th. The highest rain amounts fell across the northern mountainous counties, where 1.25 to 1.75 inches fell. This lead to minor flooding along the Tygart Valley River in Randolph County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Tygart Valley River flooded near Mill Creek. The gage on the river at Mill Creek indicated the river rose out of its banks early on the 20th. It crested at around 11.6 feet, just above its 11 foot bankfull level, before sunrise that morning and returned to its banks just after noon. This closed a section of County Route 39.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A citizen reported nickel sized hail in Mount Vernon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The phasing of two systems...a strong low pressure system that lifted across the Four Corners region and a shortwave trough that dove southward through the Great Basin...resulted in moderate to heavy snow over the mountains of eastern Utah.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An estimated 10.8 inches of snow fell at the East Willow Creek SNOTEL site. Winds gusted to almost 50 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak surface low across the Great Lakes on January 8th received upper atmospheric support (strong shortwave) during the night of the 8th and developed into a significant winter storm off the NH/ME coast by the morning of January 9th as it slowly moved into Newfoundland by January 10th.||Precipitation started as light rain, freezing rain and snow across northern NY during the evening of January 8th, changing to accumulating snow after midnight of January 9th. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A midlevel disturbance dropped into the Four Corners area and progressed east over the San Juan Mountains. Enhanced lift aloft combined with modest moisture and favorable flow produced moderate snow over the southwest San Juans.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 4 to 8 inches of snow fell across the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strengthening low pressure moved into the southern Great Lakes, crossing southern lower Michigan during the daylight hours of the 28th. This resulted in a significant winter storm for most of northern lower Michigan. Snowfall rates of 1 to 2 inches per hour were common on the 28th. Snowfall totals were mostly in the 7 to 13 inch range, and the highest amounts of around 16 inches fell near Cadillac and Lake City. Winds increased toward the tail end of the storm, resulting in increasing blowing and drifting snow. Very cold air was in place before the storm arrived, and returned as the storm exited. Wind chills of 15 to 30 below zero were common in northern lower Michigan. Wind chills were much colder in eastern upper Michigan, including -51 at Kinross, and -42 at Sault Ste Marie and Mackinac Island.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6 inches was reported on the north side of Dodge City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A high impact mini atmospheric river impacted Southern California January 14th and 15th which brought heavy rain and snow to the region. Seal Beach reported 2 inches of rain in 2 hours, which caused extensive flash flooding. Water was up to doorways outside of homes, and the Pacific Coast Highway was closed for over a day in Huntington Beach due to flooding. Rainfall rates remained below flash flood thresholds at the Holy and Cranston burn scars during this mini-AR event. Dense fog was reported in the Cajon Pass on the morning of January 16th, which resulted in a 19-car pileup and 35 patients with minor to moderate injuries. ||A larger atmospheric river moved into Southern California on January 17th, bringing heavy rain and snow to the region. Extensive flash flooding occurred due to the heavy rain. Swift water rescues occurred on the Santa Ana River in Riverside due to flooding. Rainfall rates exceeded flash flooding thresholds for the Holy fire burn scar on the 17th.||Overall, 6 to 12 inches of rain fell in the Santa Ana and San Bernardino County Mountains between January 14-17. Snowfall amounts in the mountains ranged from 4 to 12 inches above 6500 ft. Major surf and coastal flooding occurred during this event as well, which resulted in extensive damage of the Ocean Beach Pier in San Diego County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding from heavy rainfall over Holy fire scar in Trilogy parkway and Glen Eden with water going around homes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mild and moist atmospheric river event produced widespread precipitation across western Colorado with mountain snow and valley rain. Favorable upper level jet support and orographic flow resulted in significant snow over the northern and central mountains with moderate snow over the southern mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 10 to 20 inches of snow fell across the area with up to 24 inches estimated at the Molas Lake SNOTEL site.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 5 to 10 inches of snow fell on favored slopes with lesser amounts elsewhere.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A long-lived storm system responsible for floods and heavy snows across California earlier in the week moved across the county reaching the lower Mississippi valley on Saturday, January 19th and just south of New England on Sunday the 20th.  Snow began during the afternoon of the 19th and ended by early afternoon on the 20th with snow accumulations of 8 to 16+ inches. Winds developed and increased to 10 to 20 mph with gusts in excess of 30 mph late Sunday through Monday causing considerable blowing and drifting of the snow.||Very cold temperatures were experienced Saturday through Monday as well. Daytime highs -5 to +15 with overnight lows 10 to 20 below zero. Strong winds late Sunday through Monday created wind chills of 20 to 40 below zero.||The combination of all these factors created hazardous travel through Tuesday as the very cold temperatures prohibited road chemicals to work effectively.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A widespread snowfall of 12 to 18 inches occurred across Addison county, some specifics include; 19 inches in Bridport, 17 inches in Ferrisburgh and Orwell, 16 inches in Vergennes with 13 inches in Rochester.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The unsettled, progressive weather pattern continued across western Colorado during the month of March as numerous disturbances moved through. As a result of the wetter than normal conditions the state of the drought improved across the region, most notably in the Four Corners which finally eradicated the remaining extreme (D3) and severe (D2) drought conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The remaining sliver of extreme (D3) and severe (D2) drought conditions along the southern tier of the forecast zone improved to the moderate (D1) category by the end of the month. Elsewhere, the moderate drought conditions that were in place at the beginning of the month improved to the abnormally dry (D0) category.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The progression, first of a strong cold front that pushed across northern Colorado and then the surge of moisture that accompanied a decaying midlevel disturbance, resulted in heavy snow across the mountains of western Colorado. Snow began over the northern and central mountains 12  to 24 hours earlier than the rest of the zones as a result of the showers associated with the cold front. Additionally, the Upper Gunnison River Valley received moderate snow during the latter half of the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An estimated 26 inches of snow fell at the Columbine Pass SNOTEL site.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A long-lived storm system responsible for floods and heavy snows across California earlier in the week moved across the county reaching the lower Mississippi valley on Saturday, January 19th and just south of New England on Sunday the 20th.  Snow began during the afternoon of the 19th and ended by early afternoon on the 20th with snow accumulations of 8 to 16+ inches. Winds developed and increased to 10 to 20 mph with gusts in excess of 30 mph late Sunday through Monday causing considerable blowing and drifting of the snow.||Very cold temperatures were experienced Saturday through Monday as well. Daytime highs -5 to +10 with overnight lows 10 to 25 below zero. Strong winds late Sunday through Monday created wind chills of 20 to 40 below zero.||The combination of all these factors created hazardous travel through Tuesday as the very cold temperatures prohibited road chemicals to work effectively.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A widespread snowfall of 10 to 12 inches occurred across St. Lawrence county, some specifics include; 12 inches in Ogdensburg with 10 inches in Colton and Pierrepont.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific trough and associated cold front pushed into western Colorado and produced heavy snow across the mountains. Additionally, steep mid-level lapse rates and moderate instability resulted in the development of some convective snow bands which enhanced snowfall rates and accumulations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Upwards of 11 inches of snow fell west-southwest of Ridgway with locally higher amounts of 21 inches estimated at the Columbine Pass SNOTEL site.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A high impact mini atmospheric river impacted Southern California January 14th and 15th which brought heavy rain and snow to the region. Seal Beach reported 2 inches of rain in 2 hours, which caused extensive flash flooding. Water was up to doorways outside of homes, and the Pacific Coast Highway was closed for over a day in Huntington Beach due to flooding. Rainfall rates remained below flash flood thresholds at the Holy and Cranston burn scars during this mini-AR event. Dense fog was reported in the Cajon Pass on the morning of January 16th, which resulted in a 19-car pileup and 35 patients with minor to moderate injuries. ||A larger atmospheric river moved into Southern California on January 17th, bringing heavy rain and snow to the region. Extensive flash flooding occurred due to the heavy rain. Swift water rescues occurred on the Santa Ana River in Riverside due to flooding. Rainfall rates exceeded flash flooding thresholds for the Holy fire burn scar on the 17th.||Overall, 6 to 12 inches of rain fell in the Santa Ana and San Bernardino County Mountains between January 14-17. Snowfall amounts in the mountains ranged from 4 to 12 inches above 6500 ft. Major surf and coastal flooding occurred during this event as well, which resulted in extensive damage of the Ocean Beach Pier in San Diego County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Fountain Valley received 2 inches of rain in 2 hours between 2000 and 2200 PST on January 15th. An industrial roof collapsed due to water build up at approximately 2200 PST on Mt. Hermann Street.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system moved through the region with snow developing by the evening hours of January 11th. The area received several waves of heavy snowfall through the morning hours of January 13th. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mild and moist atmospheric river event produced widespread precipitation across western Colorado with mountain snow and valley rain. Favorable upper level jet support and orographic flow resulted in significant snow over the northern and central mountains with moderate snow over the southern mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 10 to 20 inches of snow fell across the area with up to 28 inches estimated at the Tower SNOTEL site.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strengthening low pressure moved into the southern Great Lakes, crossing southern lower Michigan during the daylight hours of the 28th. This resulted in a significant winter storm for most of northern lower Michigan. Snowfall rates of 1 to 2 inches per hour were common on the 28th. Snowfall totals were mostly in the 7 to 13 inch range, and the highest amounts of around 16 inches fell near Cadillac and Lake City. Winds increased toward the tail end of the storm, resulting in increasing blowing and drifting snow. Very cold air was in place before the storm arrived, and returned as the storm exited. Wind chills of 15 to 30 below zero were common in northern lower Michigan. Wind chills were much colder in eastern upper Michigan, including -51 at Kinross, and -42 at Sault Ste Marie and Mackinac Island.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave trough entered the Southern Plains during the morning hours of May 18th, and began to take on a negative tilt as it approached East Texas during the afternoon and evening. Meanwhile, an associated cold front began to shift southeast across Central Oklahoma and portions of North Texas, with the dry line having mixed east ahead of the front into Central Texas. Warm, moist, and unstable air surged north across the warm sector of Northern and Eastern Texas, Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas, and North Louisiana, with large scale forcing spreading east across this area ahead of the trough such that numerous severe thunderstorms with damaging winds developed across East Texas, and spread across much of North Louisiana during the evening and overnight hours on the 18th-19th. An isolated tornado also touched down in extreme Southern Natchitoches Parish during the early morning hours of May 19th. These storms began to move repeatedly over the same areas during the early morning hours of the 19th, with instances of flash flooding reported as well. These storms eventually diminished just prior to daybreak on the 19th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were blown down in and near Logansport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A panhandle hook low pressure system moved northeast into the Great Lakes region on December 31, deepening as it moved north of Lake Erie on the evening of the 31st. This low extended a cold front across northeast Ohio, early on the 1st. Strong winds along and behind this front downed trees and power lines across the area, prompting widespread power outages.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An automated weather station at Akron-Canton Regional Airport measured a wind gust of 53 mph. Another automated weather station at Akron Fulton Airport measured a wind gust of 48 mph. Several trees were reported downed in the northern part of the county, specifically, in Northfield and Twinsburg. Tens of thousands were without power into the morning of the 1st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked through the central Great Lakes bringing widespread rain to the area along with temperatures in the mid 40s.  This warm up was preceded by a significant snow event on the 19th and 20th which produced widespread snow amounts from 6 to 16 inches. Temperatures then dropped below freezing reaching as low as 10 degrees below zero on the 21st. This cold snap resulted in ice growth on area rivers. By the 23rd the ground had frozen and the snowpack remained dense. The rain on the 23rd into the 24th was between 0.5 and 1.5 inches, heaviest in the areas of highest snowpack. The majority of the snowpack melted, contributing 0.5-0.75 inches of runoff.  Ten river forecast points exceeded flood stage, with the Scioto River at La Rue reaching moderate flood stage.  Several roads flooded across the region, though mainly in typical low water crossing. At least two ice jams developed that resulted in flooding in evacuations; one at the Vermilion River in Vermilion, the other on the Chagrin River in Eastlake.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Eagle Creek in Findlay reached a stage of 10.9 feet midday on the 24th.  Flooding was reported but impacts were dampened due to the fact that the main stem Blanchard River was not in flood.  Flood waters inundated portions of South Blanchard Street, Brookside Drive, Fremont and Graceland Streets. The intersections of Beechmont Drive with Fairmont and Rosemont Drives also flooded.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 6 to 12 inches of snow fell across the area. Winds gusted up to 40 to 50 MPH. Colorado Highway 160 was closed for almost an hour during the storm between Hesperus and Mancos due to multiple vehicle slide-offs. Additionally, a state trooper was injured when a vehicle slid into his vehicle while he was working on a major accident.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Critical fire weather conditions were forecast for Oct 23-24 and again on October 27-28 with the eastern Pacific High allowing trough to slide into the Great Basin/Nevada areas. This caused the pressure gradients to tighten over the county warning area, which lead to additional rounds of strong northerly and easterly winds. With these winds forecast, dry conditions still in place, and fuels still being primed a Red Flag Warning was issued for most of interior northern California. Fortunately no major wildfires resulted from this but utility power lines did suffer from wind and tree damage across much of northern California. Time stamps for events are based on strongest wind gusts that occurred between Oct 23-38.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The mesonet station, Knoxville Creek, near Hidden Valley Creek reported a non-thunderstorm related wind gust up to 62 mph. Throughout Lake County, other mesonet stations reported peak wind gusts of 30-53 mph. The local utility company for Lake County reported tree and wind related damage to power lines near the Highlands, Konocti, Lucerne, Redbud, and Clear Lake areas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked through the central Great Lakes bringing widespread rain to the area along with temperatures in the mid 40s.  This warm up was preceded by a significant snow event on the 19th and 20th which produced widespread snow amounts from 6 to 16 inches. Temperatures then dropped below freezing reaching as low as 10 degrees below zero on the 21st. This cold snap resulted in ice growth on area rivers. By the 23rd the ground had frozen and the snowpack remained dense. The rain on the 23rd into the 24th was between 0.5 and 1.5 inches, heaviest in the areas of highest snowpack. The majority of the snowpack melted, contributing 0.5-0.75 inches of runoff.  Ten river forecast points exceeded flood stage, with the Scioto River at La Rue reaching moderate flood stage.  Several roads flooded across the region, though mainly in typical low water crossing. At least two ice jams developed that resulted in flooding in evacuations; one at the Vermilion River in Vermilion, the other on the Chagrin River in Eastlake.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: River ice estimated between 6 and 8 inches thick developed along the Vermilion River during a cold snap around the 21st. Rain and snowmelt on the 23rd caused the river ice to break up and jam. The jam was reported by local authorities to the NWS around 1025 PM EST. By 1144 PM evacuations were underway with swift water rescue teams. In all 11 people were rescued including children. There were at least 40 homes impacted by the ice and flood waters which measured 2 to 5 feet deep.  Reports from a resident that there were no flood waters at 10 pm, 2 feet of water starting encroaching on homes by 1030 pm, and by 11 pm had doubled to 4 feet deep.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The combination of rain, snowmelt, and river ice produced an ice jam on January 23rd. At 330 PM the river came out of banks in Eastlake. The first location to flood was Trader Jacks Riverside Grille. At approximately 1000 PM the river rose to about 15 feet with large ice chunks. The flood waters inundated West Island and Admiral Drive in Eastlake, resulting in swift water rescues. In all six families needed rescue. Erie Road was also cut off by floodwaters and ice.

CZ_NAME: FOUR CORNERS / UPPER DOLORES RIVER BASIN
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The unsettled, progressive weather pattern continued across western Colorado during the month of March as numerous disturbances moved through. As a result of the wetter than normal conditions the state of the drought improved across the region, most notably in the Four Corners which finally eradicated the remaining extreme (D3) and severe (D2) drought conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The severe (D2) drought conditions along the southern tier of the forecast zone improved to the moderate (D1) category by the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first of two lines of thunderstorms arrived in northwest Alabama during the early afternoon hours producing a couple reports of wind damage.  The second and more intense line of thunderstorms arrived during the early evening hours, and produced several reports of wind damage, one tornado in Limestone County, and flash flooding which killed one person.||After 2-3 inches of rain in less than two hours, a flash flood occurred along Anderson creek in Lauderdale County, sweeping three cars off of two roads affected. One person was killed, while at least two others were rescued.||A storm survey determined that an EF-0 tornado occurred southwest of Athens.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado touched down approximately 0.3 miles west of the intersection of Zelner Road and Ripley Road in southern Limestone County. Upon touchdown the tornado produced tree damage. Tracking to the northeast, the tornado produced damage to a metal barn roof along Bell Road, snapped a tree at the base, and uplifted an attached roof of a porch on a small home. Farther to the northeast, the tornado produced mainly roof and window damage in a mobile home park along the west side of Blackburn Road. On Ham Road, more extensive damage was found to a mobile home, which was pushed back about six feet, detaching it from an awning and cement parking pad. This mobile home was anchored to concrete pads that were sitting on gravel, but the mobile home was left largely intact. The tornado continued to snap trees across Evans Road and Reid Road. As the tornado approached U.S. Highway 72, it produced significant damage to a metal-sided outbuilding, while producing mainly roof and siding damage to a couple of metal building systems on the south side of U.S. Highway 72. The tornado produced damage to a couple of metal signs at a gas station located along the north side of U.S. Highway 72 at the intersection of W. Washington Street. Along W. Washington Street, tree damage continued, with some trees uprooted, including a tree that fell on a vehicle. At the intersection of W. Glenn Valley Drive and W. Washington Road, a large tree branch fell, partly on a house. The tornado appeared to lift near this point, with some minor tree damage farther to the northeast in western portions of Athens.

One person was killed, while at least two others were rescued.||A storm survey determined that an EF-0 tornado occurred southwest of Athens.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong arctic high pressure built into the Yukon Territory on 2/21 to 2/23 causing Taku winds again for Downtown Juneau and Douglas. One gust was 87 mph at the AJ Dock. Miraculously, no damage was reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts were very strong with this Taku wind event on the night of 2/22 and the morning of 2/23. AJ dock had a gust 87 mph at 1704 on 2/22. Numerous gusts were in the 70s. No damage was reported. LLWS was a problem at the Airport, but no accidents.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first of two lines of thunderstorms arrived in northwest Alabama during the early afternoon hours producing a couple reports of wind damage.  The second and more intense line of thunderstorms arrived during the early evening hours, and produced several reports of wind damage, one tornado in Limestone County, and flash flooding which killed one person.||After 2-3 inches of rain in less than two hours, a flash flood occurred along Anderson creek in Lauderdale County, sweeping three cars off of two roads affected. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Areas of frost occurred during the early morning hours as temperatures dipped into the lower and middle 30's. Agricultural experts reported no significant effects on protected crops or fruit trees. The only reported damage was some minor cold injury that affected random asparagus spears, but there was nothing widespread.  A ridge of high pressure extending from the Gulf coast northward to the lower Ohio and mid Mississippi Valleys provided clear skies and light winds. These conditions were conducive for frost.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Critical fire weather conditions were forecast for Oct 23-24 and again on October 27-28 with the eastern Pacific High allowing trough to slide into the Great Basin/Nevada areas. This caused the pressure gradients to tighten over the county warning area, which lead to additional rounds of strong northerly and easterly winds. With these winds forecast, dry conditions still in place, and fuels still being primed a Red Flag Warning was issued for most of interior northern California. Fortunately no major wildfires resulted from this but utility power lines did suffer from wind and tree damage across much of northern California. Time stamps for events are based on strongest wind gusts that occurred between Oct 23-38.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The mesonet station, Jarbo Gap, near Big Bend reported a non-thunderstorm related wind gust up to 70 mph, with strong wind gusts of 50-70 mph lasting through 11AM PST.  The local utility company for Lake County reported tree and wind related damage to power lines near the Oro Fino and Wyandotte areas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front approaching from the west in conjunction with a short wave trough aloft tapped into a fairly unstable air mass over Central Appalachia on the afternoon of the 17th. Storms fired up quickly that afternoon over West Virginia and continuing into the evening, with many impressive storms resulting in damaging wind gusts and hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees blew over onto power lines near Branchland and caused numerous power outages in the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: In a very unstable atmosphere, thunderstorms developed in the middle Ohio River Valley on the afternoon of the 23rd. These storms quickly grew to severe levels, producing very large hail and sporadic wind damage as they moved across central West Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Many cars were dented by the hail, but no significant building damage occurred.

Many rural roads near the river were inundated, with continued flooding of significant amounts of agricultural land. Minor flooding continued at the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Following several days of showers and thunderstorms, a final upper level disturbance crossed on the 31st bringing another round of showers and storms. A couple of the storms produced hail. The ground was wet enough that the additional 0.5 to 1.0 inch of rain that fell on the 31st caused flash flooding in the late morning and early afternoon. This led to areal flooding during the late afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several roads were closed due to flooding. State Route 356 was closed due to flooding along Raccoon Creek and Onion Creek. Elk Fork flooded, closing a section of State Route 677. Flooding along Wheelabout Creek closed a portion of State Route 278.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Surface low pressure and remnants of a frontal boundary passed through the region late on the 4th and the early morning hours of the 5th. Showers streamed through from the southwest to the northeast along an approaching wave into an atmosphere with enhanced moisture. Saturated soils from the previous day's showers and storms combined with the showers and storms to produce flash flooding across portions of Virginia and West Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High water was reported on Elk River Road near Tickelwash Avenue and at 5064 Elk River Road near Smith Avenue. A mudslide was also reported on the southbound lane of Elk River Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very slow moving cold front sunk in from the north during the afternoon of the 26th. At the same time, a mid/upper level disturbance was crossing. The combination led to severe thunderstorms across the middle Ohio River Valley and central Appalachians.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A power line was blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Areas of frost occurred during the early morning hours as temperatures dipped into the lower 30's. Agricultural experts reported no significant effects on protected crops or  fruit trees. The only reported damage was some minor cold injury that affected random asparagus spears, but there was nothing widespread.  A ridge of high pressure extending from the Gulf coast northward to the lower Ohio and mid Mississippi Valleys provided clear skies and light winds. These conditions were conducive for frost.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snowmelt and rainfall flooding from late March and April along with above normal May rainfall resulted in continued flooding on the Big Sioux River near Castlewood. The Big Sioux River did fall below flood stage for a short period of time from May 15th to the 18th. The flooding then continued into June. The river reached its highest stage in late March at 12.6 feet where flood stage is 9 feet.

Earlier snowmelt and heavy rain flooding continued into early May on the Big Sioux River near Watertown. The river went below flood stage on May 5th and with heavy rainfall in late May, went above flood stage again for a short period of time from May 24th to May 25th.  The highest the river reached near Watertown was near 11 feet in late March where the flood stage is 8 feet.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several roads remained closed due to flooding. State Route 356 was closed due to flooding along Raccoon Creek and Onion Creek. Elk Fork flooded, closing a section of State Route 677. Flooding along Wheelabout Creek closed a portion of State Route 278.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Nocturnal thunderstorms moved through during the early morning hours of Friday, May 24, 2019.  A tornado watch was in effect. A flash flood watch was also in effect. A squall line developed, with several possible embedded tornadic rotations. 24 hour rainfall amounts ranged from 2 to 8.75 inches, the highest amount in southwest Iowa. River flooding developed on local streams, including the West Nishnabotna River, the Nishnabotna River, The Nodaway River, the Little Nemaha River, Weeping Water Creek, and the Big Blue River. The rainfall also pushed the Missouri River at Rulo back into the moderate category.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Coop Observer reported 2.40 inches east of Auburn.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from May, the James River near Forestburg (gage site FORS2) crested 3.71 feet above flood stage on June 1. Many rural roads near the river were inundated, with continued flooding of significant amounts of agricultural land. Minor flooding continued at the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moderately unstable airmass was in place across the central Appalachians on the 2nd. Remnants of a decaying thunderstorms complex moved across the Ohio River that afternoon and were rejuvenated by the instability across western and central WV. Most of the storms remained below severe limits, but one storm created a very localized microburst in Kanawha County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A NWS storm survey team determined a microburst occurred in the Tornado community. Nearly 100 trees were snapped or uprooted. The Big Bend Golf course was near the epicenter of the microburst and was hit especially hard, with dozen of trees (mostly pine) blown down. Several outbuilding also suffered minor damage. The course remained close for over a month while the damage was cleaned up. The rain gutters were blown off the fire station in Tornado, and several houses nearby suffered minor roof damage. Power was out in the area for over a day.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Areas of frost occurred during the early morning hours as temperatures dipped into the lower 30's. Agricultural experts reported no significant effects on protected crops or  fruit trees. The only reported damage was some minor cold injury that affected random asparagus spears, but there was nothing widespread.  A ridge of high pressure extending from the Gulf coast northward to the lower Ohio and mid Mississippi Valleys provided clear skies and light winds. These conditions were conducive for frost.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hot temperatures developed across the lower deserts of central Arizona in early June with highs in the Phoenix area climbing into the upper 90s and eventually reaching triple digits by June 5th. Despite high temperatures only reaching to near seasonal normals (and falling well short of excessive heat warning thresholds) it proved hot enough to be fatal to an elderly man whose car became stuck in desert sand stranding him without water or shade. The Maricopa County Sheriff's Office indicated that their helicopter spotted the man's vehicle stranded in sand on Gila River Indian land near Sun Lakes. Authorities found his body at 1340MST on Thursday June 6th; he was deceased. The sheriff's office indicated that the death was likely due to heat exposure.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: During the first week of June high temperatures over the deserts were near to slightly below seasonal normal, but did finally reach into the triple digits by Wednesday June 5th. Despite highs being near normal (and well below excessive heat warning thresholds) they were sufficient to lead to a fatality in the deserts to the south of Phoenix. According to the Maricopa County Sheriff's Office, their helicopter spotted the vehicle of a World War 2 veteran stuck in soft sand on Gila River Indian land south of Phoenix at 1340MST Thursday June 6th. The 97 year old veteran had died due to exposure and dehydration. He had been missing for several days before being discovered on Thursday.

Light rain changed over to light snow by the mid afternoon on Friday January 11. After several hours of not accumulating due to warm surface temperatures snow began to pile up shortly after sunset. While the atmosphere was certainly cold enough to produce plenty of snow it was warm enough to keep the snow to liquid ratio rather low. So, while more than 1 of liquid fell in many areas, this translated to roughly 5 to 8 inches of snow. Some of that liquid fell as rain, but the low snow to liquid ratio caused it to be a rather densely packed snow which clung to trees across the area, forming a picturesque winter wonderland. Snow continued to fall through the day on January 12, but most of the snowfall occurred through the night between January 11 and 12. Some totals in the region exceeded 12 inches, but most areas ended up with between 5 and 8 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 8 and 10 inches of snow fell across Atchison County, with most of it falling over the course of the first 12 hours. Light snow continued into the next day (January 12), but was fairly light, and only accounted for 1 to 2 inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A vehicle drove over wind blown snow that had drifted onto HWY 63, just north of Clark, Missouri. The driver lost control, ran off the left side of the road and into the median, then overturned and was ejected from the vehicle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The unsettled, progressive weather pattern continued across western Colorado during the month of March as numerous disturbances moved through. As a result of the wetter than normal conditions the state of the drought improved across the region, most notably in the Four Corners which finally eradicated the remaining extreme (D3) and severe (D2) drought conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought conditions over the southern tier of the forecast zone improved to the moderate (D1) category by the end of the month. Further north, the severe (D2) drought conditions improved to the abnormally dry (D0) category.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Atlantic ridge located south of Florida resulted in southwest winds across central Florida. This pushed deep moisture over the area, and when combined with daytime heating and cold temperatures in the middle atmosphere provided the conditions for showers and thunderstorms to develop. One thunderstorm in eastern Volusia County interacted with the sea breeze front. This storm quickly became severe as it moved very slowly southward over New Smyrna Beach and Edgewater and reports of hail were received along the Halifax River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported nickel sized hail near the intersection of Roberts Street and US Highway 1 in Edgwater.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning hit a telephone pole, knocking out the power.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Surface low pressure and remnants of a frontal boundary passed through the region late on the 4th and the early morning hours of the 5th. Showers streamed through from the southwest to the northeast along an approaching wave into an atmosphere with enhanced moisture. Saturated soils from the previous day's showers and storms combined with the showers and storms to produce flash flooding across portions of Virginia and West Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High water and debris covered parts of Interstate 77 near exit 99.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast-moving, but strong, storm pushed into the Sierra Nevada the morning of the 20th. Gusty winds developed ahead of the area of low pressure. Moderate to heavy precipitation developed over the Sierra and western Nevada as the low moved into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between the 20th and 21st, northern Reno and Spanish Springs received between 1.2 to 2.2 inches of snowfall. Areas within the Carson Valley received 0.5 to 1 inch of snowfall during the time period.

He crashed into the grass and fell out of the vehicle.||EMS pronounced Windler dead on the scene. No other vehicles were involved in the crash.||Link to the story: https://www.kwch.com/content/news/Snow-Plow-driver-dies-after-fatal-accident--504597511.html .

Troopers said Schultz was thrown from the car after the vehicle went off the road, into the median and flipped over. According to the Highway Patrol, Schultz wasn't wearing a seat belt. There was also three confirmed microbursts in the Pine Hills neighborhood of Albany, Menands, and North Greenbush.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees blew over onto power lines near Pocatalico and caused numerous power outages in the area.

The storms produced hail up to the size of half dollar coins and produced damaging winds that blew down numerous trees and power lines. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong southerly winds developed ahead of an approaching cold front. Peak wind gusts ranged from 40 to 55 mph. The highest measured wind gust was 55 mph at the Poplar Bluff airport. Other measured gusts included 53 mph at the Cape Girardeau airport and 44 mph at the Perryville airport.

An approaching cold front combined with a hot and humid air mass triggered scattered severe thunderstorms across the North Carolina Piedmont. These storms produced hail up to the size of golf balls and damaging winds that blew down numerous trees and power lines.  Some of the trees fell on to homes. The winds also blew the roof off a picnic shelter and threw it to the ground in Caswell County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail up to the size of golf balls fell on Raccoon Crossing Lane about three miles east of Arlington.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A hard freeze was observed across southern Illinois. Low temperatures were in the middle 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

An upper level disturbance moving across a moderately unstable air mass across lead to the development of a line of strong to severe thunderstorms across the Mohawk Valley of NY. One storm on the northern portion of this line moved through the southern Adirondacks that caused some damage on Schroon Falls.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Route 74 from Wicker street in the town of Schroon had downed trees and wires.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Multiple rounds of localized heavy rain occurred over portions of Bath County through the overnight hours, resulting in flash flooding. One rain gauge near Owingsville measured 7.23 inches of rain between 2:30 a.m. and 4:30 a.m. This led to water entering a home as well as washing out a bridge.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The county Emergency Manager reported water from a nearby creek rushing inside of a home in Pebble. This occurred as a rain gauge on East Fork Road, southwest of Pebble, recorded 7.23 inches of rainfall in a two hour period.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms slid from northwest to southeast across eastern Kentucky late this evening into the overnight hours, resulting in an isolated occurrence of flash flooding near Flat Creek in Bath County due to training.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local Emergency Management observed nearly a foot of swiftly flowing water over Flat Creek Road north of U.S. Highway 60.

Cells developing along the southern flank of this system quickly became severe with scattered reports of large hail and damaging wind.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Approach of a cold core upper level low resulted in bands of diurnal convective development. Instability was quite limited, as much as 500-1000 J/kg with weak deep-layer shear of around 20 knots, so the favored convective mode was short-lived pulse storms which remained disorganized.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drifts of pea-sized hail at Camden State Park.  There were a few as large as nickel to quarter size.  Rainfall was 2.50 inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A brief and small landspout occurred in the northwest side of Pipestone, causing minor damage to three buildings. Two metal sheds sustained damage to small sections of roof and door panels. The tornado then crossed a street and hit an apartment building where a 10 foot by 5 foot section of the south facing roof was removed.  The average path width was 10 yards.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Areas of frost occurred during the early morning hours as temperatures dipped into the lower 30's. Agricultural experts reported no significant effects on protected crops or  fruit trees. The only reported damage was some minor cold injury that affected random asparagus spears, but there was nothing widespread.  A ridge of high pressure extending from the Gulf coast northward to the lower Ohio and mid Mississippi Valleys provided clear skies and light winds. These conditions were conducive for frost.

At 12:30 AM EST on the 9th an amateur radio operator in Boston reported power lines down on Child Street.  A tree and street light were also down on Lee Street in Boston, and a tree was down on Chester Street in Boston.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system and upper level trough moved through the region during the early afternoon and evening hours of Wednesday, August 7th, 2019. This brought scattered severe thunderstorms to western Massachusetts which resulted in an isolated report of trees and wires down.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In addition to the hail, small branches, less than 2 inches in diameter, were downed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system and upper level trough moved through the region during the early afternoon and evening hours of Wednesday, August 7th, 2019. This brought scattered severe thunderstorms to eastern New York which resulted in numerous reports of trees and wires down.

An upper level trough moved through the region ahead of a cold front. This upper level energy sparked strong to severe thunderstorms from Albany and points south during the early afternoon hours of Saturday, August 3rd, 2019. As a result of these storms, multiple trees and wires were downed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dime to nickel size hail was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather system from the Midwest initially brought snow and ice to the region. The system swung a cold front through New England, followed by strong west to northwest winds from the afternoon of the 8th to the afternoon of the 9th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At 10:30 PM EST Worcester law enforcement reported a large tree down on Sunderland Road in Worcester. At 2:03 AM on the 9th an amateur radio operator reported a tree and power line down on Hall road in Dudley.  At 2:32 AM EST an amateur radio operator in Mendon reported a wind gust to 49 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Persistent southwesterly flow brought deep tropical moisture into the area, fueling numerous thunderstorms over the Gulf of Mexico that shifted onshore throughout the day. One of these storms caused a severe wind gust as it came onshore.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mesonet station in Indian Shores Beach recorded a 51 knot thunderstorm wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Continued southwesterly flow supplied a deep tropical air mass, with numerous storms developing over the eastern Gulf of Mexico and shifting inland throughout the day. A couple of these storms produced marine wind gusts along the coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The WeatherFlow station at Egmont Channel (XEGM) recorded a 41 knot thunderstorm wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Continued southwesterly flow supplied a deep tropical air mass, with numerous storms developing over the eastern Gulf of Mexico and shifting inland throughout the day. A couple of these storms produced marine wind gusts along the coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The WeatherFlow station on the Skyway Fishing Pier (XSKY) recorded a 35 knot thunderstorm wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Easterly flow led to scattered thunderstorms developing over the Florida Peninsula and shifting west into the Gulf throughout the afternoon. One of these storms caused gusty winds along the coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The WeatherFlow station at the Skyway Fishing Pier (XSKY) reported a 37 knot thunderstorm wind gust.
