EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A gradual decrease in river levels occurred as water was routed downstream along the Little Sioux River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from May, the Little Sioux River near Montgomery (gage site MLSI4) began the month at 0.62 feet above flood stage.  Significant amounts of agricultural land remained flooded, and further impeded spring planting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A couple mesoscale convective systems within a hot and humid air mass brought lines of severe thunderstorms during the afternoon and evening hours.  The storms produced hail up to the size of half dollar coins and produced damaging winds that blew down numerous trees and power lines.  At least 4,000 people lost power due to trees falling on to power lines, and a few structures also suffered damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds blew down multiple trees on Philpott Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A couple mesoscale convective systems within a hot and humid air mass brought lines of severe thunderstorms during the afternoon and evening hours.  The storms produced hail up to the size of quarters and produced damaging winds that blew down numerous trees and power lines.  The trees also damaged several structures.  In addition, the winds destroyed bleachers, damaged a chain link fence, and blew down a light pole at a little league baseball field in Bellepoint Park.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail up to the size of quarters fell on Nubbins Ridge Road about two miles northwest of Spanishburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Discreet thunderstorm cells developed over the higher terrain of central Pennsylvania in a moderate-CAPE / low-shear environment during the afternoon and evening hours of May 19, 2019. As these storms progressed eastward, some of them produced wind damage and/or hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A severe thunderstorm producing winds estimated near 60 mph knocked down trees near Lickdale.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mesoscale convective complex moved out of central South Dakota and across northeast South Dakota late night, spurred by a strong low-level jet and elevated instability up to 3000 J/kg.  Cells developing along the southern flank of this system quickly became severe with scattered reports of large hail and damaging wind.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dime to quarter size hail, with most falling as pea to dime size.

A hard freeze was observed across most of western Kentucky. Low temperatures were in the middle to upper 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching cold front combined with a hot and humid air mass triggered scattered severe thunderstorms across the North Carolina Piedmont. These storms produced hail up to the size of golf balls and damaging winds that blew down numerous trees and power lines.  Some of the trees fell on to homes. The winds also blew the roof off a picnic shelter and threw it to the ground in Caswell County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail up to the size of quarters fell near the intersection of Pitzer Road and Stanley Mabe Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak upper level trough moved across northern NY into a moderately unstable air mass. Scattered showers and a few thunderstorms developed in the afternoon with an isolated wind damage report in Crown Point.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Fire chief reported several downed trees on cars, roads, and powerlines along Factoryville, Fisherman;s Cove, White Church roads and Russel street.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak upper disturbance moved through a marginally unstable air mass which triggered numerous showers and a few scattered thunderstorms. One particular storm traveled along the Route 2 corridor in central-northeast VT with some damaging winds in Plainfield, Marshfield and Cabot.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotty tree and wire damage due to fallen trees along the Route 2 corridor between Plainfield and Cabot.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance moving across a moderately unstable air mass across lead to the development of a line of strong to severe thunderstorms across the Mohawk Valley of NY that moved across southern VT. Several reports of wind damage accompanied these thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees reported down across Lake St. Catherine.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strengthening low pressure system and cold front brought a widespread soaking rainfall to the region from the afternoon hours of Wednesday, October 16th through the morning of Thursday, October 17th, 2019. Prior to the cold frontal passage, winds became strong, resulting in a few reports of trees and wires down. Fortunately, only minor flooding occurred due to dry antecedent conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees down blocking a road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance sparked strong to severe thunderstorms, mainly in the Capital District, during the afternoon hours of Friday, August 16th, 2019. These storms resulted in multiple reports of trees and wires down across Albany and Renssselaer counties, with over 12,000 homes and businesses without power. There was also three confirmed microbursts in the Pine Hills neighborhood of Albany, Menands, and North Greenbush.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree with numerous limbs and branches was downed on Hartman Road in Albany.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deep moisture and easterly flow allowed for scattered thunderstorms to develop mainly along sea breeze boundaries. A few of these storms caused gusty winds along the coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The WeatherFlow station at Boca Grande (XBCG) recorded a 34 knot marine wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very moist airmass was in place across the region. A low pressure system moved north out of the Gulf of Mexico and a shortwave trough was moving through the region, both of which combined with this moist air to bring efficient rainfall to the region. Some of this heavy rain resulted in flash flooding across portions of central Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding occurred on Highway 540 W just past Jupiter Road. Standing water also occurred on Highway 49 near D'Lo.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather system from the Midwest initially brought snow and ice to the region. The system swung a cold front through New England, followed by strong west to northwest winds from the afternoon of the 8th to the afternoon of the 9th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance sparked strong to severe thunderstorms, mainly in the Capital District, during the afternoon hours of Friday, August 16th, 2019. These storms resulted in multiple reports of trees and wires down across Albany and Renssselaer counties, with over 12,000 homes and businesses without power. There was also three confirmed microbursts in the Pine Hills neighborhood of Albany, Menands, and North Greenbush.

Strong southerly winds developed ahead of an approaching cold front. Peak wind gusts ranged from 40 to 55 mph. The highest measured wind gust was 55 mph at the Poplar Bluff airport. Other measured gusts included 53 mph at the Cape Girardeau airport and 44 mph at the Perryville airport.

Approach of a cold core upper level low resulted in bands of diurnal convective development. Instability was quite limited, as much as 500-1000 J/kg with weak deep-layer shear of around 20 knots, so the favored convective mode was short-lived pulse storms which remained disorganized.
Instability was somewhat limited by diurnal cloud cover to 500-1000 J/kg, but with increased deep-layer shear by evening, an isolated severe thunderstorm developed and briefly produced large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail, along with a lot of smaller hail, covered the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strengthening low pressure system and cold front brought a widespread soaking rainfall to the region from the afternoon hours of Wednesday, October 16th through the morning of Thursday, October 17th, 2019. Prior to the cold frontal passage, winds became strong, resulting in a few reports of trees and wires down. Fortunately, only minor flooding occurred due to dry antecedent conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were downed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A hard freeze was observed across southern Illinois. Low temperatures were in the middle 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

Westerly flow caused morning showers and thunderstorms forming over the Gulf of Mexico and shifting onshore through the day. A lightning strike from one storm struck a septic tank, causing an explosion in the plumbing and damaging a toilet in the house.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning struck a septic tank, igniting gas in the plumbing, which caused a toilet in the house to explode. No one was injured.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving low pressure area brought a prolonged period of light to moderate snowfall. Lake enhanced snow contributed to the overall totals for the counties bordering Lake MI. EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to seven inches of snow accumulation.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching cold front combined with a hot and humid air mass triggered scattered severe thunderstorms across the North Carolina Piedmont. These storms produced hail up to the size of golf balls and damaging winds that blew down numerous trees and power lines.  Some of the trees fell on to homes. The winds also blew the roof off a picnic shelter and threw it to the ground in Caswell County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds uprooted several trees and snapped several more tree tops along Winters Road about three miles east of Arlington.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light and moist SW flow pushed the more dominant west coast sea breeze across the Suwannee River Valley with a surface front across central GA and a lingering outflow boundary near the Altamaha River basin. The mid levels were warm, but with little subsidence which enabled scattered storms to develop in the afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: U.S. Highway 441 was closed at the 19000 block due to flooding.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A WeatherStem station measured 5.05 inches within just over 3 hours. Some flooding was reported near High Springs.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Southwest flow across the area with a lingering surface front across southern GA provide moisture and lift to produce locally heavy rainfall in diurnally driven showers and storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A station measured 1.20 inches in 15 minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Southwest flow across the area with a lingering surface front across southern GA provide moisture and lift to produce locally heavy rainfall in diurnally driven showers and storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An observed measured 2.25 inches of rainfall in about 50 minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather system from the Midwest initially brought snow and ice to the region. The system swung a cold front through New England, followed by strong west to northwest winds from the afternoon of the 8th to the afternoon of the 9th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At 12:42 AM EST an amateur radio operator in Cambridge reported a wind gust to 56 mph. At 9:50 AM EST an amateur radio operator in Medford reported a large tree and power lines down on Gleason Street near Madison Street.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A couple mesoscale convective systems within a hot and humid air mass brought lines of severe thunderstorms during the afternoon and evening hours.  The storms produced hail up to the size of half dollar coins and produced damaging winds that blew down numerous trees and power lines.  At least 4,000 people lost power due to trees falling on to power lines, and a few structures also suffered damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds blew down multiple trees in the city of Buena Vista.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Discreet thunderstorm cells developed over the higher terrain of central Pennsylvania in a moderate-CAPE / low-shear environment during the afternoon and evening hours of May 19, 2019. As these storms progressed eastward, some of them produced wind damage and/or hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A severe thunderstorm produced half-dollar sized hail near Denver.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Discreet thunderstorm cells developed over the higher terrain of central Pennsylvania in a moderate-CAPE / low-shear environment during the afternoon and evening hours of May 19, 2019. As these storms progressed eastward, some of them produced wind damage and/or hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A severe thunderstorm produced quarter-sized hail in southern Lebanon County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving low pressure area brought a prolonged period of light to moderate snowfall. Lake enhanced snow contributed to the overall totals for the counties bordering Lake MI. Two deaths occurred when a semi-truck plunged into Mirror Lake after sliding off the I-90/94 bridge near Lake Delton. Other vehicle slide-offs and accidents occurred across southern WI.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to eight inches of snow accumulation.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching cold front combined with a hot and humid air mass triggered scattered severe thunderstorms across the North Carolina Piedmont. These storms produced hail up to the size of golf balls and damaging winds that blew down numerous trees and power lines.  Some of the trees fell on to homes. The winds also blew the roof off a picnic shelter and threw it to the ground in Caswell County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail up to the size of golf balls fell near the intersection of Pleasant Grove Church Road and Highway 158 about four miles east of Yanceyville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A gradual decrease in river levels occurred as water was routed downstream along the Little Sioux River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from May, the Little Sioux River near Milford (gage site MIFI4) began the month at 3.99 feet above flood stage. Water inundated 180th Street between 170th and 190th Avenues as well as 190th Avenue near 240th Street.  Significant amounts of agricultural land remained flooded, and further impeded spring planting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High moisture content combined with weak upper level forcing and warm conditions aloft favored locally heavy rainfall in sea breeze and outflow triggered showers and thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: About 6 inches of water was flowing over the intersection of Market and Orange Streets near Hogan's Creek.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High moisture content combined with weak upper level forcing and warm conditions aloft favored locally heavy rainfall in sea breeze and outflow triggered showers and thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An observer measured 2.99 inches of rainfall in 2 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Nocturnal thunderstorms moved through during the early morning hours of Friday, May 24, 2019.  A tornado watch was in effect. A flash flood watch was also in effect. A squall line developed, with several possible embedded tornadic rotations. 24 hour rainfall amounts ranged from 2 to 8.75 inches, the highest amount in southwest Iowa. River flooding developed on local streams, including the West Nishnabotna River, the Nishnabotna River, The Nodaway River, the Little Nemaha River, Weeping Water Creek, and the Big Blue River. The rainfall also pushed the Missouri River at Rulo back into the moderate category.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters reported 3.40 inches of rain south of Tecumseh.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: At 7:18 PM EST a mesonet station on Plum Island reported sustained wind of 41 mph. At 9 PM EST a trained spotter reported a tree and wires down on Harbor Avenue in Marblehead. At 5:48 AM EST on the 9th the mesonet station on Plum Island reported a wind gust to 52 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Runoff from 1 to 2 inches of rainfall throughout the Big Sioux River basin occurred in the week to 10 days prior to onset of renewed minor flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Big Sioux River at Akron (gage site AKRI4) crested 2.62 feet above flood stage on June 28, causing significant flooding of crop and pasture land.  The river remained in minor flood stage at the end of the month.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Big Sioux River at Akron (gage site AKRI4) crested 2.62 feet above flood stage on June 28, causing significant flooding of crop and pasture land.  The river remained in minor flood stage at the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Areas of frost occurred during the early morning hours as temperatures dipped into the lower 30's. Agricultural experts reported no significant effects on protected crops or  fruit trees. The only reported damage was some minor cold injury that affected random asparagus spears, but there was nothing widespread.  A ridge of high pressure extending from the Gulf coast northward to the lower Ohio and mid Mississippi Valleys provided clear skies and light winds. These conditions were conducive for frost.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Big Sioux River near Richland (gage site BSRS2) crested 2.43 feet above flood stage on June 29, causing significant flooding of crop and pasture land.  The river remained in minor flood stage at the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Approach of a cold core upper level low resulted in bands of diurnal convective development. Instability was quite limited, as much as 500-1000 J/kg with weak deep-layer shear of around 20 knots, so the favored convective mode was short-lived pulse storms which remained disorganized.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple quarter-sized hailstones with some up to half-dollar size.  Many leaves were stripped due to abundant hail.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Right lanes were partially flooded at the intersection of San Jose and Claire Lane.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A hard freeze was observed across southern Illinois. Low temperatures were in the middle 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather system from the Midwest initially brought snow and ice to the region. The system swung a cold front through New England, followed by strong west to northwest winds from the afternoon of the 8th to the afternoon of the 9th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At 9:36 PM EST a trained spotter in Bolton reported a tree and power lines down through the roof of a house on Long Hill Road. At 8:23 PM EST the Automated Surface Observing System platform at Fitchburg Municipal Airport measured a wind gust to 51 mph.  At 5:23 AM EST on the 9th an amateur radio operator in Hardwick reported a large tree down on power lines on Greenwich Road.

Periodic heavy rainfall during early June and routing of water downstream resulted in continued flooding of the Vermillion River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from May, the Vermillion River near Wakonda (gage site WKAS2) started at 3.10 feet above flood stage on June 1. Many rural roads near the river were inundated, with continued flooding of significant amounts of agricultural land.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Periodic heavy rainfall during early June and routing of water downstream resulted in continued flooding of the Vermillion River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from May, the Vermillion River near Wakonda (gage site WKAS2) started at 3.10 feet above flood stage on June 1. Many rural roads near the river were inundated, with continued flooding of significant amounts of agricultural land.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Periodic heavy rainfall during early June and routing of water downstream resulted in continued flooding of the Vermillion River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A continuation of flooding from May, the Vermillion River at Vermillion (gage site VERS2) started at 1.37 feet above flood stage on June 1. Many rural roads near the river were inundated, with continued flooding of significant amounts of agricultural land.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A hard freeze was observed across most of western Kentucky. Low temperatures were in the middle to upper 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

A slow-moving low pressure system was accompanied by unusually-high amounts of moisture, periods of steady of heavy rain, and some thunderstorms over north-central Montana during May 25th through the early morning of the 28th. In addition, relatively-high snow levels allowed rain to fall on lingering snowpack along the Rocky Mountain Front, where easterly upslope flow enhanced rainfall totals. Portions of the Rocky Mountain Front received as much as around 3 to 6 inches of total rainfall. Runoff from snowmelt and significant rainfall led to flooding along some rivers and overland flooding. The worst flooding was focused in the Augusta area, along the Sun River, and along Badger Creek in the Browning area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Fergus County Sheriff reported flooding near Utica. Exact duration of flooding unknown.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered to numerous thunderstorms developed in the early afternoon hours within a warm and unstable airmass. A few of these thunderstorms became strong enough to produce damaging wind gusts. One storm even produced a brief tornado after interacting with a mesoscale boundary.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A National Weather Service storm survey team confirmed an EF-1 tornado in Chatham County. The tornado began over the Wilmington River, just west of the Savannah Yacht Club on Whitemarsh Island. It developed rapidly as it hit the Savannah Yacht Club. At the time the tornado struck, a boat was being lifted by a crane at the dock. This boat was thrown from the crane back into the water. The boat crane was also pushed by the winds of the tornado off its track, which caused it to crash into a small building near the crane. This small building sustained significant roof damage. One person was reportedly injured inside the building, but the extent of their injuries was unknown. The tornado continued moving east-southeast , snapping and uprooting several trees in a residential area near the end of Bradley Creek Drive. One home in that area also had minor roof damage due to missing shingles. From this point, the tornado strengthened as it moved southeast over Bradley Creek and across portions of Turners Rock Road. This was the region where the most significant damage was found, with at least two dozen large hard and softwood trees either snapped or uprooted. Wind speeds in this area were estimated to be between 100 and 105 mph. The tornado then weakened as it moved on a more easterly path across Turner Creek and onto the western edge of Wilmington Island, just south of Johnny Mercer Boulevard. The tornado broke some tree limbs and branches around Walgreens, then damaged a sign near the Autoplex as it crossed Johnny Mercer Boulevard. Once across Johnny Mercer Boulevard, the weakening tornado skipped over Molly McGuire's restaurant, finally ending in the empty lot just east of the Goodwill store. The roof on the Goodwill store sustained minor damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A hard freeze was observed across most of western Kentucky. Low temperatures were in the middle to upper 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

CZ_NAME: GORE AND ELK MOUNTAINS/CENTRAL MOUNTAIN VALLEYS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist and moderately fast southwest flow out ahead of and with the passage of a Pacific trough produced significant snow over the mountains of western Colorado. Some of the southern, central and northern valleys also received moderate snowfall. The presence of a strong subtropical jet aloft provided additional support as well as gusty winds at the surface which led to areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 4 to 7 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts ranging from 10 to 18 inches at the ski resorts. Winds gusted up to 45 MPH which led to areas of blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow-moving low pressure system was accompanied by unusually-high amounts of moisture, periods of steady of heavy rain, and some thunderstorms over north-central Montana during May 25th through the early morning of the 28th. In addition, relatively-high snow levels allowed rain to fall on lingering snowpack along the Rocky Mountain Front, where easterly upslope flow enhanced rainfall totals. Portions of the Rocky Mountain Front received as much as around 3 to 6 inches of total rainfall. Runoff from snowmelt and significant rainfall led to flooding along some rivers and overland flooding. The worst flooding was focused in the Augusta area, along the Sun River, and along Badger Creek in the Browning area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: MT DOT reported floodwater on US-2, 3-miles west of East Glacier. Exact duration of flooding unknown.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Reports from the 13h through the 19th in this entry. ||A relatively deep and widespread snowpack existed across the region during early to mid March. Many areas in central and northern Iowa had around a foot to two feet of snow on the ground, along with many areas in upstream river basins in Minnesota and the Dakotas having similar or deeper snowpacks on the ground. Additionally, with the below normal temperatures throughout the majority of the 2019 year to date, soils were frozen to depths of a foot or more throughout the aforementioned areas. All of that primed the area for potential moderate to major flooding issues should a rapid snowmelt and/or rainfall event occur, which unfortunately came to fruition. ||The primary driver was two-fold with warm air advection on the backside of a departing high pressure on the 12th, and a sizable low pressure system that moved through the region on the 13th and 14th. The event began with widespread temperatures and dew points in the upper 30s to low 40s on the 12th with the initial warm air advection, which continued through the overnight hours into the 13th. As the low pressure system developed off the Colorado Rockies, warm air advection continued to push temperatures and dew points up into the upper 40s and low 50s on the 13th and 14th, aiding the rapid snow melt. On top of the rapid snowmelt, which often went from 12 or more inches on the ground to zero in a matter of about two days, light to moderate rainfall occurred ahead of and on the backside of the low pressure system on the 13th and 14th. All combined to cause widespread overland flooding, river flooding, and ice jam issues.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Iowa DOT reported Iowa 4 closed between Wallingford in Emmet County and Graettinger in Palo Alto County due to water over the road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid level Pacific trough progressed east into western Colorado. Ample moisture in the unsettled southwesterly flow produced moderate wet, dense snowfall across much of the higher terrain. Additionally, the presence of a strong upper level jet overhead resulted in gusty winds at the surface which led to blowing snow and reduced visibilities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Around 9 inches of snow was estimated at the Columbine Pass SNOTEL site. Winds gusted up to 45 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing temperatures were observed across southeast Missouri. Low temperatures were in the upper 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

An upper level trough was over the Great Basin during the morning hours and moved over the Rocky Mountains during the day. Upper level disturbances moved over West Texas along the edge of this upper trough. A surface trough was over far West Texas and resulted in an abundance of moisture across the area. The atmosphere quickly became unstable as temperatures warmed up at the surface. A dryline was backed up to the higher terrain of West Texas and southeast New Mexico with very good wind shear and atmospheric rotation in place. During the late evening hours, upper lift increased with the approaching upper trough and the area was in a favorable position for lift with the upper jet stream. A low-level jet stream also moved across the area providing more lift. A Pacific front associated with the upper trough moved east and interacted with the dryline to create additional lift. These conditions resulted in thunderstorms rapidly developing and becoming severe with large hail, strong and damaging winds, tornadoes, and flash flooding across West Texas.

All of that primed the area for potential moderate to major flooding issues should a rapid snowmelt and/or rainfall event occur, which unfortunately came to fruition. ||The primary driver was two-fold with warm air advection on the backside of a departing high pressure on the 12th, and a sizable low pressure system that moved through the region on the 13th and 14th. The event began with widespread temperatures and dew points in the upper 30s to low 40s on the 12th with the initial warm air advection, which continued through the overnight hours into the 13th. As the low pressure system developed off the Colorado Rockies, warm air advection continued to push temperatures and dew points up into the upper 40s and low 50s on the 13th and 14th, aiding the rapid snow melt. On top of the rapid snowmelt, which often went from 12 or more inches on the ground to zero in a matter of about two days, light to moderate rainfall occurred ahead of and on the backside of the low pressure system on the 13th and 14th. All combined to cause widespread overland flooding, river flooding, and ice jam issues.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: County roads near the North River in Norwalk are flooded and impassable due an ice jam.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing temperatures were observed across southeast Missouri. Low temperatures were in the upper 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A coastal storm passed offshore of Massachusetts on February 18th, bringing snow to all of Southern New England.  The heaviest snow was located over Southern Massachusetts, especially Plymouth County.  Snow tapered off during the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: From 3 to 4 inches of snow fell on Suffolk County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid level Pacific trough progressed into eastern Utah from the Great Basin. Ample moisture in the unsettled southwesterly flow produced moderate wet, dense snowfall across much of the higher terrain. Additionally, the presence of a strong upper level jet overhead resulted in gusty winds at the surface which led to blowing snow and reduced visibilities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An average of 5 to 10 inches of snow fell across the area. Winds gusted from 40 to 50 MPH.

An upper level trough was over the Great Basin during the morning hours and moved over the Rocky Mountains during the day. Upper level disturbances moved over West Texas along the edge of this upper trough. A surface trough was over far West Texas and resulted in an abundance of moisture across the area. The atmosphere quickly became unstable as temperatures warmed up at the surface. A dryline was backed up to the higher terrain of West Texas and southeast New Mexico with very good wind shear and atmospheric rotation in place. During the late evening hours, upper lift increased with the approaching upper trough and the area was in a favorable position for lift with the upper jet stream. A low-level jet stream also moved across the area providing more lift. A Pacific front associated with the upper trough moved east and interacted with the dryline to create additional lift. These conditions resulted in thunderstorms rapidly developing and becoming severe with large hail, strong and damaging winds, tornadoes, and flash flooding across West Texas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent storm system in the Plains drove a cold front across the Midsouth that produced severe thunderstorms capable of large hail, damaging winds and tornadoes. Out ahead of the storms non-thunderstorm winds from a strong gradient also produced some damage. All four states were impacted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Brief touchdown 2.5 miles west of Falkner. No damaged reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow-moving low pressure system was accompanied by unusually-high amounts of moisture, periods of steady of heavy rain, and some thunderstorms over north-central Montana during May 25th through the early morning of the 28th. In addition, relatively-high snow levels allowed rain to fall on lingering snowpack along the Rocky Mountain Front, where easterly upslope flow enhanced rainfall totals. Portions of the Rocky Mountain Front received as much as around 3 to 6 inches of total rainfall. Runoff from snowmelt and significant rainfall led to flooding along some rivers and overland flooding. The worst flooding was focused in the Augusta area, along the Sun River, and along Badger Creek in the Browning area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency manager shared video of flooded wheat field adjacent to the Teton River. Estimated time of the event. Exact duration of flooding unknown.

On top of the rapid snowmelt, which often went from 12 or more inches on the ground to zero in a matter of about two days, light to moderate rainfall occurred ahead of and on the backside of the low pressure system on the 13th and 14th. All combined to cause widespread overland flooding, river flooding, and ice jam issues.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Iowa DOT reported Iowa 14 closed north of Parkersburg between Iowa 57 and County Road C55.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing temperatures were observed across southeast Missouri. Low temperatures were in the upper 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

Moist and moderately fast southwest flow out ahead of and with the passage of a Pacific trough produced significant snow over the mountains of western Colorado. Some of the southern, central and northern valleys also received moderate snowfall. The presence of a strong subtropical jet aloft provided additional support as well as gusty winds at the surface which led to areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Douglas Pass had a storm total snowfall of 8.5 inches. Winds were gusting to 50 to 60 MPH for much of the event with a peak gust of 62 MPH. This resulted in hazardous driving conditions with reduced visibility. Douglas Pass was closed for around an hour due to a crash and a vehicle that slid off.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Reports from the 13h through the 19th in this entry. ||A relatively deep and widespread snowpack existed across the region during early to mid March. Many areas in central and northern Iowa had around a foot to two feet of snow on the ground, along with many areas in upstream river basins in Minnesota and the Dakotas having similar or deeper snowpacks on the ground. Additionally, with the below normal temperatures throughout the majority of the 2019 year to date, soils were frozen to depths of a foot or more throughout the aforementioned areas. All of that primed the area for potential moderate to major flooding issues should a rapid snowmelt and/or rainfall event occur, which unfortunately came to fruition. ||The primary driver was two-fold with warm air advection on the backside of a departing high pressure on the 12th, and a sizable low pressure system that moved through the region on the 13th and 14th. The event began with widespread temperatures and dew points in the upper 30s to low 40s on the 12th with the initial warm air advection, which continued through the overnight hours into the 13th. As the low pressure system developed off the Colorado Rockies, warm air advection continued to push temperatures and dew points up into the upper 40s and low 50s on the 13th and 14th, aiding the rapid snow melt. On top of the rapid snowmelt, which often went from 12 or more inches on the ground to zero in a matter of about two days, light to moderate rainfall occurred ahead of and on the backside of the low pressure system on the 13th and 14th. All combined to cause widespread overland flooding, river flooding, and ice jam issues.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency management and river gauges reported 8 to 10 foot rises on the Middle Raccoon and South Raccoon Rivers due to ice jams. Several county roads were impacts with road closures. Flooding was also reported along Highway 44 between Panora and Dallas Center from heavy rain and snowmelt. Portions of Walnut Creek were also just above bankfull from the rain and snowmelt.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wet Pacific system brought snow, freezing rain and rain with many changes in type in low elevations of the Snake River Plain during the three days with mostly snow in higher elevations.  Extensive travel problems were caused by the system with school closures on both the 17th and 18th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm brought freezing rain on the 17th to the Upper Snake River Plain.  Many private schools closed in Idaho Falls on the 17th with many of the public schools remaining open.   A Jefferson County school bus collided with a semi truck around 7:27 AM MST just north of Osgood on the icy interstate.  Another semi truck crashed south of Idaho Falls near mile post 106.  Multiple slideoffs reported between Blackfoot and Idaho Falls.  Heaviest reported snowfall with the system was 4.0 inches by the Saint Anthony COOP observer.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure crossed Wyoming and brought heavy snow and strong wind to much of the area. The heaviest snow fell in the favored northerly upslope areas, including Casper and Lander where anywhere from 8 to 12 inches of snow was recorded. Close to a foot of snow also fell near Green River and Rock Springs. Over a foot fell in some of the adjacent mountains as well. The snow also combined with winds that gusted over 50 mph at times that lowered visibility to near zero at times. This led to the closure of many roads for several hours, including Interstates 80 and 25.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell on Casper Mountain. Some amounts included 17 and 14 inches at the Reno Hill and Casper Mountains SNOTEL sites, respectively.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Deepening storm center tracked into the Eastern Gulf on Sunday evening 4/21 then stalled in the NE Gulf through Mon morning. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low moved through Southern California on January 31st and brought heavy rain and thunderstorms to the region. Thunderstorms brought occasional heavy precipitation, resulting in flash flooding. The coastal areas of Orange and San Diego County received a half an inch of precipitation over 2 hours. The Pacific Coast Highway (Highway 1) was closed due to flooding. Lightning struck a tree and damaged a fence in San Diego County. 40 cloud-to-ground strikes were observed in San Diego County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: CalTrans reported Pacific Coast Highway (highway 1) closed due to flooding. This area received around 0.5 inch of rainfall in 2 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Bridwell Wildfire began around 1558CST about three miles northeast of Boise Texas in Oldham County. The wildfire consumed approximately three hundred acres and was caused by vehicle dragging chain on road or highway. There was a report that one home was threatened by the wildfire but was saved, however there were no other reports of any homes or other structures threatened, damaged or destroyed by the wildfire. There were also no reports of any injuries or fatalities. The wildfire was brought under control around 1812CST.

The FM 1260 and CR W Wildfire began around 1045CST about four miles southwest of Lelia Lake in Donley County. The wildfire was caused by vehicle dragging chain on road or highway. The wildfire consumed about four hundred acres and there were reports that five homes and twelve other structures were threatened by the wildfire but were saved. There were no reports of any homes or other structures damaged or destroyed and there were also no reports of any injuries or fatalities. The wildfire was brought under control around 2000CST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong complex of thunderstorms moved across the Eastern Gulf of Mexico while producing widespread gusty winds over the waters as well as a few waterspouts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The ASOS station at Tampa International Airport measured a wind gust of 38 knots...44 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Alberta Clipper moved southeast across Wyoming. Most areas only had light amounts of snow. However, local banding developed near Lander where some areas had over 6 inches of snow. More areas saw high wind as the cold front moved through. Some of the more notable wind gusts included 87 mph along the Chief Joseph Highway and 71 mph south of Casper.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds occurred in portions of the Absarokas. Along the Chief Joseph Highway, there were several hurricane force wind gusts, including a maximum gust of 87 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The ASOS at the Buffalo airport measured a maximum wind gust of 62 mph. Along Interstate 25, wind gusts as high as 64 mph. The wind combined with snow to produce sharply reduced visibility that made travel very difficult for a time.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An inside slider low moved into Southern California on January 21 and brought widespread precipitation and strong westerly winds to the region. A period of Santa Ana winds immediately followed the inside slider, and brought high winds to the region, especially in the mountain areas. The peak observed wind gust was 84 knots in Burns Canyon. Two people were killed when a large tree fell on their home in Point Loma in San Diego County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Borrego Air Ranch Airport mesonet reported a peak wind gust of 54 knots between 0600 and 0700 PST on January 21st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low moved through Southern California on January 31st and brought heavy rain and thunderstorms to the region. Thunderstorms brought occasional heavy precipitation, resulting in flash flooding. The coastal areas of Orange and San Diego County received a half an inch of precipitation over 2 hours. The Pacific Coast Highway (Highway 1) was closed due to flooding. Lightning struck a tree and damaged a fence in San Diego County. 40 cloud-to-ground strikes were observed in San Diego County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Broadcast media reported that lightning struck a fence and caused damage to it. 40 cloud-to-ground lightning strikes were observed during this event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By 1000 am CST, the weather was rapidly changing. Northern and western sections of Arkansas had temperatures in the 20s and 30s. It was 26 degrees at Fayetteville (Washington County) and 28 degrees at Harrison (Boone County). Given northwest winds at 15 to 20 mph and some gusts over 30 mph, wind chill index values were in the single digits at several locations. Meanwhile, it was still 59 degrees at Monticello (Drew County) and 57 degrees at West Memphis (Crittenden County).||At this time, drier air mostly shut off rain across the southern counties. Farther north/west, there was enough moisture to keep precipitation going. As temperatures dropped, it was cold enough for snow.  ||One to three inches of snow was common across the north and west. There were spotty reports of more than four inches, and isolated instances of half foot accumulations.|The highest amounts included 7 inches at Big Flat (Baxter County), 6 inches at Booneville (Logan County), 5 inches at Hardy (Sharp County) and Pocahontas (Randolph County), and 4 inches at Mansfield (Scott County), Marshall (Searcy County), Mountain View (Stone County), and Mount Magazine (Logan County).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer reported 0.2 inch of snow in Russellville for an event total.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed across the south central United States during the daylight hours of January 12th as high pressure was positioned over the northeastern United States and southeastern Canada. The low pressure system then tracked into the southeastern United States during the overnight hours of January 12th and moved northeastward offshore near the Outer Banks of North Carolina through the day of January 13th. Widespread accumulating snow affected the state of Maryland, with the highest totals south and west of Baltimore.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 inches were observed across Frederick County, with a localized maximum of 10.9 inches measured near Point of Rocks.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist and moderately fast southwest flow out ahead of and with the passage of a Pacific trough produced significant snow over the mountains of western Colorado. Some of the southern, central and northern valleys also received moderate snowfall. The presence of a strong subtropical jet aloft provided additional support as well as gusty winds at the surface which led to areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter measured 12 inches of snow 14 miles southwest of Olathe and the Columbine Pass SNOTEL site had an estimated 20 inches. Winds gusted up to 45 MPH.

Cold Canadian high pressure settled over the Northland the night of the 18th into the 19th. Clear skies and light winds led to good radiational cooling conditions allowing lows to cool into the 30s and 40s below zero. In areas that didn't see winds completely subside, very cold wind wind chills approaching 50 below zero were recorded.

A dry upper low brought blustery conditions to the region into New Years Day. Gusty northerly winds were observed in the higher elevations of the North and East Bay. The highest peaks saw gusts of over 60 mph at Mt St Helena and Mt Diablo.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wet Pacific system brought snow, freezing rain and rain with many changes in type in low elevations of the Snake River Plain during the three days with mostly snow in higher elevations.  Extensive travel problems were caused by the system with school closures on both the 17th and 18th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters reported 9 to 10 inches of snow in Hailey with the Bellevue COOP observer reporting 8.3 inches.  The Picabo COOP observer had 5.0 inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Island Park COOP observer reported 14.4 inches of snow with the White Elephant SNOTEL reporting 14.2 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A skier and snowboarder were buried for 25 minutes on the 20th.  The two were carried 100 to 150 yards in an avalanche they triggered in the Warm Springs Creek drainage riding in the out-of-bounds area of Bald Mountain.  IT was 100 feet wide near 7,800 feet elevation and they were able to dig out and did not suffer serious injuries.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A skier and snowboarder were buried for 25 minutes on the 20th.  The two were carried 100 to 150 yards in an avalanche they triggered in the Warm Springs Creek drainage riding in the out-of-bounds area of Bald Mountain.  IT was 100 feet wide near 7,800 feet elevation and they were able to dig out and did not suffer serious injuries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta clipper moved through the region.  It's associated cold front allowed the stronger winds aloft to reach all the way down to the surface for a number of locations across northeast Montana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Beaver Hill I-94 DOT site, measured sustained winds of 40 mph and above at least each hour from 3:41 PM MST to 7:13 PM MST. An initial wind gust of 60 mph was recorded at 8:53 PM MST.  The peak wind gust of 61 mph was recorded at 9:04 PM MST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system reached Lower Michigan on January 28th.  Blizzard conditions were common from North Dakota to southern Wisconsin, with snow falling heavily in Lower Michigan on the 28th. Snowfall totals were generally from 4 to 10 inches, with a stripe of higher amounts along and north of Highway 10.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Eight to eleven inches was reported.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A public report from the Timberline neighborhood (northeast Flagstaff) indicated that 7.5 inches of snow fell between midnight and 730 AM on the 13th.  Light snow was still falling at the time of the observation.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A QLCS moved through southwest Georgia during the early morning hours with one brief tornado confirmed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A brief tornado touched down just west of Zetto and impacted a single family residence.  Part of the roof was ripped off from an attached carport as well as a garage on a shed blown in.  Trees were uprooted and large branches were broken off on the residence.  Brick and shingle damage was noted as well as other debris thrown about the yard and well behind the residence.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A QLCS moved through southeast Alabama during the early morning hours with one brief tornado confirmed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF0 tornado with max winds of 85 mph briefly touched down about 1.5 miles north of Abbeville.  A semi was blown off the road with no injuries, and tree damage occurred.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: It was far too mild for winter weather early on the 19th. During the wee hours, showers and scattered thunderstorms became widespread. Lightning struck a home near Butlerville (Lonoke County) and caused minor damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning struck a house on Bethlehem Rd. causing minor damage.  There were no injuries.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail stones varied from blueberry and coco puff size to roughly nickel size.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved out of northern Indiana into northwestern Ohio where limited heating allowed for some intensification of the complex. One thunderstorm produced a wet microburst in Van Wert county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency management officials reported eight trees, approximately 80 feet tall, were damaged. A few were snapped half way up the trunk with lots of smaller limbs on the ground. All fell towards the southeast.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed, but struggled to organize with mainly 30 to 50 mph wind gusts. Boundary interactions allowed for 2 storms to briefly produce wet microbursts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 65 year old male and a friend were heading for shore getting away from a thunderstorms when lightning struck the 65 year old. CPR was started but they were unable to save him. The other passenger was not harmed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Activity associated with a weakening MCS and pre-frontal trof moved across the region. Some of the storms produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to three inches of rain fell in about an hour and a half. This caused several local creeks to rise well out of their banks. Belleau Creek flooded Belleau Creek Road with over 6 inches of water, just south of intersection with I-70. Also a creek that feeds into Dardenne Creek in the St. Peters Golf Club rose well above it's banks flooding Salt Lick Road at the intersection with Timberbrook Drive and flooded sections of Four Winds and South Winds Drives. A couple of cars had to be abandoned on Salt Lick Road after the drivers drove into the flood waters and stalled their cars. No water rescues needed to be performed. Also, on Four Winds Drive at least half a dozen parked cars were flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disorganized trough of low pressure moved over the region starting late in the morning of the 21st and then exited the area during the mid-morning hours of the 22nd. While snow was seen across much of the Northland, a concentrated area of snow was seen from Cass County eastward to the Duluth and Two Harbors area. Snowfall totals in this band ended up in the 8 to 10 inch range while the remainder of the area was below 6.

CZ_NAME: LITTLE COLORADO RIVER VALLEY IN APACHE COUNTY
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quick moving strong cold front moved across Arizona with areas of high winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Springerville Airport ASOS measured sustained winds above 40 MPH between 710 AM and 215 PM, wind gusts above 58 MPH between 755 AM and 235 PM, and a peak wind gust of 68 MPH at 155 PM.  The St Johns Airport ASOS measured sustained winds above 40 MPH between 910 AM AM and 135 PM, wind gusts above 58 MPH between 1025 AM and 120 PM, and a peak wind gust of 64 MPH at 135 PM.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level jet in the wake of a departing storm system combined with a sharp surface pressure along the central mountain chain to produce high winds on January 7th. Many areas from the central mountain chain eastward into the eastern plains experienced peak wind gusts between 45 and 55 mph through the afternoon and early evening. The strongest winds impacted the area around Clines Corners were sustained winds reached 40 mph for a couple hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Clines Corners reported sustained winds of 40 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent storm system shifted east through the southern Rockies on January 22nd and forced a major cold front southward down the Front Range. A sharp north wind shift surged south across the Colorado border into northeastern New Mexico with wind gusts up to 62 mph at Raton. Light snow and frigid temperatures behind the front set the stage for hazardous travel conditions with snow, blowing snow, and very low visibility. Interstate 25 at Raton Pass was closed for several hours. Several rural highways over eastern Colfax and western Union counties were also closed due to extremely icy travel.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The combination of light snow, blowing snow, high winds, and frigid temperatures resulted in extremely hazardous travel conditions along Interstate 25 at Raton Pass. The highway was closed for much of the day.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The combination of light snow, blowing snow, high winds, and frigid temperatures resulted in extremely hazardous travel conditions over many rural highways near the Colorado border. NM-456 was closed for the entire day and severe travel conditions were reported along U.S. 64/87.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By 1000 am CST, the weather was rapidly changing. Northern and western sections of Arkansas had temperatures in the 20s and 30s. It was 26 degrees at Fayetteville (Washington County) and 28 degrees at Harrison (Boone County). Given northwest winds at 15 to 20 mph and some gusts over 30 mph, wind chill index values were in the single digits at several locations. Meanwhile, it was still 59 degrees at Monticello (Drew County) and 57 degrees at West Memphis (Crittenden County).||At this time, drier air mostly shut off rain across the southern counties. Farther north/west, there was enough moisture to keep precipitation going. As temperatures dropped, it was cold enough for snow.  ||One to three inches of snow was common across the north and west. There were spotty reports of more than four inches, and isolated instances of half foot accumulations.|The highest amounts included 7 inches at Big Flat (Baxter County), 6 inches at Booneville (Logan County), 5 inches at Hardy (Sharp County) and Pocahontas (Randolph County), and 4 inches at Mansfield (Scott County), Marshall (Searcy County), Mountain View (Stone County), and Mount Magazine (Logan County).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A report was received of 1 inch of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed across the south central United States during the daylight hours of January 12th as high pressure was positioned over the northeastern United States and southeastern Canada. The low pressure system then tracked into the southeastern United States during the overnight hours of January 12th and moved northeastward offshore near the Outer Banks of North Carolina through the day of January 13th. Widespread accumulating snow affected the state of Maryland, with the highest totals south and west of Baltimore.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 4 to 5 inches were observed across northern Baltimore County, with a maximum of 4.7 inches measured near Glyndon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong short wave trough pivoted across a moderately unstable airmass during the afternoon that triggered a few severe storms. Strong speed shear  in the low and levels combined with cool temperatures aloft favored storm impacts of gusty winds 40-60 mph and hail.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 4 and 5 inches fell in just 3 hours, especially over the western sections of the citiy of St. Louis. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Three snowmobilers near Circleville Mountain triggered an avalanche, and one of them was killed in the accident.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three snowmobilers near Circleville Mountain triggered an 800-foot-wide avalanche, and two snowmobilers were caught, while the third made it to the bottom unharmed. One snowmobiler caught in the avalanche was able to dig out, and another was fully buried under 1-2 feet of snow. A search and rescue team was dispatched late in the afternoon, but was unable to continue operations overnight.  The buried snowmobiler was found the following morning.

CZ_NAME: SOUTHERN MONTEREY BAY AND BIG SUR COAST
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Monterey local 18 year old fell off a cliff at Garrapata State Park Saturday morning January 12 while hiking. After a few crashes of the waves his friends were unable to locate him.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A Monterey local 18-year old man fell off a cliff at Garrapata State Park around 11:44 Saturday morning and into the Pacific Ocean. According to Coast Guard spokeswoman Emily Rowan, the 18-year old fell off a cliff at Garrapata Beach while hiking with two friends. According to the search report, the two friends initially saw the man put a thumbs up after he fell, but after a few crashes of the waves they were unable to locate him. News article https://www.ksbw.com/article/search-suspended-for-18-year-old-man-who-fell-off-cliff-at-garrapata-beach/25874389.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system reached Lower Michigan on January 28th.  Blizzard conditions were common from North Dakota to southern Wisconsin, with snow falling heavily in Lower Michigan on the 28th. Snowfall totals were generally from 4 to 10 inches, with a stripe of higher amounts along and north of Highway 10.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Seven to eleven inches was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed across the south central United States during the daylight hours of January 12th as high pressure was positioned over the northeastern United States and southeastern Canada. The low pressure system then tracked into the southeastern United States during the overnight hours of January 12th and moved northeastward offshore near the Outer Banks of North Carolina through the day of January 13th. Widespread accumulating snow affected northern and central Virginia, with the highest totals in northern Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 6 to 8 inches were observed across southern Fauquier County, with 8.3 inches being reported near Opal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Outflow boundaries from convection across central Lower Michigan and subtle shortwaves passing through the region caused thunderstorms to develop. High CAPE values but low shear allowed the storms to form quickly but struggle to organize. Eventually, greater DCAPE values arrive with one of the waves and caused more extensive wind damage in a few locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported a large tree branch was blown down at the intersection of CR 10 and R.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rapid clearing and very wet low levels in the wake of an atmospheric river event led to areas of dense fog in many of the lower valleys.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dense fog was observed at the Rifle Garfield County Airport with visibility at or below a quarter mile for several hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Three snowmobilers near Chalk Creek triggered an avalanche and one of them was killed in the accident.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three snowmobilers were riding near Chalk Creek when one of them triggered a 1000- foot-wide avalanche and was buried in the snow. The other two snowmobilers immediately began search and rescue operations and located the buried snowmobiler after approximately 30 minutes. The buried snowmobiler was dug out of the snow and was found breathless, CPR was initiated and life flight helicopters were dispatched to the scene and arrived within 40 minutes. The snowmobiler was taken to Evanston Hospital and pronounced dead due to traumatic injury.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Utah's first significant winter storm of 2019 entered the state on January 6 and brought heavy snowfall to both valley and mountain locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snowfall amounts included 12 inches in Logan, 11 inches in Wellsville, and 7 inches in Smithfield.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deepening low pressure lifted across Iowa and Minnesota, passing west of Michigan. Moisture surged northward into northern Michigan on the 7th, ahead of the low. Precipitation started everywhere as snow, but in northern lower Michigan turned to sleet, freezing rain, and then rain. The heaviest wintry precipitation fell in eastern upper Michigan, almost all in the form of snow. Snowfall totals of 10 to 16 inches were common in northern and eastern Mackinac County, and all of Chippewa County. Drummond Island reached 18 inches.

Strong west to northwest winds trailing the January 20th storm drew cold air across Southern New England on January 21st and caused wind chill values of 25 below zero or colder in Central and Western Massachusetts.  The wind diminished during the afternoon and evening of of January 21st allowing wind chill values to become less extreme, in the teens below zero.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Automated Surface Observing System platform at Westfield-Barnes Regional Airport reported wind chill values as low as 28 degrees below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moving north from the Gulf of Mexico brought high south winds and heavy rain to the coastal waters of Massachusetts and Rhode Island on January 24th. The storm moved off through the Maritimes by the next morning.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At 11 AM EST the marine mesonet station at Borden Flats Light reported a wind gust to 58 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dense fog formed after midnight on the east side of Austin and contributed to a 20-40 vehicle accident. Six people were taken to hospitals as a result.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dense fog formed after midnight on the east side of Austin and contributed to a 20-40 vehicle accident. Six people were taken to hospitals as a result. Visibility improved shortly after 3 am.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A snow mobiler died in an avalanche that occurred around 6 pm on the 25th near Palisades Lake in Bonneville County near the Wyoming border.  A 35 year old male died din the avalanche that occurred near Palisades Lake.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A snowmobiler died in an avalanche that occurred around 6 pm on the 25th near Palisades Lake in Bonneville County near the Wyoming border. A 35 year old male died din the avalanche that occurred near Palisades Lake.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dense fog was partially responsible for a train ans SUV crash on US 20 near mile post 343 south of Saint Anthony.   The vehicle failed to yield to a train.   Several other vehicles went off the road.   The accident caused the road to be backed up for miles.   Idaho State Police were forced to divert traffic.  No injuries occurred due to the accident.  The accident with the train and SUV occurred around noon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong and gusty elevated winds from the west entered a favorable environment which allowed them to reach the surface near higher elevation areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At the Malta South US-191 DOT site, sustained winds of 40 mph lasted for little more than an hour at a time, but a few minutes of 60 mph gusts were measured in the noon hour.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta clipper moved through the region.  It's associated cold front allowed the stronger winds aloft to reach all the way down to the surface for a number of locations across northeast Montana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Malta South US-191 DOT site measured sustained winds near and above 40 mph for only one hour in the morning and a few minutes in the afternoon, but an initial wind gust of 58 mph was recorded at 7:50 AM.  The peak wind gust of 63 mph was recorded at 8:00 AM.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system reached Lower Michigan on January 28th.  Blizzard conditions were common from North Dakota to southern Wisconsin, with snow falling heavily in Lower Michigan on the 28th. Snowfall totals were generally from 4 to 10 inches, with a stripe of higher amounts along and north of Highway 10.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Seven to ten inches was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moderate to severe drought conditions across portions of western and central New Mexico at the end of December 2018 improved only slightly through January 2019. However, exceptional drought conditions over the northwestern half of the state improved significantly for January. Severe drought conditions improved to 33 percent of the state, of which around 15 percent was deemed extreme drought or worse. Exceptional drought improved to roughly 1 percent of New Mexico. Precipitation amounts for January 2019 ranged from around one half inch to three inches of parts of central and northern New Mexico. Several winter storm systems that moved across the state at the end of December 2018 and the beginning of January 2019 brought much needed snowfall to the region, especially across the northwest. Snow pack conditions continued to improve across the northern mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Exceptional drought conditions from December 2018 for areas around Gallup improved to extreme in January 2019.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front approached the area during the day and into the evening of January 7th as a strong area of high pressure remained positioned off the Northeastern US coastline. Warm and moist air overrunning much cooler air at the surface led to areas of precipitation, some of which fell as light freezing rain across the terrain near the Allegheny Front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trace amounts of freezing rain were reported across western Mineral County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By 1000 am CST, the weather was rapidly changing. Northern and western sections of Arkansas had temperatures in the 20s and 30s. It was 26 degrees at Fayetteville (Washington County) and 28 degrees at Harrison (Boone County). Given northwest winds at 15 to 20 mph and some gusts over 30 mph, wind chill index values were in the single digits at several locations. Meanwhile, it was still 59 degrees at Monticello (Drew County) and 57 degrees at West Memphis (Crittenden County).||At this time, drier air mostly shut off rain across the southern counties. Farther north/west, there was enough moisture to keep precipitation going. As temperatures dropped, it was cold enough for snow.  ||One to three inches of snow was common across the north and west. There were spotty reports of more than four inches, and isolated instances of half foot accumulations.|The highest amounts included 7 inches at Big Flat (Baxter County), 6 inches at Booneville (Logan County), 5 inches at Hardy (Sharp County) and Pocahontas (Randolph County), and 4 inches at Mansfield (Scott County), Marshall (Searcy County), Mountain View (Stone County), and Mount Magazine (Logan County).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A report was received of 7.0 inches of snow at Big Flat.

CZ_NAME: SALISBURY SOUND TO CAPE FAIRWEATHER COASTAL AREA
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Deepening storm center tracked into the Eastern Gulf on Sunday evening 4/21 then stalled in the NE Gulf through Mon morning. High winds reached the SW coast of Prince of Wales by midnight then Ketchikan and Edna Bay through early Monday morning. The high winds will continued to move northward through the day as the strong low level jet 70 KT moved north. High pressure building in after the system made the winds persist into Tuesday for the inner channels with a large swell moving onto the outer coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gusts to 75 MPH occurred during the late morning at Cape Spencer on 4/22. No damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wet pattern continued heading into the middle of the month. Another storm system approached from the southwest on the 11th, and produced mainly rain across the region.  This led to some flooding on the White and Cache Rivers.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooding began on the White River at Clarendon on 1/12 and continued through the end of the month.

In the predawn hours of the 23rd, rain started tapering off from the west. ||As far as rainfall, one to more than two inches of liquid was common in much of southern, central, and eastern Arkansas. CZ_NAME: FOUR CORNERS / UPPER DOLORES RIVER BASIN
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rapid clearing and very wet low levels in the wake of an atmospheric river event led to areas of dense fog in many of the lower valleys.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dense fog was observed at an automated Colorado Department of Transportation sensor as visibility dropped down to 0.3 miles.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The unsettled, progressive weather pattern continued across eastern Utah during the month of March as numerous disturbances moved through. As a result of the wetter than normal conditions the state of the drought improved across the region, most notably in the Four Corners which finally eradicated the remaining severe (D2) drought conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The remaining severe (D2) drought conditions along the southern tier of the forecast zone improved to the moderate (D1) category by the end of the month. Elsewhere, the moderate conditions improved to the abnormally dry (D0) category.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved across Michigan from southwest to northeast on the 23rd. Wintry precipitation came in two waves. The first brought a few inches of snow to the area on the evening of the 22nd. Then, after a lull overnight, precipitation rates ramped up again during the day on the 23rd. Total snowfall amounts of 7 to 12 inches were common, over a fairly small portion of eastern upper and far northern lower Michigan. The highest amount, around 14 inches, fell near Royston in Montmorency County.

Widespread accumulating snow affected the state of Maryland, with the highest totals south and west of Baltimore.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 7 to 12 inches were observed across Anne Arundel County, with a maximum of 11.9 inches measured near Chelsea Beach.

Widespread accumulating snow affected the state of Maryland, with the highest totals south and west of Baltimore.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 5 to 9 inches were observed across southern Baltimore County, with a maximum of 9.3 inches measured near Towson.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant winter storm affected southeast Idaho for several days with heavy snow and strong winds creating closed roads, multiple traffic accidents and many school closings on January 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A strong winter storm produced heavy snowfall and very strong winds making travel extremely hazardous.  A semi-truck and snow plow got in an accident on interstate 15 six miles south of Dubois on the 7th.   Clark County School District 161 closed on January 7th due to the dangerous travel conditions.   The COOP observer 6 miles north of Small recorded 6.3 inches of snow from the storm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moderate to severe drought conditions across portions of western and central New Mexico at the end of December 2018 improved only slightly through January 2019. However, exceptional drought conditions over the northwestern half of the state improved significantly for January. Severe drought conditions improved to 33 percent of the state, of which around 15 percent was deemed extreme drought or worse. Exceptional drought improved to roughly 1 percent of New Mexico. Precipitation amounts for January 2019 ranged from around one half inch to three inches of parts of central and northern New Mexico. Several winter storm systems that moved across the state at the end of December 2018 and the beginning of January 2019 brought much needed snowfall to the region, especially across the northwest. Snow pack conditions continued to improve across the northern mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Exceptional drought conditions from December 2018 improved to extreme in January 2019. Far eastern portions of the area remained in exceptional drought.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broad upper level low and surface low reflection made their way off the Rockies and into the central and southern Plains. The upper level and surface features generally slide eastward across southern and central Missouri on the 12th of January, leaving Iowa in the wrap around and deformation regions of the low. Temperatures were generally of little issue with surface and above surface temperatures below freezing, resulting in snow from onset to finish of the event. Initially, indications were for the event to primarily be sub-warning criteria (6 inches in 12 hours, or 8 inches in 24 hours), but out performed initial forecasts to the tune of 10 to 14 inches in select areas and widespread 6 to 8 inches or more across the southern 3 tiers of the state.

Moist and moderately fast southwest flow out ahead of and with the passage of a Pacific trough produced significant snow over the mountains of western Colorado. Some of the southern, central and northern valleys also received moderate snowfall. The presence of a strong subtropical jet aloft provided additional support as well as gusty winds at the surface which led to areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 4 to 5.5 inches of snow fell across the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the morning of January 19th, a low pressure system was located across the lower Mississippi Valley. This moved northeastward through the day and by the evening of the 19th was located across eastern Kentucky and Tennessee, intensifying to 994 mb as it did so. Overnight, the low tracked across Virginia and by mid morning on January 20th it was located near Philadelphia and had strengthened further to 988 mb. As it crossed the region, the system brought widespread rain to central and northern Virginia, although trace amounts of ice were reported across the Blue Ridge and in western and far northwestern Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trace amounts of ice were observed across the central Virginia Blue Ridge.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Utah's first significant winter storm of 2019 entered the state on January 6 and brought heavy snowfall to both valley and mountain locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snowfall amounts included 18 inches in Liberty, 11.1 inches at the Deer Creek Dam, 11 inches in Heber City, 8 inches in Jeremy Ranch. For the calendar day of January 7, Deer Creek Dam recorded 7 inches of snow, tying the calendar day record recorded in 1964.

CZ_NAME: JUNEAU BOROUGH AND NORTHERN ADMIRALTY ISLAND
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Modified arctic air had moved over the Panhandle on 1/9 and 1/10 due to offshore flow from colder regions in Canada. Some temperatures had lowered to zero to +10F.  On 1/10 there was a burst of warm moist air that moved over the Panhandle from the south causing numerous winter weather advisories to be issued. Warnings were issued for both the Juneau and Hyder areas due to heavy snow. Impacts: intense snow removal, poor driving conditions, and travel disrupted. The Juneau School District closed schools. ||Details: Bands of snow set up over the central panhandle with the core over Juneau over an extended period of time. Outside of Juneau bands caused heavy snow in Gustavus, Hoonah, Tenakee Springs and Angoon. Prior to the snow reaching the central panhandle, snow fell across the south, changing to rain in Ketchikan and Hydaburg on time, but lasting longer over from Coffman Cove to Edna Bay north. The main low center remained over the far SE gulf/SW of Sitka. This caused NELY flow through inside passages including Klawock/Angoon and down Chatham Strait which kept surface temperatures colder longer, even through temperatures aloft were warming. The prolonged NE flow kept Angoon as below freezing until about noon Friday the 11th, at this time the low was moving inland and weakening. The wind shifted for Angoon enough to change to rain, but remained cold enough for snow to continue in the Juneau area through 4pm Friday. However, during the day Friday the flakes became more icy or pellets, which caused the light fluffy snow that had fallen all day Thursday to compact down significantly and limit additional depth - altough observers in Angoon and Hoonah noting still needing to clear a lot of snow off their vehicles multiple times.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow for the Juneau area, 1/10 to 1/12 was 11 to 17 inches. Outlying areas may have gotten up to 20 inches in this storm. Impact was intense snow removal. Driving conditions were impassable in some instance. Public schools were closed in Juneau on 1/11.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were downed on Park Avenue.
