EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved across Michigan from southwest to northeast on the 23rd. Wintry precipitation came in two waves. The first brought a few inches of snow to the area on the evening of the 22nd. Then, after a lull overnight, precipitation rates ramped up again during the day on the 23rd. Total snowfall amounts of 7 to 12 inches were common, over a fairly small portion of eastern upper and far northern lower Michigan. The highest amount, around 14 inches, fell near Royston in Montmorency County.
A very strong jet stream combined with tight surface pressure gradients resulted in high winds across the western half of the Billings Forecast Area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant winter storm affected southeast Idaho for several days with heavy snow and strong winds creating closed roads, multiple traffic accidents and many school closings on January 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall and very strong winds caused extremely difficult travel in the Upper Snake River Plain .  The following schools were closed on January 7th due to road conditions caused by the snow and wind:  Madison School District 321, Fremont School District 215, Sugar-Salem Joint School District 322, Ririe School District 252.  Snow amounts were not extraordinarily heavy with COOP observers reporting 3 inches in Rigby and 4.5 inches in Hamer.  US Highway 26 was closed from Ririe to Swan Valley due to the snow and wind on the 7th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant winter storm affected southeast Idaho for several days with heavy snow and strong winds creating closed roads, multiple traffic accidents and many school closings on January 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very strong winds combined with snowfall caused the West Jefferson School District 253 and the Butte County School District 111 to close on January 7th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta clipper moved through the region.  It's associated cold front allowed the stronger winds aloft to reach all the way down to the surface for a number of locations across northeast Montana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Cooperative observer reported that his private weather station first recorded a 65 mph wind gust at 7:52 PM MST, then a peak wind gust of 66 mph sometime after 9:00 PM MST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta clipper moved through the region.  It's associated cold front allowed the stronger winds aloft to reach all the way down to the surface for a number of locations across northeast Montana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The McDonalds MT-13 DOT site measured sustained winds of at least 40 mph each hour from 2:01 PM MST through 6:47 PM MST.  An initial wind gust of 61 mph was recorded at 6:07 PM.  The peak wind gust of 68 mph was recorded at 6:16 PM and 6:17 PM.  Other shorter periods of 40 mph winds occurred later that evening.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system reached Lower Michigan on January 28th.  Blizzard conditions were common from North Dakota to southern Wisconsin, with snow falling heavily in Lower Michigan on the 28th. Snowfall totals were generally from 4 to 10 inches, with a stripe of higher amounts along and north of Highway 10.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Twelve to sixteen inches was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moderate to severe drought conditions across portions of western and central New Mexico at the end of December 2018 improved only slightly through January 2019. However, exceptional drought conditions over the northwestern half of the state improved significantly for January. Severe drought conditions improved to 33 percent of the state, of which around 15 percent was deemed extreme drought or worse. Exceptional drought improved to roughly 1 percent of New Mexico. Precipitation amounts for January 2019 ranged from around one half inch to three inches of parts of central and northern New Mexico. Several winter storm systems that moved across the state at the end of December 2018 and the beginning of January 2019 brought much needed snowfall to the region, especially across the northwest. Snow pack conditions continued to improve across the northern mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe drought conditions from December 2018 continued through January 2019.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broad upper level low and surface low reflection made their way off the Rockies and into the central and southern Plains. The upper level and surface features generally slide eastward across southern and central Missouri on the 12th of January, leaving Iowa in the wrap around and deformation regions of the low. Temperatures were generally of little issue with surface and above surface temperatures below freezing, resulting in snow from onset to finish of the event. Initially, indications were for the event to primarily be sub-warning criteria (6 inches in 12 hours, or 8 inches in 24 hours), but out performed initial forecasts to the tune of 10 to 14 inches in select areas and widespread 6 to 8 inches or more across the southern 3 tiers of the state.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough was diving through the Great Basin with a strong surface low developing over eastern Colorado. An upper level jet in excess of 100 knots was over the region.  These features helped to contribute to strong southwest winds developing over the region with a peak wind of 80 mph reported at San Augustin Pass.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak gust of 80 mph was reported at San Augustin Pass at 235 PM.  Other gusts in the zone included 68 mph one mile southeast and one mile northwest of the White Sands Missile Range Main Post, 60 mph seven miles southwest of Northrup Strip and at Condron Field.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the morning of January 19th, a low pressure system was located across the lower Mississippi Valley. This moved northeastward through the day and by the evening of the 19th was located across eastern Kentucky and Tennessee, intensifying to 994 mb as it did so. Overnight, the low tracked across Virginia and by mid morning on January 20th it was located near Philadelphia and had strengthened further to 988 mb. As it crossed the region, the system brought widespread rain to central and northern Virginia, although trace amounts of ice were reported across the Blue Ridge and in western and far northwestern Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trace amounts of ice were observed across Frederick County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed across the south central United States during the daylight hours of January 12th as high pressure was positioned over the northeastern United States and southeastern Canada. The low pressure system then tracked into the southeastern United States during the overnight hours of January 12th and moved northeastward offshore near the Outer Banks of North Carolina through the day of January 13th. Widespread accumulating snow affected eastern West Virginia, with the highest totals near the I-81 corridor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 4 to 7 inches were observed across eastern Mineral County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong short wave trough pivoted across a moderately unstable airmass during the afternoon that triggered a few severe storms. Strong speed shear in the low and levels combined with cool temperatures aloft favored storm impacts of gusty winds 40-60 mph and hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The St. Augustine CMAN station SAUF1 measured a wind gust to 40 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist and moderately fast southwest flow out ahead of and with the passage of a Pacific trough produced significant snow over the mountains of western Colorado. Some of the southern, central and northern valleys also received moderate snowfall. The presence of a strong subtropical jet aloft provided additional support as well as gusty winds at the surface which led to areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 2 to 6 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts of 8 to 9 inches near Glenwood Springs and Gypsum. Winds gusted from 30 to 35 MPH. The Roaring Fork School District cancelled classes for the day on February 6th due to the snow.

CZ_NAME: INNER CHANNELS FROM KUPREANOF ISLAND TO ETOLIN ISLAND
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Modified arctic air had moved over the Panhandle on 1/9 and 1/10 due to offshore flow from colder regions in Canada. Some temperatures had lowered to zero to +10F.  On 1/10 there was a burst of warm moist air that moved over the Panhandle from the south causing numerous winter weather advisories to be issued. Warnings were issued for both the Juneau and Hyder areas due to heavy snow. Impacts: intense snow removal, poor driving conditions, and travel disrupted. The Juneau School District closed schools. ||Details: Bands of snow set up over the central panhandle with the core over Juneau over an extended period of time. Outside of Juneau bands caused heavy snow in Gustavus, Hoonah, Tenakee Springs and Angoon. Prior to the snow reaching the central panhandle, snow fell across the south, changing to rain in Ketchikan and Hydaburg on time, but lasting longer over from Coffman Cove to Edna Bay north. The main low center remained over the far SE gulf/SW of Sitka. This caused NELY flow through inside passages including Klawock/Angoon and down Chatham Strait which kept surface temperatures colder longer, even through temperatures aloft were warming. The prolonged NE flow kept Angoon as below freezing until about noon Friday the 11th, at this time the low was moving inland and weakening. The wind shifted for Angoon enough to change to rain, but remained cold enough for snow to continue in the Juneau area through 4pm Friday. However, during the day Friday the flakes became more icy or pellets, which caused the light fluffy snow that had fallen all day Thursday to compact down significantly and limit additional depth - altough observers in Angoon and Hoonah noting still needing to clear a lot of snow off their vehicles multiple times.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Petersburg had a storm total 12 inches. Wrangell had a storm total 7 inches then turned to rain.  Impact was intense snow removal and poor travel conditions.

CZ_NAME: JUNEAU BOROUGH AND NORTHERN ADMIRALTY ISLAND
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong arctic high pressure built into the Yukon Territory on 1/31 through 2/1. This caused a Taku wind event for Downtown Juneau and Douglas on the evening of 1/31 into the morning of 2/1. One gust at the AJ Dock got to 90 mph. No damage was reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: On 1/31 at 2048, SDIA2 wind gust 65 mph. At 2/1 0213 JLXA2 (library) observed a wind gust 61 mph.  At 2/1 0302 AJ Dock gust 90 mph. No damage reported anywhere. Impact was that the LeConte of the AMHS canceled sailing for Lynn Canal on 1/31 and 2/1.

CZ_NAME: FLAGLER BEACH TO VOLUSIA-BREVARD COUNTY LINE 0-20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong squall line rapidly advanced across and offshore the central Florida peninsula during the morning, resulting in wind gusts of 34 knots or more in numerous locations along the coast from Brevard County to Martin County. A waterspout was also sighted offshore of Hobe Sound.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mesonet site located two miles north-northwest of Ormond-by-the-Sea measured a peak wind gust of 34 knots from the west as a squall line crossed into the nearshore waters.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disorganized trough of low pressure moved over the region starting late in the morning of the 21st and then exited the area during the mid-morning hours of the 22nd. While snow was seen across much of the Northland, a concentrated area of snow was seen from Cass County eastward to the Duluth and Two Harbors area. Snowfall totals in this band ended up in the 8 to 10 inch range while the remainder of the area was below 6.

Storm totals included:  16 inches at Lake Irene, 13 inches at Never Summer, 11.5 at Arapahoe Ridge, 11 inches at Buffalo Park and Loveland; 8 inches at Deadman Hill and Roach; with 4 to 7 inches elsewhere.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By 1000 am CST, the weather was rapidly changing. Northern and western sections of Arkansas had temperatures in the 20s and 30s. It was 26 degrees at Fayetteville (Washington County) and 28 degrees at Harrison (Boone County). Given northwest winds at 15 to 20 mph and some gusts over 30 mph, wind chill index values were in the single digits at several locations. Meanwhile, it was still 59 degrees at Monticello (Drew County) and 57 degrees at West Memphis (Crittenden County).||At this time, drier air mostly shut off rain across the southern counties. Farther north/west, there was enough moisture to keep precipitation going. As temperatures dropped, it was cold enough for snow.  ||One to three inches of snow was common across the north and west. There were spotty reports of more than four inches, and isolated instances of half foot accumulations.|The highest amounts included 7 inches at Big Flat (Baxter County), 6 inches at Booneville (Logan County), 5 inches at Hardy (Sharp County) and Pocahontas (Randolph County), and 4 inches at Mansfield (Scott County), Marshall (Searcy County), Mountain View (Stone County), and Mount Magazine (Logan County).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A report was received of 4.5 inches of snow in Pocahontas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Utah's first significant winter storm of 2019 entered the state on January 6 and brought heavy snowfall to both valley and mountain locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Kodachrome Basin State Park received 7.8 inches of snow on January 6, breaking the previous calendar day record of 6 inches recorded in 2016. For the day, Kodachrome Basin State Park received 0.48 inches of liquid equivalent precipitation, also breaking the previous calendar day record of 0.45 inches recorded in 2016.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Utah's first significant winter storm of 2019 entered the state on January 6 and brought heavy snowfall to both valley and mountain locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snowfall amounts included 11 inches in Alpine, 4.8 inches in Lehi, and 4.5 inches at Woodland Hills. The Provo BYU COOP observer site received 0.65 inches of liquid equivalent precipitation on January 6, breaking the calendar day record of 0.49 inches recorded in 1988.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disorganized trough of low pressure moved over the region starting late in the morning of the 21st and then exited the area during the mid-morning hours of the 22nd. While snow was seen across much of the Northland, a concentrated area of snow was seen from Cass County eastward to the Duluth and Two Harbors area. Snowfall totals in this band ended up in the 8 to 10 inch range while the remainder of the area was below 6.

This was the second day of a prolonged cold period across the CWA. Overnight lows dropped into the 20s and 30s below zero under mainly clear skies with wind chills in 30s and 40s below zero. Some clouds started moving in after midnight capping the cooling and preventing many locations from cooling into warning criteria. The clouds moved out shortly before sunrise allowing a secondary dip in temperatures and wind chills before warming above warning criteria.

High tides and surf brought large waves and coastal flooding to Southern California. Areas of the San Diego County coastline observed sets as high as 15 ft and significant coastal flooding due to the King Tides. Surf was less extreme in Orange County but received significant coastal flooding during this event. Many water rescues due to the high surf and rip currents, and extensive damage to the Ocean Beach Pier in San Diego County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: San Diego lifeguards reported sets as high as 15 ft during this 3 day period of high surf. In Ocean Beach, sets were as high as 10 ft, and the pier sustained extensive damage. The railings were broken on both sides of the pier, and it had to be closed down for an extended period of time for repairs.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An inside slider low moved into Southern California on January 21 and brought widespread precipitation and strong westerly winds to the region. A period of Santa Ana winds immediately followed the inside slider, and brought high winds to the region, especially in the mountain areas. The peak observed wind gust was 84 knots in Burns Canyon. Two people were killed when a large tree fell on their home in Point Loma in San Diego County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Broadcast media reported 2 fatalities when a large Torrey Pine tree fell over onto a home due to strong wind. Wind gusts were around 45 mph at the time of the event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant winter storm affected southeast Idaho for several days with heavy snow and strong winds creating closed roads, multiple traffic accidents and many school closings on January 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow and strong winds occurred for close to two days in the Centennial Mountains.  A storm total of 14 inches was reported by the COOP observer at Island Park.  Fremont County School District 215 was closed on January 7th due to the roads.  Idaho Highway 47 was closed from Ashton to Warm River.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant winter storm affected southeast Idaho for several days with heavy snow and strong winds creating closed roads, multiple traffic accidents and many school closings on January 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Teton County School District 401 closed on January 7th due to snow and strong winds.  Snow amounts were estimated at 4 to 8 inches for the storm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moderate to severe drought conditions across portions of western and central New Mexico at the end of December 2018 improved only slightly through January 2019. However, exceptional drought conditions over the northwestern half of the state improved significantly for January. Severe drought conditions improved to 33 percent of the state, of which around 15 percent was deemed extreme drought or worse. Exceptional drought improved to roughly 1 percent of New Mexico. Precipitation amounts for January 2019 ranged from around one half inch to three inches of parts of central and northern New Mexico. Several winter storm systems that moved across the state at the end of December 2018 and the beginning of January 2019 brought much needed snowfall to the region, especially across the northwest. Snow pack conditions continued to improve across the northern mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Exceptional drought conditions from December 2018 improved to extreme drought in January 2019.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By 1000 am CST, the weather was rapidly changing. Northern and western sections of Arkansas had temperatures in the 20s and 30s. It was 26 degrees at Fayetteville (Washington County) and 28 degrees at Harrison (Boone County). Given northwest winds at 15 to 20 mph and some gusts over 30 mph, wind chill index values were in the single digits at several locations. Meanwhile, it was still 59 degrees at Monticello (Drew County) and 57 degrees at West Memphis (Crittenden County).||At this time, drier air mostly shut off rain across the southern counties. Farther north/west, there was enough moisture to keep precipitation going. As temperatures dropped, it was cold enough for snow.  ||One to three inches of snow was common across the north and west. There were spotty reports of more than four inches, and isolated instances of half foot accumulations.|The highest amounts included 7 inches at Big Flat (Baxter County), 6 inches at Booneville (Logan County), 5 inches at Hardy (Sharp County) and Pocahontas (Randolph County), and 4 inches at Mansfield (Scott County), Marshall (Searcy County), Mountain View (Stone County), and Mount Magazine (Logan County).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A report was received of 2.0 inches of snow in Parthenon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broad upper level low and surface low reflection made their way off the Rockies and into the central and southern Plains. The upper level and surface features generally slide eastward across southern and central Missouri on the 12th of January, leaving Iowa in the wrap around and deformation regions of the low. Temperatures were generally of little issue with surface and above surface temperatures below freezing, resulting in snow from onset to finish of the event. Initially, indications were for the event to primarily be sub-warning criteria (6 inches in 12 hours, or 8 inches in 24 hours), but out performed initial forecasts to the tune of 10 to 14 inches in select areas and widespread 6 to 8 inches or more across the southern 3 tiers of the state.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Roads and highways were very slick across the county. Some accidents were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front crossed the Mid-Atlantic on the night of January 16th with high pressure building in across the northeastern United States. A wave of low pressure developing near the St. Louis area then moved eastward along the frontal boundary during the daytime hours of the 17th and into the eastern Great Lakes overnight. The combination of the cold air provided by the high pressure area to the north and the moisture and lift associated with the low pressure system generated widespread accumulating snow from late afternoon on January 17th and persisting through the first half of the night until precipitation ended and temperatures rose to near or above freezing.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 1 to 1.5 inches were observed across the District of Columbia, with 1.2 inches being reported near the National Zoo.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms pushed south across northern and central Ohio during the overnight hours ahead of a slow moving cold front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to four inches of rain caused flash flooding in the Montzuma area. State Route 127 was closed due to high water. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Outflow boundaries from convection across central Lower Michigan and subtle shortwaves passing through the region caused thunderstorms to develop. High CAPE values but low shear allowed the storms to form quickly but struggle to organize. Eventually, greater DCAPE values arrive with one of the waves and caused more extensive wind damage in a few locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency management officials reported trees and power lines were blown down. The doors from a barn were also removed.

Deepening low pressure lifted across Iowa and Minnesota, passing west of Michigan. Moisture surged northward into northern Michigan on the 7th, ahead of the low. Precipitation started everywhere as snow, but in northern lower Michigan turned to sleet, freezing rain, and then rain. The heaviest wintry precipitation fell in eastern upper Michigan, almost all in the form of snow. Snowfall totals of 10 to 16 inches were common in northern and eastern Mackinac County, and all of Chippewa County. Drummond Island reached 18 inches.

Low pressure moved across Michigan from southwest to northeast on the 23rd. Wintry precipitation came in two waves. The first brought a few inches of snow to the area on the evening of the 22nd. Then, after a lull overnight, precipitation rates ramped up again during the day on the 23rd. Total snowfall amounts of 7 to 12 inches were common, over a fairly small portion of eastern upper and far northern lower Michigan. The highest amount, around 14 inches, fell near Royston in Montmorency County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure moved over Minnesota following a cold front that brought new snowfall to the area the following day. With cold, Canadian air pouring in, coupled with clear skies, light winds and fresh snow, temperatures plunged into the 30s below zero with wind chills in the 40s below zero. However, many areas were spared from the extreme wind chills as winds completely subsided during the time of coldest temperatures.

This was day 3 of a prolonged cold period across the CWA. A weak system had passed through the area during the day on the 26th with a reinforcing shot of cold air arriving behind it. Skies cleared out by early evening with temperatures dropping into the 20s and 30s below zero over a wide area. Winds were able to remain light through the night leading to wind chills of 40 to 50 below zero in many areas. Some areas remained at warning criteria until midday before warming above criteria.

Outflow boundaries from convection across central Lower Michigan and subtle shortwaves passing through the region caused thunderstorms to develop. High CAPE values but low shear allowed the storms to form quickly but struggle to organize. Eventually, greater DCAPE values arrive with one of the waves and caused more extensive wind damage in a few locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nine to ten inch diameter tree limbs were blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An inside slider low moved into Southern California on January 21 and brought widespread precipitation and strong westerly winds to the region. A period of Santa Ana winds immediately followed the inside slider, and brought high winds to the region, especially in the mountain areas. The peak observed wind gust was 84 knots in Burns Canyon. Two people were killed when a large tree fell on their home in Point Loma in San Diego County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Burns Canyon mesonet reported a peak wind gust of 84 knots between 0200 and 0300 PST on January 21st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta clipper moved through the region.  It's associated cold front allowed the stronger winds aloft to reach all the way down to the surface for a number of locations across northeast Montana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Comertown Turn-Off MT-5 DOT site measured sustained winds of 40 mph and above at least each hour between 2:02 PM MST and 5:49 PM MST.  The first wind gust of 58 mph was recorded from 2:47 PM to 2:49 PM.  The peak wind gust of 59 mph was recorded at 5:09 PM.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: At the US-2 @Stateline DOT site, sustained winds of 40 mph were measured at least each hour between 3:16 PM MST and 6:02 PM MST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist and moderately fast southwest flow out ahead of and with the passage of a Pacific trough produced significant snow over the mountains of western Colorado. Some of the southern, central and northern valleys also received moderate snowfall. The presence of a strong subtropical jet aloft provided additional support as well as gusty winds at the surface which led to areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 4 to 8 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts exceeding a foot at the North Lost Trail and Schofield Pass SNOTEL sites. Monarch Pass reported a peak wind gust of 67 MPH. Otherwise, winds gusted from 25 to 35 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed across the south central United States during the daylight hours of January 12th as high pressure was positioned over the northeastern United States and southeastern Canada. The low pressure system then tracked into the southeastern United States during the overnight hours of January 12th and moved northeastward offshore near the Outer Banks of North Carolina through the day of January 13th. Widespread accumulating snow affected northern and central Virginia, with the highest totals in northern Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 6 to 8 inches were observed across Shenandoah County, with 8.0 being reported near Clary.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta clipper moved through the region.  It's associated cold front allowed the stronger winds aloft to reach all the way down to the surface for a number of locations across northeast Montana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Beaver Hill I-94 DOT site, measured sustained winds of 40 mph and above at least each hour from 3:41 PM MST to 7:13 PM MST. An initial wind gust of 60 mph was recorded at 8:53 PM MST.  The peak wind gust of 61 mph was recorded at 9:04 PM MST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moderate to severe drought conditions across portions of western and central New Mexico at the end of December 2018 improved only slightly through January 2019. However, exceptional drought conditions over the northwestern half of the state improved significantly for January. Severe drought conditions improved to 33 percent of the state, of which around 15 percent was deemed extreme drought or worse. Exceptional drought improved to roughly 1 percent of New Mexico. Precipitation amounts for January 2019 ranged from around one half inch to three inches of parts of central and northern New Mexico. Several winter storm systems that moved across the state at the end of December 2018 and the beginning of January 2019 brought much needed snowfall to the region, especially across the northwest. Snow pack conditions continued to improve across the northern mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe drought conditions from December 2018 continued through January 2019.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By 1000 am CST, the weather was rapidly changing. Northern and western sections of Arkansas had temperatures in the 20s and 30s. It was 26 degrees at Fayetteville (Washington County) and 28 degrees at Harrison (Boone County). Given northwest winds at 15 to 20 mph and some gusts over 30 mph, wind chill index values were in the single digits at several locations. Meanwhile, it was still 59 degrees at Monticello (Drew County) and 57 degrees at West Memphis (Crittenden County).||At this time, drier air mostly shut off rain across the southern counties. Farther north/west, there was enough moisture to keep precipitation going. As temperatures dropped, it was cold enough for snow.  ||One to three inches of snow was common across the north and west. There were spotty reports of more than four inches, and isolated instances of half foot accumulations.|The highest amounts included 7 inches at Big Flat (Baxter County), 6 inches at Booneville (Logan County), 5 inches at Hardy (Sharp County) and Pocahontas (Randolph County), and 4 inches at Mansfield (Scott County), Marshall (Searcy County), Mountain View (Stone County), and Mount Magazine (Logan County).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer reported 3.5 inches of snow in the last 24 hours at Salem.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong complex of thunderstorms moved across the Eastern Gulf of Mexico before coming ashore across the Florida peninsula during the afternoon. Strong to severe thunderstorms produced widespread wind damage across west-central and southwest Florida along with a brief tornado as a waterspout moved ashore.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A home weather station at Sparks RC Flying Field measured a wind gust of 58 mph.

CZ_NAME: JUNEAU BOROUGH AND NORTHERN ADMIRALTY ISLAND
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Deepening storm center tracked into the Eastern Gulf on Sunday evening 4/21 then stalled in the NE Gulf through Mon morning. High winds reached the SW coast of Prince of Wales by midnight then Ketchikan and Edna Bay through early Monday morning. The high winds will continued to move northward through the day as the strong low level jet 70 KT moved north. High pressure building in after the system made the winds persist into Tuesday for the inner channels with a large swell moving onto the outer coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gusts to 60 MPH occurred during the early afternoon of 4/22 in Auke Bay. Damage was reported to the Allen Marine Dock and a window was broken on Shelter Island. Wind waves in Auke Bay caused dock  problems.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong short wave trough pivoted across a moderately unstable airmass during the afternoon that triggered a few severe storms. Strong speed shear in the low and levels combined with cool temperatures aloft favored storm impacts of gusty winds 40-60 mph and hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down across Highway 121 near mile marker 7. The cost of damage was unknown, but it was estimated for Storm Data inclusion.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front crossed the Mid-Atlantic on the night of January 16th with high pressure building in across the northeastern United States. A wave of low pressure developing near the St. Louis area then moved eastward along the frontal boundary during the daytime hours of the 17th and into the eastern Great Lakes overnight. The combination of the cold air provided by the high pressure area to the north and the moisture and lift associated with the low pressure system generated widespread accumulating snow from late afternoon on January 17th and persisting through the first half of the night until precipitation ended and temperatures rose to near or above freezing.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 1 to 2 inches were observed across Culpeper County, with 2.3 inches being reported near Rixeyville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the morning of January 19th, a low pressure system was located across the lower Mississippi Valley. This moved northeastward through the day and by the evening of the 19th was located across eastern Kentucky and Tennessee, intensifying to 994 mb as it did so. Overnight, the low tracked across Virginia and by mid morning on January 20th it was located near Philadelphia and had strengthened further to 988 mb. As it crossed the region, the system brought widespread precipitation, with mainly rain across central and southern Maryland, but accumulating snow and ice to areas near the Catoctin Mountains and points westward.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were observed across western Allegany County, with 5 inches being reported near Frostburg. A glaze of ice between a tenth and two tenths of an inch was also reported.

Freezing temperatures were observed across southeast Missouri. Low temperatures were in the upper 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

More heavy rain impacted the region shortly after the middle part of the month, once again causing the Ohio and Green Rivers to rise above flood stage by the end of January. The flooding was minor, consisting mostly of flooded bottomland fields, woodlands, and public park and recreation areas. Some lesser-traveled roads in the bottomlands were flooded. The flooding continued into February on the Ohio River.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust of 62 mph was recorded at Bitter Creek along Interstate 80. A 60 mph was recorded at the Snow Springs RAWS site.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By 1000 am CST, the weather was rapidly changing. Northern and western sections of Arkansas had temperatures in the 20s and 30s. It was 26 degrees at Fayetteville (Washington County) and 28 degrees at Harrison (Boone County). Given northwest winds at 15 to 20 mph and some gusts over 30 mph, wind chill index values were in the single digits at several locations. Meanwhile, it was still 59 degrees at Monticello (Drew County) and 57 degrees at West Memphis (Crittenden County).||At this time, drier air mostly shut off rain across the southern counties. Farther north/west, there was enough moisture to keep precipitation going. As temperatures dropped, it was cold enough for snow.  ||One to three inches of snow was common across the north and west. There were spotty reports of more than four inches, and isolated instances of half foot accumulations.|The highest amounts included 7 inches at Big Flat (Baxter County), 6 inches at Booneville (Logan County), 5 inches at Hardy (Sharp County) and Pocahontas (Randolph County), and 4 inches at Mansfield (Scott County), Marshall (Searcy County), Mountain View (Stone County), and Mount Magazine (Logan County).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer reported 1.5 inches of snow in Flippin.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist and moderately fast southwest flow out ahead of and with the passage of a Pacific trough produced significant snow over the mountains of western Colorado. Some of the southern, central and northern valleys also received moderate snowfall. The presence of a strong subtropical jet aloft provided additional support as well as gusty winds at the surface which led to areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 3 to 4 inches of snow fell across the area. Winds gusted up to 43 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the morning of January 19th, a low pressure system was located across the lower Mississippi Valley. This moved northeastward through the day and by the evening of the 19th was located across eastern Kentucky and Tennessee, intensifying to 994 mb as it did so. Overnight, the low tracked across Virginia and by mid morning on January 20th it was located near Philadelphia and had strengthened further to 988 mb. As it crossed the region, the system brought widespread rain to central and northern Virginia, although trace amounts of ice were reported across the Blue Ridge and in western and far northwestern Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trace amounts of ice were observed across western Highland County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong surface cold front crossed the region from west to east on January 29th. As it did so, a wave of low pressure developed along the frontal boundary over southwestern Virginia and moved northeastward to a position near Philadelphia by the evening of the 29th. This led to a rain and snow mix developing ahead of the cold front, but changing over to all snow following the frontal passage. In general, 1 to 3 inches of snow were observed across northern Virginia, with less amounts south and west.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 2 to 3 inches were observed across the northern Virginia Blue Ridge, with 3.0 inches measured near Panorama.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved up the eastern seaboard of the United States from January 8th through the 9th, with cold temperatures and strong northwest winds funneling behind the system and a secondary arctic front from the night of the 9th into the morning of the 10th. This was able to produce wind chill values as low as -10 degrees over the higher terrain near the Allegheny Front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The combination of cold temperatures and strong winds produced wind chills as low as -10 degrees.

A strong low pressure system moved from the Plains into the western Great Lakes on the 14th. This pushed a cold front through the middle Ohio River Valley that evening into the early hours of the 15th. Thunderstorms formed ahead of this front and tapped into very strong winds aloft to produce isolated tree and power line damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three power poles were snapped along Route 204 west of Thornville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: This was day 3 of a prolonged cold period across the CWA. A weak system had passed through the area during the day on the 26th with a reinforcing shot of cold air arriving behind it. Skies cleared out by early evening with temperatures dropping into the 20s and 30s below zero over a wide area. Winds were able to remain light through the night leading to wind chills of 40 to 50 below zero in many areas. Some areas remained at warning criteria until midday before warming above criteria.

Heavy rains toward the end of December sent the Ohio River above flood stage from December into the first part of January. The flooding was minor, consisting mostly of flooded bottomland fields, woodlands, and public park and recreation areas. Some lesser-traveled roads in the bottomlands were flooded.

More heavy rain impacted the region shortly after the middle part of the month, once again causing the Ohio and Green Rivers to rise above flood stage by the end of January. The flooding was minor, consisting mostly of flooded bottomland fields, woodlands, and public park and recreation areas. Some lesser-traveled roads in the bottomlands were flooded. The flooding continued into February on the Ohio River.

Freezing rain caused ice to develop on roadways in the Lower Snake River Plain and 2 inches of snow in the Upper Snake River Plain caused traffic issues as well.   Interstate 86 east bound was closed for two hours east of American Falls and Highway 20 east bound was shut down for over an hour between Idaho Falls and Ucon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain fell on the morning of the 10th from American Falls through the Pocatello area causing a glaze of ice to form on the roads.   A traffic accident due to the icy roads closed interstate 86 east bound for over two hours east of American Falls.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain caused ice to develop on roadways in the Lower Snake River Plain and 2 inches of snow in the Upper Snake River Plain caused traffic issues as well. EVENT_NARRATIVE: US Highway 20 was closed east bound from Idaho Falls to Ucon due to a  trailer flipping on a snow covered road.   Several slide offs and accidents were reported in the Idaho Falls area.  Although snowfall was not heavy, 2 to 2.5 inches of snow was reported in the Idaho Falls area and caused extensive traffic problems.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Some property and farmland flooding occurred south of Moore in Butte County on January 9th along the Big Lost River.  A land owner rescued his cattle from the flooding with none lost due to the flood.  Hay storage was also safely relocated.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Some property and farmland flooding occurred south of Moore in Butte County on January 9th along the Big Lost River. A land owner rescued his cattle from the flooding with none lost due to the flood. Hay storage was also safely relocated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wet Pacific system brought snow, freezing rain and rain with many changes in type in low elevations of the Snake River Plain during the three days with mostly snow in higher elevations.  Extensive travel problems were caused by the system with school closures on both the 17th and 18th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A long drawn out system brought a variety of weather to the Lower Snake River Plain.   Freezing rain caused schools to close on the 17th for Blackfoot School District 55 and Snake River School District 52.  Many private schools also closed in Blackfoot and Bingham County on the 17th.  Precipitation was rain for much of the 17th then changed to snow during the overnight and morning period of the 17th and 18th.   A burst of heavy snow brought 2 to 4 inches on the morning of the 18th to the Pocatello and Chubbuck and Fort Hall areas and the heavy snow on rain that froze caused very icy roads and Pocatello/Chubbuck School District 25 closed on the 18th.   Many other schools in Pocatello and Fort Hall also closed due to the conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure brought locally heavy snow to portions of western Wyoming. The heaviest snow fell in the Star Valley and Wyoming Range where over a foot of new snow fell in several locations. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure crossed Wyoming and brought heavy snow and strong wind to much of the area. The heaviest snow fell in the favored northerly upslope areas, including Casper and Lander where anywhere from 8 to 12 inches of snow was recorded. Close to a foot of snow also fell near Green River and Rock Springs. Over a foot fell in some of the adjacent mountains as well. The snow also combined with winds that gusted over 50 mph at times that lowered visibility to near zero at times. This led to the closure of many roads for several hours, including Interstates 80 and 25.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter measured 13 inches of snow in the foothills of the Wind River Mountains near Lander. In addition, a combination of snow and strong winds closed South Pass for several hours during the height of the storm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Deepening storm center tracked into the Eastern Gulf on Sunday evening 4/21 then stalled in the NE Gulf through Mon morning. High winds reached the SW coast of Prince of Wales by midnight then Ketchikan and Edna Bay through early Monday morning. The high winds will continued to move northward through the day as the strong low level jet 70 KT moved north. High pressure building in after the system made the winds persist into Tuesday for the inner channels with a large swell moving onto the outer coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gusts to 60 MPH occurred during the morning of 4/22 in Tenakee Springs. No damage was reported.

This led to a rain and snow mix developing ahead of the cold front, but changing over to all snow following the frontal passage. In general, 1 to 3 inches of snow were observed across central and northern Maryland, with very little to no snow reported in southern or western Maryland.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 1 to 2 inches were observed across Washington County, with 2.1 inches reported near Boonsboro.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist and moderately fast southwest flow out ahead of and with the passage of a Pacific trough produced significant snow over the mountains of eastern Utah as well as in the eastern Uinta Basin. The presence of a strong subtropical jet aloft provided additional support as well as gusty winds at the surface which led to areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 5 to 11 inches of snow fell across the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved across Michigan from southwest to northeast on the 23rd. Wintry precipitation came in two waves. The first brought a few inches of snow to the area on the evening of the 22nd. Then, after a lull overnight, precipitation rates ramped up again during the day on the 23rd. Total snowfall amounts of 7 to 12 inches were common, over a fairly small portion of eastern upper and far northern lower Michigan. The highest amount, around 14 inches, fell near Royston in Montmorency County.

Oppressive temperatures in the mid 90's to around 100 degrees along with dew point readings in the mid to upper 70's produced very dangerous heat conditions with heat index readings in excess of 105 degrees for much of the afternoon and early evening.||Some of the more extreme heat index readings experienced during the afternoon included 113 degrees at Wagner, 112 degrees at Le Mars, Canton and Mitchell, 111 degrees at Cherokee, Sioux City, Huron and Yankton, 110 degrees at Sioux Falls, Colton and White Lake, and 109 degrees near Beaver Creek.
With temperatures peaking in the mid to upper 90's and dew points in the lower to mid 70's, heat index values ranged from 100 to 108 during the afternoon and early evening hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Ample moisture and energy out ahead of and with the progression of a Pacific trough moving across the Great Basin brought widespread precipitation to western Colorado. Additionally, a secondary shortwave trough moved through in the southwesterly flow which enhanced orographic flow over the mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 6 to 12 inches of snow fell across the area with up to 14.4 inches estimated at the Ivanhoe SNOTEL site. Due to the hazardous road conditions, schools in Aspen School District 1 were cancelled on Friday, January 18th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A winter storm impacted northwestern Connecticut on January 19th and 20th. Low pressure formed over the lower Mississippi Valley and lifted northeast across the Tennessee Valley during the night of the 19th before moving along the Mason-Dixon line on the 20th. Strong rising motion occurred as southerly winds aloft transported moist air northward, which was lifted over the cold airmass in place over northwestern Connecticut. Snowfall broke out during the afternoon of the 19th, continuing heavy at times into the evening hours. The strong southerly flow brought above-freezing air aloft into the region, causing the snow to turn to sleet and freezing rain overnight into the early morning of the 20th before turning back to snow. Snow and sleet totals ranged from three to six inches with ice accretion of one to three tenths of an inch due to freezing rain. The freezing rain resulted in a handful of power outages over far southern parts of the county.||Frigid temperatures followed the snow for Monday and Tuesday, January 21st-22nd, with wind chills falling to -15 to -30F. The cold weather prompted the closing of schools and the opening of warming shelters across the region.

Following a heavy snowfall event on January 19-20 over much of eastern New York, a strong low pressure system tracking through southern Canada ushered in an unseasonably warm and moist airmass on January 24th. Temperatures surged into the 40s to mid-50s. Steady rainfall occurred during much of the 24th as a secondary low pressure system developed over the Mid-Atlantic and tracked into southern New England. One to two inches of rainfall occurred over much of the region, although a few reports of three to four inches were recorded over portions of the southern Adirondacks and the eastern Catskills. New daily rainfall records were set at Albany, Glens Falls, and Poughkeepsie.||The combination of the rainfall along with the mild temperatures melting some of the snow resulted in urban and poor drainage flooding over portions of the region along with minor to moderate river flooding in the Hoosic basin. Some ice jam flooding also occurred. Numerous road closures also occurred due to flooding in Washington County, NY. In addition, seven vessels along the Hudson River near Troy were ripped from their moorings during the early morning of the 25th, likely by a surge of water and ice from upstream. Some of these vessels struck bridges, resulting in bridge closures during the morning rush hour, including the Patroon Island Bridge which carries I-90 over the Hudson.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Route 213 was closed between Creek Locks Road and Mountain Road due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very heavy long period swell moved into the Oregon coastal waters, bringing heavy surf to the coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Buoy 46027 off of Point Saint George recorded swell sufficient to generate heavy surf with breaker heights up to 31 feet along the coast during this interval. Due to the travel time to the coast from the buoy, the heavy surf likely lasted a bit longer than recorded here.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Humidity was high across the southwestern deserts during the morning hours on January 7th, and conditions were favorable for the formation of fog. Dense fog developed across portions of the community of Yuma, aided by good radiational cooling and relatively light wind. According to members of the public, starting at about 0650MST visibility dropped to less than 1/4 mile in dense fog at Avenue B and 12th Street in Yuma. Shortly after that, visibility fell to 150 feet about 2 miles southwest of Yuma. A Dense Fog Advisory was in effect at the time of the reports and fortunately there were no reports of accidents due to the sharply reduced visibility and associated hazardous driving conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Humidity was high across the southwest deserts, and conditions were favorable for the formation of morning fog in the Yuma area. Dense fog developed in Yuma during the morning on January 7th; at 0650MST the public reported visibility less than 1/4 mile in dense fog at Avenue B and 12th Street. At 0700MST another member of the public reported that visibility had fallen to 150 feet in dense fog about 2 miles southwest of Yuma. A Dense Fog Advisory was in effect at the time of the reports and fortunately there were no accidents reported due to the sharply reduced visibility.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Humidity was high in the low levels of the atmosphere on January 7th, winds were light and skies were generally clear. These conditions set the stage for the formation of fog, and indeed, patchy dense fog developed across portions of the Imperial valley during the morning hours. At about 0800PST a member of the public reported visibility near 1/4 mile about 1 mile northwest of the town of Imperial. A Dense Fog Advisory was in effect at the time of the report. Fortunately there were no reports of accidents due to the sharply restricted visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High low level humidity, light winds and generally clear skies provided optimal conditions for the formation of fog, and indeed, patchy dense fog developed across portions of the Imperial Valley during the morning hours on January 7th. At 0710PST a member of the public reported that visibility had fallen to 1/4 mile in dense fog about 1 mile northwest of Imperial. A Dense Fog Advisory was in effect at the time of the report. No accidents were reported due to the sharply reduced visibility.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure system through the Ohio Valley produced a swath of accumulating snow and strong winds across the Lower Great Lakes region on Saturday, January 19th. Snow totals of 4 to 8 inches and wind gusts to near 40 mph created difficult travel conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to at times heavy snow developed during the morning hours of January 19th and continued through the rest of the day. Winds really picked up during the day, gusting between 30 and 40 mph during the afternoon and early evening hours. Snow accumulations across the county generally ranged between 4 and 6 inches, with significant blowing and drifting reported due to the strong winds. Hudson received 5.8 of total snow accumulation. Slide-offs and accidents were reported across the region. A few secondary roads were impassable due to the significant drifting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist air flowing over a wedge of cold air banked against the eastern slopes of the Appalachians resulted in precipitation development across the Blue Ridge and surrounding areas beginning during the evening of the 12th. The atmosphere quickly cooled to or below freezing near the escarpment and out across the lower elevations of the foothills and far northwest Piedmont. This resulted in much of the precipitation falling as freezing rain in these areas. The freezing rain continued through the overnight across the Blue Ridge and surrounding areas before tapering off around daybreak on the 13th. Total ice accretion of one quarter to one half inch was reported, with the heaviest amounts being across the foothills and immediately along the Blue Ridge escarpment. Scattered downed trees and power outages were reported throughout the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A winter storm impacted northwestern Connecticut on January 19th and 20th. Low pressure formed over the lower Mississippi Valley and lifted northeast across the Tennessee Valley during the night of the 19th before moving along the Mason-Dixon line on the 20th. Strong rising motion occurred as southerly winds aloft transported moist air northward, which was lifted over the cold airmass in place over northwestern Connecticut. Snowfall broke out during the afternoon of the 19th, continuing heavy at times into the evening hours. The strong southerly flow brought above-freezing air aloft into the region, causing the snow to turn to sleet and freezing rain overnight into the early morning of the 20th before turning back to snow. Snow and sleet totals ranged from three to six inches with ice accretion of one to three tenths of an inch due to freezing rain. The freezing rain resulted in a handful of power outages over far southern parts of the county.||Frigid temperatures followed the snow for Monday and Tuesday, January 21st-22nd, with wind chills falling to -15 to -30F. The cold weather prompted the closing of schools and the opening of warming shelters across the region.

An arctic cold front tracked through eastern New York during the afternoon of the 30th, accompanied by a heavy snow squall. Frigid air poured in behind this front along with strong westerly winds. Wind chills the morning of the 31st fell to 15 to 35 degrees below zero. The wind chills prompted many schools to close or delay opening, and there were several reports of water main breaks due to the cold.||In addition to the frigid temperatures, a heavy band of lake effect snow developed off of Lake Ontario and impacted far northern portions of Herkimer County from the evening of the 30th through the late evening of the 31st. Snowfall amounts of 8 to 12 inches occurred in this band.

Following a heavy snowfall event on January 19-20 over much of eastern New York, a strong low pressure system tracking through southern Canada ushered in an unseasonably warm and moist airmass on January 24th. Temperatures surged into the 40s to mid-50s. Steady rainfall occurred during much of the 24th as a secondary low pressure system developed over the Mid-Atlantic and tracked into southern New England. One to two inches of rainfall occurred over much of the region, although a few reports of three to four inches were recorded over portions of the southern Adirondacks and the eastern Catskills. New daily rainfall records were set at Albany, Glens Falls, and Poughkeepsie.||The combination of the rainfall along with the mild temperatures melting some of the snow resulted in urban and poor drainage flooding over portions of the region along with minor to moderate river flooding in the Hoosic basin. Some ice jam flooding also occurred. Numerous road closures also occurred due to flooding in Washington County, NY. In addition, seven vessels along the Hudson River near Troy were ripped from their moorings during the early morning of the 25th, likely by a surge of water and ice from upstream. Some of these vessels struck bridges, resulting in bridge closures during the morning rush hour, including the Patroon Island Bridge which carries I-90 over the Hudson.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Route 29 westbound was closed at Brook Road due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Erickson helicopter pilot was killed when his aircraft crashed in a wooded area near Interstate 5 at an elevation of 4100 feet.  The time of the crash is unknown, but it occurred in the morning and the pilot took off from Medford airport at 8:45 PST.    Weather conditions at the time included showers, low ceilings, obscuration of terrain, and significant mountain wave turbulence. The cause of the crash was unknown and will likely remain unknown at least until the investigation is complete.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong gusty southwest winds developed across portions of Imperial County during the morning hours on January 21st. The winds were not severe, but they were in excess of 40 mph and sufficient to warrant the issuance of Wind Advisories for favored areas in far southeast California. Gusty winds in excess of 40 mph managed to down a telephone pole near the town of Calexico, according to local law enforcement. No injuries were reported due to the falling telephone pole. Calexico was located well to the south of Imperial and just north of the Mexican border.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong gusty southwest winds developed across portions of far southeast California during the morning hours on January 21, and some of the stronger gusts affected the south portions of the Imperial Valley. According to local law enforcement, at 0700PST wind gusts estimated as high as 50 mph blew down a telephone pole near the town of Calexico. No injuries were reported due to the falling pole. A Wind Advisory was in effect for portions of far southeast California at the time but the advisory did not include the Imperial Valley.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level system produced a period of accumulating snow on Saturday January 12th. Snowfall amounts ranged between 3 and 5 inches north of US 30 to 4 to 8 inches south of US 30.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow, at times moderate to heavy, developed during the morning hours of January 12th and continued into the afternoon and early evening. Snow amounts of 5 to 8 inches were common across the county. There was a report of 7.8 inches 5 miles west of Chalmers. Visibilities were reduced to less than a half mile at times. Winds gusting to 30 mph also led to some blowing and drifting. There were reports of minor accidents and slide-offs across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful low pressure system affected much of the southwestern United States from February 20th through the 23rd. This storm was characterized by cold temperatures and very high snowfall totals across the Four Corners region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 16 to 22 inches of snow fell in the La Sal Mountains with 48 to 58 inches across the favored slopes of the Abajo Mountains. The cooperative observer located near Monticello reported 28 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure system through the Ohio Valley produced a swath of accumulating snow and strong winds across the Lower Great Lakes region on Saturday, January 19th. Snow totals of 4 to 8 inches and wind gusts to near 40 mph created difficult travel conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to at times heavy snow developed during the morning hours of January 19th and continued through the rest of the day. Winds really picked up during the day, gusting between 30 and 40 mph during the afternoon and early evening hours. Snow accumulations across the county generally ranged between 5 and 7 inches, with significant blowing and drifting reported due to the strong winds. James Lake received 6.5 of total snow accumulation. Slide-offs and accidents were reported across the region. A few secondary roads were impassable due to the significant drifting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing drizzle and freezing rain developed during the afternoon and early evening hours of January 22nd creating slick roads. Ice accretions of a glaze to one tenth of an inch were common across far northwest Ohio.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain and drizzle developed late in the afternoon on January 22nd and continued into the evening. Temperatures did warm above freezing into the morning of January 23rd while the rain continued, though sub-freezing road temperatures kept most secondary roads and sidewalks slick into January 23rd. There were numerous reports of slide-offs and accidents across the region. Many schools and businesses across the region were closed due to these icy road conditions.

Lingering moisture trapped underneath a surface inversion in the wake of a departing winter storm allowed dense fog to form across portions of western Colorado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dense fog was reported by an NWS employee 1 mile north of Grand Junction with visibility less than 1/4 mile.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Ample moisture and energy out ahead of and with the progression of a Pacific trough moving across the Great Basin brought widespread precipitation to western Colorado. Additionally, a secondary shortwave trough moved through in the southwesterly flow which enhanced orographic flow over the mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 6 to 9 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts nearing a foot around Craig and Hayden.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta Clipper brought heavy snow and gusty winds to Lower Michigan January 28th into early January 29th. Snow accumulations generally ranged between 4 and 9 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow overspread around daybreak on January 28th and continued through early January 29th. Some freezing drizzle did mix in during the late afternoon and evening hours. Total snow accumulations across the county ranged between 7 and 10 inches. A trained spotter 1 mile southwest of Fair Plain received 9.0 inches of snow. Gusty winds to near 30 mph led to considerable blowing and drifting snow which resulted in limited visibility and difficult travel. There were numerous school delays and cancellations, along with reports of accidents and slide-offs across the region.

An arctic cold front tracked through eastern New York during the afternoon of the 30th, accompanied by a heavy snow squall. Frigid air poured in behind this front along with strong westerly winds. Wind chills the morning of the 31st fell to 15 to 35 degrees below zero. The wind chills prompted many schools to close or delay opening, and there were several reports of water main breaks due to the cold.||In addition to the frigid temperatures, a heavy band of lake effect snow developed off of Lake Ontario and impacted far northern portions of Herkimer County from the evening of the 30th through the late evening of the 31st. Snowfall amounts of 8 to 12 inches occurred in this band.

Following a heavy snowfall event on January 19-20 over much of eastern New York, a strong low pressure system tracking through southern Canada ushered in an unseasonably warm and moist airmass on January 24th. Temperatures surged into the 40s to mid-50s. Steady rainfall occurred during much of the 24th as a secondary low pressure system developed over the Mid-Atlantic and tracked into southern New England. One to two inches of rainfall occurred over much of the region, although a few reports of three to four inches were recorded over portions of the southern Adirondacks and the eastern Catskills. New daily rainfall records were set at Albany, Glens Falls, and Poughkeepsie.||The combination of the rainfall along with the mild temperatures melting some of the snow resulted in urban and poor drainage flooding over portions of the region along with minor to moderate river flooding in the Hoosic basin. Some ice jam flooding also occurred. Numerous road closures also occurred due to flooding in Washington County, NY. In addition, seven vessels along the Hudson River near Troy were ripped from their moorings during the early morning of the 25th, likely by a surge of water and ice from upstream. Some of these vessels struck bridges, resulting in bridge closures during the morning rush hour, including the Patroon Island Bridge which carries I-90 over the Hudson.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Burch Hollow Road was closed between Burton Road and Easton Station Road due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong southerly flow combined with dynamic lifting and a cold air mass to bring heavy snow to parts of western and central Siskiyou county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A spotter 2SSW Weed reported 8 inches of snow between 05/1000 and 05/2400 PST, and 7 additional inches of snow between 06/0000 and 06/1500 PST for a storm total of 15 inches. A spotter in Mount Shasta City reported 7.0 inches of snow in 11 hours ending at 05/2200 PST. He later reported a storm total of 12.0 inches at 06/1800 PST.  A CoCoRAHs observer 5.1 NW Mount Shasta City reported 12.0 inches of snow in 24 hours at 06/1000 PST.  He reported another 6.5 inches by 07/1000 PST for a storm total of 18.5 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta Clipper brought heavy snow and gusty winds to Lower Michigan January 28th into early January 29th. Snow accumulations generally ranged between 3 and 8 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow overspread around daybreak on January 28th and continued through early January 29th. Some freezing drizzle did mix in during the late afternoon and evening hours. Total snow accumulations across the county ranged between 5 and 8 inches. La Porte received 6.5 inches of snow. Gusty winds to near 30 mph led to considerable blowing and drifting snow which resulted in limited visibility and difficult travel. There were numerous school delays and cancellations, along with reports of accidents and slide-offs across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure system through the Ohio Valley produced a swath of accumulating snow and strong winds across the region on Saturday, January 19th. Snow totals of 4 to 8 inches and wind gusts to near 40 mph created difficult travel conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to at times heavy snow developed during the morning hours of January 19th and continued through the rest of the day. Winds really pick up during the day, gusting between 35 and 45 mph during the afternoon and evening hours. Snow accumulations across the county generally ranged between 6 and 9 inches, with significant blowing and drifting reported due to the strong winds. Lima received 7.0 of total snow accumulation. Slide-offs and accidents were reported across the region. A few secondary roads were impassable due to the significant drifting.

Winds really pick up during the day, gusting between 35 and 45 mph during the afternoon and evening hours. Snow accumulations across the county generally ranged between 6 and 8 inches, with significant blowing and drifting reported due to the strong winds. Van Wert received 7.0 of total snow accumulation. Slide-offs and accidents were reported across the region. A few secondary roads were impassable due to the significant drifting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Alberta Clipper brought heavy snow and gusty winds to Lower Michigan January 28th into early January 29th. Snow accumulations generally ranged between 3 and 8 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow overspread around daybreak on January 28th and continued through early January 29th. Some freezing drizzle did mix in during the late afternoon and evening hours. Total snow accumulations across the county ranged between 3 and 5 inches. This in tandem with 30 mph wind gusts created difficult travel conditions. There were numerous school delays and cancellations, along with reports of accidents and slide-offs across the region.

An arctic cold front tracked through eastern New York during the afternoon of the 30th, accompanied by a heavy snow squall. Frigid air poured in behind this front along with strong westerly winds. Wind chills the morning of the 31st fell to 15 to 35 degrees below zero. The wind chills prompted many schools to close or delay opening, and there were several reports of water main breaks due to the cold.||In addition to the frigid temperatures, a heavy band of lake effect snow developed off of Lake Ontario and impacted far northern portions of Herkimer County from the evening of the 30th through the late evening of the 31st. Snowfall amounts of 8 to 12 inches occurred in this band.

Following a moderate to heavy snowfall event on January 19-20, a strong low pressure system tracking through southern Canada ushered in an unseasonably warm and moist airmass on January 24th. Temperatures surged into the 40s to mid-50s. Steady rainfall occurred during much of the 24th as a secondary low pressure system developed over the Mid- Atlantic and tracked into southern New England. One to three inches of rainfall occurred over western Massachusetts. The combination of the rainfall along with the mild temperatures melting some of the snow resulted in isolated poor drainage flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hubbard Avenue was closed at the railroad underpass due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Following a heavy snowfall event on January 19-20 over much of eastern New York, a strong low pressure system tracking through southern Canada ushered in an unseasonably warm and moist airmass on January 24th. Temperatures surged into the 40s to mid-50s. Steady rainfall occurred during much of the 24th as a secondary low pressure system developed over the Mid-Atlantic and tracked into southern New England. One to two inches of rainfall occurred over much of the region, although a few reports of three to four inches were recorded over portions of the southern Adirondacks and the eastern Catskills. New daily rainfall records were set at Albany, Glens Falls, and Poughkeepsie.||The combination of the rainfall along with the mild temperatures melting some of the snow resulted in urban and poor drainage flooding over portions of the region along with minor to moderate river flooding in the Hoosic basin. Some ice jam flooding also occurred. Numerous road closures also occurred due to flooding in Washington County, NY. In addition, seven vessels along the Hudson River near Troy were ripped from their moorings during the early morning of the 25th, likely by a surge of water and ice from upstream. Some of these vessels struck bridges, resulting in bridge closures during the morning rush hour, including the Patroon Island Bridge which carries I-90 over the Hudson.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rathbun Avenue was closed due to flooding along the Mettawee River.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms ahead of an approaching cold front were enhanced by a passing upper level short wave trough axis during the afternoon. Bulk shear within the 0-6 km layer was 46 kts with cool mid level temperatures. Hail and gusty winds were hazards from isolated severe storms.

A low pressure system moved into southeastern Canada on January 30th, with  a cold front crossing through the Mid-Atlantic states. Cold temperatures and strong northwest winds followed behind the front on the night of the 30th and into the morning of the 31st. This was able to produce very low wind chills across much of the state.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The combination of cold temperatures and strong winds produced wind chills as low as -10 degrees.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow developed during the late morning hours of January 12th and continued into the afternoon and early evening. Snow amounts of 2 to 4 inches were common across the county. There were reports of minor accidents and slide-offs across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A dangerous arctic air mass overspread Lower Michigan January 30th into the morning hours of January 31st. Wind chills between 25 and 40 degrees below zero were common.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gusty west winds ushered in a bitterly cold arctic air mass on January 30th into the morning hours of January 31st. The coldest of the air and strongest winds occurred during the morning hours of January 30th when the wind chill value at Hillsdale dropped to 38 degrees below zero. Wind chills through the event generally ranged between 25 and 40 degrees below zero. The coldest air temperature recorded at Hillsdale was 18 degrees below zero on January 30th. Many businesses and schools were closed on both January 30th and January 31st due to this record breaking shot of dangerous cold air.

CZ_NAME: SOUTHERN SANGRE DE CRISTO MOUNTAINS ABOVE 9500 FEET
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system moved slowly east across northern New Mexico on April 13, 2019 and delivered scattered showers and thunderstorms with high terrain snow. Temperatures were cold enough with this system to support snowfall over the Sangre de Cristo Mountains and parts of northeastern New Mexico. Two to five inches of snow fell from near Angel Fire to Las Vegas and Capulin. The heaviest snowfall impacted locations above 9,000 feet west of Las Vegas where up to 18 inches was reported. Impacts were limited with this event as temperatures were too warm to support hazardous travel in most areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Wesner Springs SNOTEL reported 18 inches of snowfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Breezy southwest winds across northern and central New Mexico on April 20, 2019 were enhanced by virga showers moving quickly northeast through the region. The strongest wind gusts occurred in the area from near Farmington to Taos where peak winds near 60 mph were reported. Rainfall amounts from this activity were generally less than five hundredths of an inch.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A virga shower produced a peak wind gust up to 59 mph several miles northwest of Kirtland.

CZ_NAME: GORE AND ELK MOUNTAINS/CENTRAL MOUNTAIN VALLEYS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough dropping south across eastern Colorado brought locally heavy snowfall to the higher mountains in central Colorado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall accumulations from 4 to 8 inches were measured across the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous winter disturbances moved across western Colorado during the month of January which led to wetter than normal conditions and cooler temperatures. As a result, the state of the drought improved across much of the region, most notably in the Four Corners which finally began to break out of the exceptional (D4) drought conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The sliver of extreme (D3) drought conditions along the west-central border of the zone improved two categories to moderate (D1) conditions. The severe (D2) drought across the rest of the area also improved to the moderate category by the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A dangerous arctic air mass overspread northern Indiana late on January 29th through the morning hours of January 31st. Wind chills between 30 and 50 degrees below zero were common.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gusty west winds ushered in a bitterly cold arctic air mass late on January 29th through the morning hours of January 31st. The coldest of the air and strongest winds occurred during the morning hours of January 30th when the wind chill value at Tri-Lakes dropped to 35 degrees below zero. Wind chills through the event generally ranged between 25 and 50 degrees below zero. The coldest air temperature recorded at Tri-Lakes was 16 degrees below zero on January 31st. Many businesses and schools were closed due to this record breaking shot of dangerous cold air.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous winter disturbances moved across western Colorado during the month of January which led to wetter than normal conditions and cooler temperatures. As a result, the state of the drought improved across much of the region, most notably in the Four Corners which finally began to break out of the exceptional (D4) drought conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The sliver of extreme (D3) drought conditions along the southeast border of the zone improved to severe (D2) conditions. The severe drought across the rest of the area improved to the moderate (D1) category by the end of the month.

An arctic cold front tracked through western Massachusetts during the afternoon of the 30th, accompanied by a heavy snow squall. Frigid air poured in behind this front along with strong westerly winds. Wind chills the morning of the 31st fell to 15 to 30 degrees below zero. The wind chills prompted many schools to close or delay opening.

Snow developed along a warm front and ahead of an upper level trough during the morning of the 29th. The snow was initially focused across the southern Adirondacks and Lake George-Saratoga Region during the morning, but spread throughout eastern New York during the afternoon and evening. The highest totals were across the southern Adirondacks, Lake George-Saratoga Region, eastern Catskills, and portions of the Mid-Hudson Valley, where 8 to 12 inches of snow was recorded. Amounts generally ranged from 3 to 8 inches across the rest of eastern New York. The snow resulted in schools being delayed or cancelled the next day along with several traffic accidents.

Strong westerly to northwesterly winds developed during the morning of the 1st behind a cold front. Several reports of wind gusts in the 45 to 55 mph range were recorded, with a few isolated gusts up to 60 mph. The winds brought down trees and wires and took out power to an estimated 25,000 to 30,000 customers. The winds diminished in the late afternoon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure system through the Ohio Valley produced a swath of accumulating snow and strong winds across the Lower Great Lakes region on Saturday, January 19th. Snow totals of 4 to 8 inches and wind gusts to near 40 mph created difficult travel conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to at times heavy snow developed during the morning hours of January 19th and continued through the rest of the day. Winds really picked up during the day, gusting between 30 and 40 mph during the afternoon and early evening hours. Snow accumulations across the county generally ranged between 4 and 5 inches, with significant blowing and drifting reported due to the strong winds. Slide-offs and accidents were reported across the region. A few secondary roads were impassable due to the significant drifting.
