EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved up the eastern seaboard of the United States on January 20th, with cold temperatures and strong northwest winds funneling behind the system from the night of the 20th into the morning of the 21st. This was able to produce very low wind chills across much of the state.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The combination of cold temperatures and strong winds produced wind chills as low as -10 degrees.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough was over the Great Basin during the morning hours and moved over the Rocky Mountains during the day. Upper level disturbances moved over West Texas along the edge of this upper trough. A surface trough was over far West Texas and resulted in an abundance of moisture across the area. The atmosphere quickly became unstable as temperatures warmed up at the surface. A dryline was backed up to the higher terrain of West Texas and southeast New Mexico with very good wind shear and atmospheric rotation in place. During the late evening hours, upper lift increased with the approaching upper trough and the area was in a favorable position for lift with the upper jet stream. A low-level jet stream also moved across the area providing more lift. A Pacific front associated with the upper trough moved east and interacted with the dryline to create additional lift. These conditions resulted in thunderstorms rapidly developing and becoming severe with large hail, strong and damaging winds, tornadoes, and flash flooding across West Texas.

A deepening low pressure system through the Ohio Valley produced a swath of accumulating snow and strong winds across the region on Saturday, January 19th. Snow totals of 4 to 8 inches and wind gusts to near 40 mph created difficult travel conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to at times heavy snow developed during the morning hours of January 19th and continued through the rest of the day. Winds really pick up during the day, gusting between 35 and 45 mph during the afternoon and evening hours. Snow accumulations across the county generally ranged between 5 and 8 inches, with significant blowing and drifting reported due to the strong winds. Napoleon received 7.5 of total snow accumulation. Slide-offs and accidents were reported across the region. A few secondary roads were impassable due to the significant drifting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A dangerous arctic air mass overspread Lower Michigan January 30th into the morning hours of January 31st. Wind chills between 25 and 40 degrees below zero were common.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gusty west winds ushered in a bitterly cold arctic air mass on January 30th into the morning hours of January 31st. The coldest of the air and strongest winds occurred during the morning hours of January 30th when the wind chill value at Three Rivers dropped to 39 degrees below zero. Wind chills through the event generally ranged between 25 and 40 degrees below zero. The coldest air temperature recorded at Three Rivers was 19 degrees below zero on January 31st. Many businesses and schools were closed on both January 30th and January 31st due to this record breaking shot of dangerous cold air. Lake effect snow showers and blowing snow also helped wreak havoc on area roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous winter disturbances moved across western Colorado during the month of January which led to wetter than normal conditions and cooler temperatures. As a result, the state of the drought improved across much of the region, most notably in the Four Corners which finally began to break out of the exceptional (D4) drought conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The small sliver of exceptional (D4) drought conditions over the far southwest portion of the zone improved to extreme (D3) conditions. The extreme drought continued across the rest of the forecast area, though it was trimmed back slightly over the far northwest by the end of the month.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: January ended with extreme (D3) drought conditions across the entirety of the zone after the area of exceptional (D4) conditions over the western portion of the zone improved one category.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Southwest to west winds increased to more than 80 mph over the summits of Mauna Kea and Mauna Loa on the Big Island. No significant injuries or property damage were reported.

A surface trough just east of the island chain, in combination with high pressure north of the state, induced strong north winds across the area. Damages from the winds occurred on the Big Island and Oahu, with one individual injured on Oahu as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tin roof of a building was blown off at the Kona Airport in the leeward part of the Big Island.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A blaze charred about 200 acres of dry brush near Wailea in leeward East Maui. Around 100 people had to evacuate the area, including guests at a luxury hotel. Firefighters struggled for a time with the blaze because of breezy, swirling winds. No injuries were reported, and the cost of any damages was not available. The cause of the fire was not known.
Dry conditions began to increase over parts of the Big Island and Maui in January. The D2 category of severe drought took hold in these areas.
